{[%evp 0,11,19,29,54,50,88,74,71,36,36,36,45,59]} 1. e4 c5 {The Sicilian
Defence has not ceased to fascinate amateurs professionals, and commentators
for at least one century. When evaluating the pros and cons of each individual
system I feel that we need to distinguish between three major categories. We
have what I would call the "traditional" variations, using the word
traditional instead of classical, because there is a system called like that!
Apart from them, we have a few specific systems, leading to slightly different
configurations. In the first category, I would include the Najdorf,
Scheveningen and Classical variations, while the Sveshnikov, the Kalashnikov, and the Paulsen belong to the latter. Finally, we have the Dragon and the
Accelerated Dragon, which looks more like a reversed English opening to me. If
asked to restrict myself to two categories I would include the Dragon into
the group of traditional systems and the Accelerated Dragon (mainly the
Maroczy bind) into the latter. Let us focus on the traditional systems. All of
them have their appeal, but against each of them, White has a system that can
be considered critical. It is not about fashion, but it has been like that for
many decades. Let us review them one by one.} 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
5. Nc3 a6 {This move order was introduced by Tartakower in 1926 and several
players (such as Van den Bosch, Noteboom, Alatortsev) used it repeatedly
before Don Miguel himself played it in a few games starting with the late '40s.
} ({In the classical system, defined by} 5... Nc6 {the bishop's development to
g5 remains the most consistent answer.} 6. Bg5 {Maybe White's attacking chances
are a bit lower than in the Najdorf, but Black, too, is slightly less
flexible. In fact, playing the classical Sicilian is 90% equivalent to playing
the Rauzer attack, since all the other systems are inoffensive, maybe with the
partial exception of the Sozin Attack, with which we deal in this database.} ({
The attempt to play the English attack with} 6. Be3 {runs into} Ng4) (6. Be2 {
and other positional systems (6.g3, 6.f4) can be met with 6...e6 and 6...e5,
of course, but my favourite is} g6 {since the positional Dragon lines are
pleasant for Black.})) ({The same as in the case of the Najdorf system, I feel
that the Scheveningen has an improper denomination. True, it was twice played
by George Salto Fontain in Scheveningen 1923, but prior to that, the much
better-known Rubinstein introduced it in 1922. I can admit that we could not
name all the systems introduced by the great Akiba after him, since the
opening theory would be too monotonous. However, the player who really made this
system look like an opening was Efim Bogoljubov, who intensively and
successfully used it during the '20s and the '30s.} 5... e6 {Bogoljubov
introduced many "modern" ideas, but also had the occasion to understand the
main danger for Black. In 1943, a much younger player continued with the new
move} 6. g4 {and crushed him completely. Bogoljubov never played his system
again after that. Oh, the young player was Keres, of course, and the Keres
Attack has the proper name. Over all these decades after this first game, this
attack has remained the most powerful way of meeting the Scheveningen move
order.}) ({If forced to include the Dragon into the category of traditional
Sicilians, after} 5... g6 {there is only one challenging system once again
baptized after Rauzer.} 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 O-O 8. Qd2 Nc6 9. Bc4 {Abstractly,
this is the absolute main system, leading to a fascinating play. More details are in
my database on the Dragon also published by Modern Chess.} ({However,} 9.
O-O-O {has been fashionable for too long and we could consider it an
alternative to the traditional old move. When I wrote "for too long", I
thought of the English Attack (6.Be3) in the Najdorf and the Scheveningen,
which at some point was more popular than 6.Bg5 and maybe still is, but here
the tendency seems to be more stable.} d5)) 6. Bg5 {This is the absolute main
line, offering White ample attacking chances. There is a wealth of games with
sacrifices and mutual sacrifices, pleasant to replay but maybe a bit scary to
have during a game. Theory will never come to a final conclusion probably, but
in most of the lines, Black is balancing over the precipice.} ({Against the
positional lines, such as} 6. Be2 {, 6.f4 or 6.g3, the usual Najdorf reaction
is} e5 {. Advancing the pawn only to e6 would transpose to the Scheveningen.})
(6. Be3 {is the second most challenging system, especially if Black answers} e5
{. In the ensuing positions with opposite castled, everything depends on tiny
nuances.}) *

