1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 {After making this long review of the traditional Sicilians,
the time has come to explain the purpose of this database. I will never stop
loving the Dragon, but I also feel like playing a traditional Sicilian. In the
past, I have tried all of them, but from the perspective of an experienced
player, my preference goes for the Scheveningen, which is the most flexible of
them. However, I am a bit scared of the Keres Attack. There is a tricky move
order, though.} e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 {This is one of the two Paulsen
system versions.} (4... a6 {may seem more flexible, but by not putting
pressure in the centre, Black allows White better possibilities to stay in
control.} 5. Bd3 {This is the absolute main line. White maintains the
possibility of reaching the Hedgehog with c2-c4, without allowing much of
Black's counterplay.} (5. c4 {is also a bit more challenging than after 4...
Nc6.}) (5. Nc3 {allows Black to switch to the SCheweningen with} d6 {since the
Keres attack can be met in a similar way as in our repertoire below.}) 5... Nf6
6. O-O Qc7 (6... d6 7. c4) 7. Qe2 d6 8. c4) 5. Nc3 {The fact that this is the
most consistent answer is a small success for Black.} (5. c4 Nf6 {does not
offer White the slightest chance for an advantage.}) ({Karpov used to play} 5.
Nb5 d6 6. c4 {reaching the Hedgehog but this implies a huge commitment.} (6.
Bf4 e5 7. Be3 Nf6 {is some sort of Sveshnikov system in an improved version
for Black, since the bishop does not get to g5 in one move.}) 6... Nf6 7. N1c3
a6 8. Na3 (8. Nd4 {is equivalent with wasting two tempi.}) 8... Be7 9. Be2 O-O
10. O-O b6 11. Be3 Bb7 {This is a genuine Hedgehog, but the fact that White
spent two tempi on transferring his knight to the unusual square on a3,
simplifies Black's task.}) 5... d6 {Now is a good moment for transposing to
the Scheveningen.} (5... Qc7 {leads to a genuine Paulsen, even though Black
could later transpose to the Scheveningen anyway. In that case, he will have
committed himself on the way. Here is just an example.} 6. Be2 a6 7. O-O Nf6 8.
Be3 Be7 (8... Bb4 {is the typical Paulsen continuation.}) 9. f4 d6 10. Qe1 O-O
11. Qg3 Nxd4 12. Bxd4 b5 13. a3 Bb7 14. Kh1 Bc6 15. Rae1 Qb7 16. Bd3 {
Combining ...a6 with ...Nc6 and ...Qc7 is possible, but offers White some time
to reach a dangerous attacking setup. I am not aware of the final evaluation
of this position, but I know that the position remains dangerous for Black.}) (
5... a6 6. Nxc6 $5 ({Just for the record,} 6. Be2 {or other developing move
offers Black a choice between switching to the Scheveningen without having the
queen on c7, but with the slightly committal ...a7-a6 and} Nge7 {, a system
designed by Taimanov and similar to our reaction to the Keres attack in the
present repertoire.}) 6... bxc6 7. Bd3 {This is one of the critical white
reactions, since the move ...a7-a6 looks like a waste of time and a weakening
now.}) 6. g4 {This is the first move we need to check, of course.} (6. Be2 {
or 6.g3 can be comfortably met with} Nf6 {The positional Scheveningen systems
with an early ...Nc6 are by no means worse than those based on ...a7-a6 and ...
Qc7 and keeping the knight on b8 for a while. From the abstract point of view
of development, ...Nc6 is more desirable, of course, but Sicilian rules are
very specific.}) (6. Be3 Nf6 {requires a special mention, since it can be
followed by f2-f3, leading to the complicated English Attack or f2-f4, which
is another aggressive system in the Scheweningen}) (6. Bc4 Nf6 {transposes to
the Sozin Attack, about which I wrote a bit in the introduction to the
respective lines.}) 6... Nge7 {This is the main (if not the only) reason why I
chose the Scheveningen via Paulsen move order. After such a committal move
like 6.g4, Black can deviate from the natural development. He does not need to
expose his knight to g4-g5, but can play in the spirit of the Taimanov system
mentioned above.} 7. Be3 a6 {Black plans ...b7-b5, ...Bb7, maybe ...Rc8, too
and only after the white queen moves, ...Nxd4 followed by ...Nc6. If the
knight retreats from d4, there are things to do with the superfluous knight on
e7. The time has come to investigate each system in detail.} *

