1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. c4 {In the systems with 4...a6
instead of 4...Nc6, this early gain of space offers White certain chances to
maintain some control. Since the latter move is more useful for developing
purposes than the former, in our current position, the last move yields Black
easy play, with chances to take over the initiative.} Nf6 {The obvious
reaction.} 6. Nxc6 {Preparing to defend the pawn on e4 with a developing move
without allowing the bin along the e1-a5 diagonal.} (6. f3 {is weakening the
kingside too much, in a moment when White is poorly developed.} Bb4+ 7. Bd2 (7.
Nc3 {transposes below.}) 7... Bc5 8. Nb3 (8. Nxc6 dxc6 9. Nc3 e5 $15) (8. Nc2
Nxe4 $1 9. fxe4 Qh4+ $19 {with similar play as below.}) (8. Bc3 {Dabringhaus,
A-Pick,S (2104) Leverkusen Bayer op 9th 2011 (6) 1-0} Nxd4 9. Bxd4 Nxe4 $17 10.
fxe4 Qh4+ $19 {retrieving the bishop on d4 soon.}) 8... Nxe4 $5 ({The simple} 
8... Be7 9. Nc3 d5 $36 {also causes White problems.}) 9. fxe4 (9. Nxc5 {
is another interesting line.} Nxc5 10. b4 {it may seem that the knights are in
danger. True, Black could return with the knight to e4, and after fxe4, ...Qh4+
would lead to a perpetual, but} Qh4+ $5 {is more ambitious.} 11. g3 Qd4 12. Na3
Qe5+ $5 {The check on d3 also works well.} 13. Kf2 a5 14. bxc5 Qxc5+ 15. Be3
Qxa3 16. c5 {with just some white compensation for the pawns.}) 9... Qh4+ 10.
g3 (10. Ke2 Qxe4+ 11. Be3 Qxe3#) 10... Qxe4+ 11. Qe2 Qxh1 12. Nxc5 Nd4 13. Qe4
(13. Qd3 Nf3+ 14. Kf2 Nxh2 15. Nc3 d5 16. cxd5 Ng4+ 17. Ke1 O-O $17) 13...
Qxe4+ 14. Nxe4 Nc2+ 15. Kd1 Nxa1 16. Bb4 a5 17. Ba3 d5 18. Nd6+ Kd7 19. Nxf7
Rd8 20. Nc3 {The material balance is unusual. Black is two exchanges up but
has to catch up in development.} b6 $3 (20... Re8 $2 21. cxd5 exd5 22. Bb5+ $18
) (20... Rg8 21. Kc1 b6 22. Ne5+ Kd8 23. Bh3 $16) 21. Nxd8 (21. Kc1 Ba6 22.
Nxd8 Kxd8 23. b3 Ra7 24. Kb2 Rf7 25. Bh3 Nxb3 26. axb3 dxc4 27. Bxe6 Rf2+ $19)
21... Kxd8 22. Kc1 Ra7 23. Nb1 Rf7 24. Nd2 Rf2 $19 {White still needs two
tempi to grab the knight and his kingside is in trouble.}) (6. Nc3 {is
examined in Line 2.}) 6... bxc6 7. Bd3 e5 {This is the move I liked during my
teenage and my taste did not change in the meantime. Black prepares for
playing on dark squares.} ({The slightly more popular} 7... d5 $11 {is good
for clear equality.}) 8. O-O ({Preventing ...Bc5 with} 8. Be3 {is simplest met
with} Bb4+ 9. Nd2 (9. Nc3 O-O 10. O-O {transposes to Line 2.}) 9... d6 {
preventing c4-c5.} 10. a3 (10. Qa4 {wins a pawn but exposes the queen.} Rb8 11.
Qxc6+ Bd7 12. Qa6 O-O 13. f3 (13. O-O {alows} Ng4 14. Qxa7 Qe7 15. h3 Ra8 16.
Qb7 Rfb8 {White has to take on either a8 or b8, with insufficient compensation
for the queen, since after} 17. Qd5 {Black has a choice between taking on e3
and d2, and} Nf6 18. Bg5 Nxd5 19. Bxe7 Nxe7 $19) 13... Ne8 14. Qxa7 Bc6 15. Bf2
Nc7 $17) 10... Ba5 ({I would prefer to offer the bishops' exchange on c5:} 
10... Bc5 11. Bxc5 dxc5 {The c-pawns are not really weak. In fact, Black can
dream of installing the knight on d4, while d5 is not accessible to any white
piece.} 12. Nb3 Qb6 {Besides, a2-a3 has weakened the square on b3.} 13. O-O O-O
14. Bc2 Be6 15. Qd3 a5 16. Rab1 Nd7 17. Qc3 f6 18. Rfd1 Rfe8 19. a4 Nf8 20. Qe3
Bxc4 21. Qxc5 Qxc5 22. Nxc5 Rab8 23. Rd6 Ne6 $11 24. Rxc6 $2 Nd4 $19) 11. O-O (
11. b4 Bb6 12. Qe2 Bg4 13. f3 Bxe3 14. Qxe3 Be6 15. Nb3 Qb6 16. c5 dxc5 17.
Nxc5 Nd7 18. Rc1 a5 $11) 11... Ng4 12. c5 Nxe3 13. fxe3 dxc5 14. Nb3 Bb6 $13 {
Pineiro,D (2180)-Bassan,R (2337) Buenos Aires Bolivar op 4th 2011 (5) 0-1})
8... Bc5 9. Nc3 (9. Nd2 {deserves mentioning, even though it is not dangerous.}
a5 10. Nb3 Be7 11. a4 O-O (11... d6 12. c5 d5 $11) 12. c5 d5 13. cxd6 Qxd6 {
The mutual queenside weaknesses compensate for each other.} 14. Be3 Ng4 15. Bc5
Qh6 16. h3 Bxc5 17. Nxc5 Ne3 18. fxe3 Qxe3+ 19. Kh2 Qxc5 20. Rc1 Qb6 21. Bc4
Ra7 22. Qd6 Qc7 23. Qc5 Ba6 24. Bb5 Rc8 25. Rfd1 g6 26. Bxc6 {Zlatic,M (2463)
-Perunovic,M (2580) SRB-ch Kragujevac 2009 (7) 0-1} Kg7 27. Rc3 Qe7 28. Qb6 Qc7
$11) 9... d6 10. h3 ({At the age of 18, I won a game continuing with} 10. Ne2
$6 O-O 11. Qa4 $2 Ng4 $19 {Many years (or decades) later I happened to meet
with my opponent, who had stopped playing in the meanwhile. He knew me since I
was a child, but indicated this game as the moment when he felt that I was
going to become a strong player. In those years, prodigies were not
flourishing as nowadays. True, there had been this guy, Fischer, who became a
grandmaster and World title candidate at the age of 15, but that was an
isolated case.} 12. g3 Nxf2 13. b4 (13. Rxf2 Qf6 $19) 13... Nxd3+ 14. bxc5 Nxc5
15. Qc2 Bh3 16. Rf2 Qd7 17. Ba3 f5 18. Bxc5 dxc5 19. Rd1 Qe6 20. exf5 Bxf5 21.
Qc3 Bh3 {Velea Panaite-Marin Mihail, Eforie Nord 1983. Apart from the small
story written above, I have included this game because it emanates the same
attacking spirit as the main line below.}) 10... g5 $5 {After Kramnik's ...Rg8
against Aronian at his last Candidates, such a move should not surprise
anymore.} (10... O-O $11) (10... Be6 $11) 11. Kh1 $2 (11. g3 $2 Bxh3 (11... Qd7
12. Bxg5 Qxh3 13. Qf3 Rg8 $19) 12. Re1 (12. Bxg5 Rg8 13. Bh4 Rg4 14. Qf3 Rxh4
15. gxh4 Bg4 16. Qg2 Qd7 17. Kh2 Ke7 18. f3 Rg8 19. Rae1 Rg6 $19) 12... Ng4 13.
Be3 Nxe3 14. fxe3 {Gulacsi,D (1822)-Nemeth,Z (2194) Puspokladany Arnoth
Memorial 15th 2022 (8) 0-1} h5 $19) (11. Bxg5 $2 Rg8 12. Bxf6 (12. Bh4 Bxh3 $19
) (12. h4 h6 13. Bxh6 Ng4 14. Bg5 Rxg5 15. hxg5 Qxg5 16. Qf3 Ke7 17. g3 Be6 18.
Kg2 Rh8 19. Rh1 Nxf2 20. Rxh8 Bg4 21. Qxf2 Bxf2 22. Kxf2 Qf6+ $1 $19) 12...
Qxf6 13. Kh1 Ke7 (13... Qh6 14. Qf3 Bg4 $6 15. Qg3 Rg6 16. Qh2 $15 Qd2 17. f4
Qxd3 18. hxg4 $132) (13... Rb8 $5 {is a cunning way of improving over the
variation above.} 14. Rb1 (14. Na4 Bd4 $19) 14... Qh6 15. Qf3 Bg4 16. Qg3 Rg6
17. Qh2 Qd2 $19 18. f4 Qxd3 19. hxg4 Rxb2 $1 $19 {This is the difference.} 20.
Qh3 Be3 21. Rbe1 exf4) 14. Be2 (14. Qh5 Rg6 $17) 14... Qg5 (14... Qh4 15. Qd3)
15. g4 (15. Bf3 Qh4) 15... h5 16. f3 Be6 17. Kg2 Rh8 18. Rh1 Rag8 $17 {
Hernandez Moya,Y (2227)-Pina Vega,S (2279) CUB-ch (Women) 2014 (4) 1/2-1/2}) (
11. Be2 $5 $146 Rg8 12. Qd3 g4 13. h4 $1 (13. hxg4 $2 Nxg4 14. Bxg4 Bxg4 $19
15. Be3 (15. Qg3 h5) 15... Bf3 16. Bg5 Bxg2 17. Bxd8 Bxe4+) 13... g3 $5 14. Be3
Nd7 15. fxg3 Rxg3 16. Bf3 Qxh4 17. Bxc5 Rh3 18. gxh3 Qg3+ 19. Kh1 Qxh3+ $11) (
11. Ne2 $5 $146 Rg8 $5 (11... g4 12. h4 g3 13. Nxg3 Rg8 14. Nf5 Bxf5 15. exf5
Ng4 16. Bg5 Rxg5 17. hxg5 Qxg5 18. Be2 h5 $44) 12. b4 (12. Ng3 g4 13. h4 Nh5
