{[%evp 0,38,39,38,61,56,49,26,28,26,26,35,40,10,-3,-10,-10,-44,-31,-50,3,-20,
-5,-7,4,-4,-9,-16,-14,-56,-16,-51,-50,-43,-27,-32,-17,-41,17,36,21]} 1. e4 c5
2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nb5 {In each Paulsen version, there are
two continuations that try to take advantage of the specific move order.
After 4...a6, we have the straightforward 5.c4 and the more refined 5.Bd3,
usually followed by c2-c4 in the near future. With our move order, 5.c4 is
completely inoffensive, as we will see, but the system examined in this and
the next lines are the equivalent of 5.Bd3 after 4...a6. To me, the main merit
of the move order based on 4...Nc6 is that 5.Nb5 is by far less dangerous than
5.Bd3 in the other line.} d6 6. c4 {White chooses the Hedgehog setup. While
this remains playable for Black with other move orders, in our case, the time
wasted by the white knight strongly restricts his chances to retain an
advantage.} (6. Bf4 {is examined in Lines 15 to 17.}) 6... Nf6 7. N5c3 {
I feel that this move is a small concession since Black can spare the move ...
a7-a6.} ({The main continuation is} 7. N1c3 {, to be examined in Lines 6 to 14.
}) 7... Be7 8. g3 {White is heading for some sort of English Hedgehog.} (8. g4
$6 {The Keres setup does not work here, since White has wasted too much time
with his previous queenside play.} h6 ({In fact, Black can even ignore the
attack with} 8... O-O 9. g5 Nd7 10. h4 f5 $17) 9. Rg1 a6 10. Be3 (10. h4 Nh7
$17 11. h5 O-O 12. Be3 Bg5 $17) 10... g5 $5 {Ensuring the knight's stability
on e5.} 11. Be2 Ne5 12. Nd2 Bd7 13. Qb3 Bc6 14. O-O-O Ng6 15. Bf3 $6 (15. Kb1
Nd7 $11) 15... Nd7 16. Qc2 Nde5 17. Be2 Rc8 (17... b5 $17) 18. Kb1 Qc7 19. Na4
Nd7 20. Qb3 Nc5 21. Nxc5 dxc5 22. Qc3 f6 (22... O-O $5 $19) 23. h3 Kf7 24. Bd3
Rhd8 $17 {Cardoso,R-Schmidt,W Olot 1975 (5) 1/2-1/2}) (8. Be3 O-O 9. g4 $2 {
This is an even worse version of the Keres setup.} (9. Be2 {transposes to Line
5.}) 9... d5 $1 {With such an advance in development, Black can answer an
intended attack on the wing with a pawn break in the centre.} 10. g5 (10. exd5
exd5 11. cxd5 Nxg4 $5 {Not the only winning move, but an elegant one.} 12. dxc6
Nxe3 13. Qxd8 Rxd8 14. fxe3 Bh4+ 15. Ke2 Bg4#) 10... d4 11. gxf6 Bxf6 $19) (8.
Be2 {is examined in Line 5.}) 8... a6 9. Bg2 Rb8 {Since the bishop has
abandoned the f1-a6 diagonal, Black threatens ...b7-b5.} 10. Na3 (10. a4 {
weakens the b4-square. Black can always think of blocking the queenside with..
.a6-a5, thus ensuring a stable square for the knight on c5. This could also
happen if White plays b2-b4.} O-O 11. O-O Nd7 12. Na3 b6 13. Be3 Bb7 14. Rc1 ({
With hindsight, the less natural} 14. Rb1 {makes sense, but is hardly
challenging.} Rc8 15. Qe2 Qc7 16. Rfd1 Nce5 17. Rbc1 Qb8 18. f4 Nc6 19. Rb1
Rfd8 20. b4 Bf6 21. Bd2 a5 $11 22. b5 $2 Nb4 23. Be1 Nc5 $17) 14... Rc8 (14...
Nc5 15. b3 Bf6 {is also possible.}) 15. f4 Nc5 16. Rb1 (16. Qe2 Bf6 17. Rfd1
Qc7 $15 {and White faces certain problems of mobility. Among others, he needs
to permanently count with ...Bxc3 followed by ...Nxa4.}) 16... Nb4 $11) 10...
O-O 11. O-O Bd7 12. Be3 (12. Qe2 {allows} b5 $1 13. cxb5 Nd4 $1 14. Qd3 (14.
Qd1 Nxb5 {Smikovski,I (2545)-Uskova,F (2310) RUS-Cup3 Omsk 1996 (7) 1/2-1/2})
14... Nxb5 15. Ncxb5 axb5 16. Bf4 e5 17. Bd2 Qb6 18. Nc2 Be6 (18... b4 19. Rfd1
b3 $11) 19. b3 Rfc8 20. Rac1 {Mergard,H (2165)-Giobbi,C (2258) W-ch WS/M/264
email 2010 1/2-1/2} Qa7 21. Nb4 Bd7 $11) 12... Qa5 13. Bd2 Qc7 14. Rc1 Ne5 15.
Qe2 Rfc8 ({Another possible regrouping is} 15... Rbc8 16. Rfd1 Rfe8 17. Be3 h5
18. h3 Ng6 19. Bg5 (19. f4 {Threatening c4-c5 followed by e4-e5, with
initiative.} b6 $11 {followed by ...Bf8, with a flexible position.}) 19... h4
20. gxh4 Qd8 $44) 16. Rfd1 (16. b3 d5 $132) 16... Be8 17. Kh1 h5 (17... Qb6 $2
{should have caused Black to lose coordination.} 18. f4 Neg4 19. Be1 Qe3 {
Leko,P (2465)-Van Mil,J (2435) Budapest FS04 GM 1993 (9) 1/2-1/2} 20. Qf1 $16)
(17... Nxc4 $5 {is playable, leading to a complicated fight with balanced
chances.} 18. Ncb1 d5 19. b3 Bxa3 20. Nxa3 Qe7 $13 21. Nxc4 (21. bxc4 Qxa3 22.
exd5 Ba4 23. Re1 exd5 24. Bf4 Re8 25. Qd2 Rxe1+ 26. Rxe1 Rc8 27. cxd5 Rc2 $132)
21... dxc4 22. Rxc4 Bb5 23. Rxc8+ Rxc8 24. Qe3 Qa3 25. e5 Nd5 26. Bxd5 exd5 27.
e6 Qe7 28. exf7+ Qxf7 $11) 18. h3 Ng6 19. f4 b6 $11 {With a similar position
as above, though with a different black regrouping.} *

