2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nb5 d6 6. c4 Nf6 7. N1c3 {The main move,
forcing Black to play his next move due to the threat Bf4.} a6 8. Nd4 {White
tries to reach a "normal" hedgeho9g, with his knight on d4. The time lost in
the opening will yield Black good play, though.} ({The absolute main line of
the whole system is} 8. Na3 {, examined in Lines 7 to 14.}) 8... Be7 9. Be2 O-O
10. O-O Bd7 {Black prepares his queenside counterplay, based on ...Nxd4
followed by ...b7-b5.} (10... d5 {is entirely possible, though.} 11. cxd5 exd5
12. exd5 Nxd5 13. Nxc6 bxc6 14. Bd2 (14. Nxd5 cxd5 15. Be3 Bf5 $146 16. Bf3 Bf6
17. Bd4 Be4 $11) 14... Be6 15. Na4 a5 {Black's central activity compensates
for the structural problems. I must confess that I prefer the main line plan
slightly, be it for mere aesthetical reasons.} 16. Bf3 Rb8 17. b3 (17. Rc1 Nb4
$11) 17... Bd6 (17... Nb4 $11) 18. Rc1 Nb4 19. Bxb4 Rxb4 20. g3 (20. Bxc6 Rd4
$1 21. Qc2 Rd2 $36) (20. Rxc6 Rd4 21. Qa1 Be5 22. Re1 Qb8 23. g3 Rxa4 24. Rxe5
Rxa2 $11) 20... Qf6 (20... c5 21. Nxc5 Bxc5 22. Rxc5 a4 23. bxa4 Rd4 {Shen, Y 
(2450)-Cramling, P (2550) CHN-chT 4th China 2008 (16) 0-1 Black is struggling a
bit, but should count on reaching a draw. In the game, she eventually won!})
21. Qxd6 Qxf3 22. Rc3 Qf6 23. Qxc6 h6 $44) 11. Be3 (11. Nc2 {prevents ...Nxd4,
but consumes a developing tempo. Had Black played ...Bd7 instead of ...b7-b6
in Line 7, White would not have removed the knight from a3, transposing to our
current position, since this weakens the control over b5.} Qc7 12. Ne3 (12. Be3
Ne5 {makes 11.Nc2 look like a mere waste of time.} 13. Na3 {More or less
forced, since 11.b3 allows 11...b5.} d5 14. exd5 Bxa3 15. bxa3 Nxc4 $11) (12.
Bf4 Ne5 $5 $146 13. Rc1 b5 14. cxb5 axb5 $11) (12. f4 Na5 13. b3 b5 $15) (12.
b3 b5 13. cxb5 Na7 14. Bb2 Nxb5 15. Nxb5 axb5 16. Bd3 Qb7 17. Qe2 b4 18. Rfe1
Rfc8 $15 {Pelitov,D-Liebert,H Albena-05 1973 (6) 1-0}) 12... Rfd8 13. Kh1 (13.
a4 Nb4 14. b3 Bc6 {[%cal Gd6d5]} 15. Bf3 a5 16. Qe2 Nd7 17. Ncd5 exd5 18. cxd5
Nc5 19. dxc6 bxc6 $11 {with a good blockade on dark squares.}) 13... Bf8 14. f4
b5 $5 15. cxb5 axb5 16. Nxb5 Qb8 17. Nc3 d5 $1 {Black has carried out both
typical breaks.} 18. exd5 Nb4 {Due to White's delay in development and his
vulnerable kingside, Black has full compensation for the pawn.}) 11... Nxd4 12.
Qxd4 (12. Bxd4 b5 $11) 12... Qb8 13. a4 a5 {AFter the exchange of one knight,
this is a reliable plan.} 14. Rfd1 (14. Bg5 Bc6 15. b3 Rd8 16. Rad1 {
Chepukaitis,G (2415)-Shaposhnikov,E (2474) St Petersburg-ch 1999 (9) 0-1} h6
17. Bh4 Qa7 18. Qxa7 Rxa7 $11) (14. Qd2 Bc6 15. Bd3 Nd7 16. Bc2 Bf6 {The
bishop has to merge onto this diagonal, of course.} (16... Nc5 {, hoping to
play ...Bf6 without losing the d6-pawn, is met with} 17. Bd4 $14 {With the
knight on d7, this move could always be answered with ...Bf6.}) 17. Rfd1 Rd8
18. Qxd6 (18. Nd5 exd5 19. exd5 Ne5 20. dxc6 bxc6 $11) (18. Rac1 Nc5 19. f3 Rd7
20. b3 b6 $11) 18... Qxd6 19. Rxd6 Ne5 $11 {Due to Black's minor pieces'
activity, White cannot keep his extra pawn.}) 14... Bc6 15. f3 Rd8 16. Nb5 {
Trying to prevent ...Nd7.} (16. Qb6 Nd7 17. Qb3 Nc5 18. Qc2 b6 19. Rd2 Bf6 $11
{Berdugo Guihur,J (1865)-Marichal Gonzalez,A (2281) Maicao op 3rd 2014 (2) 0-1}
) (16. Kh1 d5 {This is possible, but play is more complicated than Black might
have thought.} ({I would prefer the calm} 16... Nd7 $11 {followed by the
familiar regrouping.}) 17. cxd5 exd5 18. e5 Nd7 19. Nxd5 (19. f4 Nc5 20. Rab1
Ne6 21. Qd2 d4 $19) 19... Bc5 (19... Bxd5 20. Qxd5 Nc5 21. Qc4 Qxe5 $11) 20.
