{[%evp 0,36,21,39,43,43,79,51,40,30,50,50,41,3,0,11,20,-17,-3,0,1,1,7,2,13,-24,
40,40,58,9,9,12,9,-43,-43,-44,-3,-3,-27]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4
Nc6 5. Nb5 d6 6. c4 Nf6 7. N1c3 a6 8. Na3 {This leads to the main tabiya of
this system. In his days, it used to be Karpov's main weapon against the 4...
Nc6 Paulsen.} Be7 9. Be2 O-O 10. O-O b6 11. Be3 Bb7 {This is the old
continuation, which I had in my repertoire more than three decades ago. I
still consider it the most flexible. Black continues developing before
deciding what to do with his queen's knight.} ({Introduced in 1968 by Kurajica,
} 11... Ne5 {was used by the young Kasparov and Polugaevsky starting in 1979.
This caused it to become the main continuation. The main idea is to avoid the
lines with 12.Qb3, examined below.} 12. f3 (12. f4 Ned7 13. Bf3 Bb7 $13 {
Tseshkovsky,V (2560)-Kasparov,G URS-ch47 Final 1979 (9) 1/2-1/2}) 12... Bb7 13.
Qe1 Re8 14. Qf2 Ned7 {Tal, M (2705)-Polugaevsky, L (2635) Candidates qf
Polugaevsky-Tal +3-0=5 1980 (8) 1/2-1/2 While there is nothing wrong with this
line, I cannot avoid the feeling that White gets a bit more freedom of action
than in the old variation.}) 12. Qb3 ({For} 12. Qd2 {see Line 9.}) (12. f4 {
is examined in Line 10.}) (12. Rc1 {is the subject of Line 11.}) (12. f3 {
is the second most popular move after 12.Qb3 and we will deal with it in Line
12.}) 12... Ne5 $1 {This move was introduced in 2015. It maintains Black's
flexibility and invites White to justify his somewhat unusual queen's
development.} ({Earlier,} 12... Nd7 {was considered to be forced.} 13. Rad1 Nc5
14. Qc2 (14. Bxc5 $2 bxc5 $17 15. Qxb7 $2 Na5 $19) 14... Qc7 {Black has
parried the queenside threats and even seems to have gained a tempo. In fact,
with the knight on c5, he cannot think of ...d6-d5 already, while the play on
dark squares is not likely to yield him equality.}) ({In his first match
against Karpov, Kasparov tried the new move} 12... Na5 {, which was
unanimously criticized, due to the challenger's quick loss. In fact, the move
seems to be playable.} 13. Qxb6 Nxe4 14. Nxe4 Bxe4 15. Qxd8 Bxd8 16. Rad1 ({
I may be wrong, but I seem to remember having read that Kasparov's team only
analyzed} 16. Rfd1 {, when after} Bf6 {Black is obviously fine.}) 16... Bf6 $1
$146 {This is the only move with which Black can hang on. True, it is a bit
speculative, which is the reason why I did not recommend it as our repertoire
choice.} (16... Be7 17. Nb1 Rfc8 18. b3 Bb7 19. Nc3 $16 {Nordstrom, F (2184)
-Westerinen,H (2410) Gausdal Byggern Masters 2005 (5) 0-1}) ({Kasparov played} 
16... d5 17. f3 Bf5 18. cxd5 exd5 19. Rxd5 Be6 20. Rd6 Bxa2 21. Rxa6 Rb8 22.
Bc5 Re8 23. Bb5 Re6 24. b4 $14 {Karpov,A (2700)-Kasparov,G (2710)
World-ch30-KK1 Karpov-Kasparov +5-3=40 1984 (3) 1-0 White has got massive
domination, typical for Karpov. Black went on losing quickly.} {Instead of
retreating with the knight to b7, he could have stayed in the game with} Nb3
25. Rxe6 fxe6 26. Be3 Be7 27. Bc4 Bxb4 28. Bxe6+ Kf8 {with good drawing
chances.}) 17. b3 (17. Rd2 Rfc8 18. Bf4 Nb7 19. f3 Bg6 $11 {The black bishops'
activity compensates for White's space advantage and the knight on a3 faces
problems returning in the game.}) (17. Bd4 {allows} Be7 $1 {since after} 18.
Nb1 Rfc8 19. b3 d5 {the d5-pawn will not be hanging after f2-f3.}) 17... Nc6
18. f3 (18. Rxd6 Be7 19. c5 Bxd6 20. cxd6 Nb4 $13 {with just good white
compensation for the exchange.}) 18... Bb2 19. Nb1 Bxb1 20. Rxb1 Ba3 $11 {
For instance} 21. f4 a5 22. Bf3 Ra6 23. f5 Bc5 $11) 13. Bxb6 {This is the
first move that needs testing. White wins a pawn with gain of time, not giving
Black the time to take on e4 yet.} (13. f4 {allows Black to rgroup
harmoniously with} Ned7 {defending the pawn on b6. The queen is obviously
misplaced on b3. Since White would need to relocate it soon, we can evaluate
that Black is at least one tempo up with respect to the line with 11...Ne5 12.
f4 Ned7. Why did I say "at least" one tempo? The reason is that c2 is not the
best square for the queen, since it would be under the black rook's indirect
pressure along the c-file.} 14. Bf3 Qc7 15. Rfe1 Rac8 16. Rad1 Rfe8 17. Bf2 Qb8
18. Nab1 Bc6 19. a4 {Nitin,S (2395)-Ganguly,S (2636) IND-chT 39th 2019 (8.1) 1/
2-1/2} Nc5 20. Qc2 d5 (20... e5 $5 21. f5 b5 $11) 21. cxd5 exd5 22. e5 (22.
exd5 Bd7 23. Qd2 Bd6 {Black has great compensation for the pawn. White's
structure is weak and the pawn on a4 is hard to defend.}) 22... Nfe4 $11) (13.
Qxb6 Qxb6 14. Bxb6 Nxe4 15. Nxe4 Bxe4 $15 {Jakubiec,A (2526)-Jurcik,M (2510)
CZE-chT 0910 2009 (2.2) 1/2-1/2}) (13. f3 {is examined in Line 8.}) 13... Qd7
$1 {Connecting the rooks and preparing the next move.} 14. f3 {The most solid
way of defending e4.} (14. Bd4 Nxe4 15. Nxe4 Bxe4 $11) (14. Qc2 Qc6 15. Bd4
Nxe4 16. Nxe4 Qxe4 17. Qxe4 Bxe4 18. f3 Bg6 $15 {Guliev,L (2367)-Ozalp,B (2141)
Corum op 2016 (7) 1-0 This is a greatly improved version of the position in
Karpov-Kasparov. Black is better regrouped and the knight on a3 is suffering.})
(14. f4 {mainly weakens the e4-square.} Ng6 15. Bd3 (15. Qc2 Qc6 16. Be3 Nxe4
17. Bf3 f5 $11) (15. Bf3 $2 Nxf4 $17) 15... Rab8 $1 {Unlike in the main line,
it is this rook that belongs to this square.} (15... Rfb8 $2 16. Qc2 $13 Bxe4
$2 17. Bxe4 $18 {and the rook on a8 is hanging.}) 16. Ba7 (16. Qc2 Bxe4 $17)
16... Bxe4 17. Bxb8 Bxd3 18. Rf3 Ne4 $1 ({Even stronger than} 18... Bf5 $17 {
Nowak, K (2313)-Kozak, A (2157) Rubinstein Memorial-A 54th 2018 (6) 1/2-1/2 ,
when White cannot bring his bishop back into the game.}) 19. Rxd3 (19. Nxe4
Bxe4 20. Rf2 d5 $19) 19... Nc5 20. Qc2 Nxd3 $19) 14... Rfb8 $1 {White has
problems evacuating the bishop.} 15. Rad1 ({The untested} 15. Nd1 $1 $146 {
is the only way to keep the game equal.} Qc8 (15... d5 16. cxd5 exd5 17. Bd4
Bc8 18. Qe3 Nc6 $44) 16. Qe3 Ned7 17. Ba5 (17. Bd4 e5 18. Bc3 d5 $15) 17... d5
18. Kh1 dxe4 19. f4 Nc5 $13) 15... Qc8 16. Bd4 (16. Nab1 $2 {Kazarian,A (2248)
-Guramishvili,S (2365) Hoogeveen m2 2015 (4) 0-1} Bc6 17. a4 a5 $19) 16... Bxe4
17. Qa4 Bc6 18. Qc2 {[%cal Gc4c5]} Ng6 $15 *

