{[%evp 0,38,28,18,46,40,40,22,22,36,26,14,17,7,15,17,17,-11,3,5,4,4,13,15,13,
22,32,1,75,75,12,12,0,0,0,-3,-3,0,0,-63,-63]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4.
Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nb5 d6 6. c4 Nf6 7. N1c3 a6 8. Na3 Be7 9. Be2 O-O 10. O-O b6 11.
Be3 Bb7 12. Qb3 Ne5 13. f3 {This solid move does not justify the early
incursion to b3.} Ned7 {Black has carried out the regrouping advocated by
Kasparov and Polugaevsky, with the difference that the white queen does not
have much to do on b3.} 14. Rfd1 Qc7 15. Rac1 Rac8 16. Kh1 (16. Bf1 {allows} g5
$5 {threatening ...g5-g4, with good counterplay, since} 17. Bxg5 {loses to}
Qc5+ $19 {More about this plan in later lines.}) 16... Rfe8 {After f2-f3, this
is a move Black plays almost automatically. In view of the potential threat ...
d6-d5, White's bishops are hanging slightly. I have selected a series of games
illustrating the possible plans.} 17. Nab1 (17. Bf1 g5 $5 $146 ({The neutral} 
17... Qb8 {is also possible, of course.} 18. Bg1 h6 19. Nab1 Bc6 20. a3 a5 21.
Nd2 Nc5 22. Qa2 a4 23. b4 axb3 24. Nxb3 Nxb3 25. Qxb3 Nd7 26. Rb1 Qa8 27. Nb5
Nc5 28. Qa2 Red8 29. Nd4 Ba4 $11 {Magem Badals,J (2500)-Almasi,Z (2668)
ESP-chT Honor Gp2 2008 (4) 1/2-1/2}) 18. Bxg5 $6 (18. h3 Nh5 19. Bf2 Bf6 20.
Nc2 Be5 $132) 18... Ng4 $1 19. Bxe7 (19. fxg4 Bxg5 20. Ra1 Nf6 21. h3 Bxe4 $19)
19... Nf2+ 20. Kg1 Qc5 21. h4 Nxd1+ 22. Kh2 Nxc3 $19) 17... h5 {Another
typical way of gaining kingside space.} ({With the bishop on e2,} 17... g5 $6 {
is premature.} 18. Qc2 $14 g4 $6 19. fxg4 Ne5 20. h3 Nxc4 21. Bxc4 Qxc4 22. Nd2
Qc7 23. Qd3 $16) 18. Bf1 (18. a3 Qb8 19. Bf2 h4 $15 20. Bxh4 (20. Bf1 h3 21. g3
g5 $15) ({In the event of} 20. h3 {, apart from the immediate 20...Nh5-/+,
Black has} d5 21. exd5 exd5 22. cxd5 Qe5 {with an almost decisive attack, for
instance} 23. Bg1 Bd6 24. Nd2 Nh5 25. Nf1 Rxc3 $19) 20... Nc5 21. Qa2 (21. Qc2
Nfxe4 $15 22. Nxe4 $6 Bxe4 {This is the difference with the queen on c2.} 23.
fxe4 Bxh4 $17) 21... Nfxe4 22. Nxe4 Nxe4 23. Bxe7 (23. Be1 Nf6 24. Nc3 d5 $15)
23... Nf2+ 24. Kg1 Nxd1 25. Bg5 d5 26. Bxd1 Qe5 {White has won material, but
his coordination is very poor.} 27. Bd2 dxc4 28. Rxc4 $2 (28. Bc2 Qd4+ 29. Kf1
Red8 $15) 28... Bd5 29. Rxc8 Rxc8 30. b3 Rc1 $1 31. Nc3 (31. Bxc1 Qe1#) 31...
Qd4+ 32. Kf1 Bxb3 $1 33. Qxb3 Qxd2 34. Qxb6 Rxc3 {Sandipan,C (2555)-Nisipeanu,
L (2686) Pune 2004 (5) 0-1 A beautiful attacking game by Nisipeanu.}) (18. Bf2
Qb8 19. Na4 (19. Bf1 Bc6 {Getting ready for ...b6-b5 if the occasion arises.}
20. Nd2 h4 $5 21. Bxh4 Ng4 22. Bg3 Ne3 23. Re1 Nc5 24. Qa3 Bg5 25. f4 Nxf1 26.
Rxf1 Bf6 $44) 19... Nc5 20. Nxc5 bxc5 {This structure is comfortable for Black,
who controls the weak square on d4. The following regrouping is typical for
this type of position.} 21. Bg3 Nd7 22. h3 h4 23. Bh2 Ne5 24. Qe3 Nc6 25. Nc3
Nd4 26. Bf1 Bc6 27. Rd2 Qb7 28. Bd3 a5 $11 {Kabisch,T (2330)-Jaracz,P (2492)
Bayern-chI Bank Hofmann 9th 2005 (8) 0-1}) 18... h4 19. Nd2 Nc5 20. Qc2 d5 $5
$11 {Black does not have reasons to refrain from the central break, since he
is perfectly coordinated.} ({In the event of} 20... h3 21. g4 d5 22. g5 d4 23.
Bxd4 Nh5 24. Be3 Red8 {Black should have reasonable compensation for the pawn.}
) 21. b4 (21. cxd5 exd5 22. exd5 Nxd5 23. Nxd5 Bxd5 24. b4 Qe5 25. Bg1 Ne6 26.
Qxc8 Rxc8 27. Rxc8+ Kh7 $15) 21... Ncd7 22. Qb3 (22. exd5 Bxb4) (22. cxd5 exd5
23. Qb3 Qe5 24. f4 Qh5 $15 25. e5 $6 d4 $1 26. Bxd4 h3 $1 27. exf6 Bxf6 28.
Bxf6 Nxf6 {Black has a decisive attack already, for instance.} 29. Kg1 hxg2 30.
Bxg2 Bxg2 31. Kxg2 Rxc3 32. Qxc3 Re2+ $19 {The rook is well placed on e8 even
without white bishops on e2 and e3.}) 22... dxe4 23. Ndxe4 Nxe4 24. Nxe4 h3 25.
g3 Ne5 26. Bf4 Bxe4 (26... g5 27. Bxe5 Qxe5 28. Bxh3 f5 29. Nf2 Qe2 30. Bg2
Red8 $36) 27. fxe4 Qc6 28. Re1 Ng4 29. Qf3 f5 30. Bxh3 Bxb4 31. Rf1 Bc5 32.
Rce1 Bb4 33. Rc1 Bc5 $13 {Nolte,R (2396)-Rahman,Z (2522) Kuala Lumpur op 4th
2007 (4) 1/2-1/2} *

