{[%evp 0,44,21,36,43,43,67,50,41,41,41,41,41,11,18,20,13,-8,0,0,7,7,1,19,21,
-17,-2,5,33,33,33,33,72,66,50,37,37,-1,-1,-13,-14,24,43,18,36,-10,75]} 1. e4 c5
2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nb5 d6 6. c4 Nf6 7. N1c3 a6 8. Na3 Be7 9.
Be2 O-O 10. O-O b6 11. Be3 Bb7 12. Qd2 {This is the most natural move,
connecting the rooks and preparing to complete the development by centralizing
them. One of the merits of Black's move order is that after such a natural
continuation, he can equalize at once.} Ne5 {There are two reasons why this
knight jump is more effective than one move earlier. In Line 10, the white
queen loses a tempo, and besides, the square on g4 is not sufficiently defended
already.} 13. f3 (13. f4 $6 {is an invitation to troubles.} Neg4 $1 {Not
available with the queen on d1.} 14. Kh1 (14. Bxg4 Nxg4 $17) (14. Bd4 $2 e5 15.
Bf2 Nxf2 16. Rxf2 Nxe4 $19) 14... Nxe3 15. Qxe3 Re8 16. Rad1 Qc7 17. Nc2 Bf8
$15 {Followed by ...g7-g6 and ...Bg7. Due to his potentially strong
dark-squared bishop, the future is promising for Black.}) (13. Qd4 {is
examined in Line 10.}) 13... d5 {The most straightforward continuation.} ({
There is nothing wrong with the slower} 13... Qc7 14. Rac1 Rac8 15. Rfd1 Rfe8
$11 {, but this is already more typical for the move order based on 11...Ne5.})
14. cxd5 exd5 15. exd5 b5 $5 {As we can see later from the game
Karpov-Andersson, mentioned in the comments to Line 14, that the gambit spirit has been
typical for this structure for a long time.} (15... Nxd5 {leads to clear
equality and a probable draw.} 16. Nxd5 Bxd5 17. Rfd1 Be6 18. Qxd8 {Browne,
W-Byrne, R San Juan 1969 (3) 1/2-1/2}) 16. Rfd1 {Threatening d5-d6.} ({
Optically,} 16. Rad1 {looks more appealing, but it was played only once.} Bd6 (
16... Re8 {with similar play as below is also possible. In some lines, the
pawn on a2 could be hanging with the queen's rook on d1.}) 17. Nc2 ({In the
main line, the knight jump} 17. Ne4 {is simply wrong, but here it is playable.
Black can take on d5 with the knight, with comfortable play, or else go for}
Nxe4 18. fxe4 Qh4 19. Rf4 Qe7 {Threatening to retrieve the pawn with ...Ng6.}
20. Rff1 Qh4 21. Bf4 {Unlike in the similar line with the alternate rooks'
display, the bishop is well-defended now.} f5 22. exf5 Rxf5 23. Bg3 Rxf1+ 24.
Bxf1 Qf6 25. Nc2 Rd8 26. Ne3 Bc5 27. Bf2 Qf4 $44 {White has managed to keep
his extra pawn, but probably not for long. Black's activity compensates for
the small material investment.}) 17... Re8 18. a3 Qc7 19. f4 Ned7 20. g3 Rad8 {
Black is perfectly regrouped and White's position is a bit weak. The game
below illustrates the possible plans.} 21. Bf3 Nb6 22. Bxb6 Qxb6+ 23. Kg2 a5
24. Rfe1 Rxe1 25. Rxe1 b4 26. axb4 axb4 27. Ne4 b3 (27... Nxe4 {[%cal Gb4b3,
Gd6b4]} 28. Rxe4 Bf8 29. Nxb4 Qb5 $11 30. Rd4 $6 Bc5 31. Re4 f5 {wins the
exchange.}) 28. Qe3 (28. Nxd6 bxc2 29. Nxb7 Qxb2 30. Qc1 Qxb7 31. Qxc2 Qb4 32.
Rd1 Ne8 $44 {After blocking the pawn with the knight, Black has entirely
adequate compensation for the pawn. We should also keep in mind that White's
king is exposed.}) 28... Nxd5 29. Qxb6 Nxb6 30. Na1 Bb4 31. Re3 Bxe4 (31... f5
32. Nf2 Nc4 33. Rxb3 Bxf3+ 34. Rxf3 Nxb2 35. Rb3 Rd2 36. Rxb4 Nd1 $11) 32. Rxe4
Bc3 (32... Rd2+ 33. Re2 Rxe2+ 34. Bxe2 Bc3 35. Nxb3 Bxb2 $11) 33. bxc3 b2 34.
Re1 Na4 $2 (34... g6 $1 {was better, in order to free the rook from the need
of defending the back rank.} 35. Nb3 {On c2, the knight would be lost to ...
Rd2+, since there is no more backrank mate.} Na4 36. Rb1 Rb8 37. Bc6 Nxc3 38.
Rxb2 Nd1 39. Rb1 Nc3 40. Rb2 Nd1 41. Rd2 Ne3+ 42. Kf2 Rxb3 $11) 35. Nc2 $5 Nxc3
36. Na3 Rd2+ 37. Kh3 (37. Kf1 $1 f5 38. Re8+ Kf7 39. Rb8 $18) 37... f5 38. Nb1
(38. Re8+ Kf7 39. Rb8 Rf2 40. Bc6 Ne2 41. g4 Kg6 42. Be8+ Kf6 43. g5+ Ke7 44.
Bc6 g6 $44) 38... Nxb1 39. Rxb1 Kf7 40. g4 fxg4+ 41. Bxg4 g6 42. Kg3 Kf6 $1 (
42... Ke7 $6 {was the start of a wrong plan. The king should stay on the
kingside.} 43. h4 Kd6 44. h5 Kc5 $2 45. h6 Kb4 46. f5 $18 {Solomon, S (2401)
-Dale, A (2308) Melbourne Cup Weekend 2013 (8) 1-0}) 43. h4 Rc2 44. Kf3 h5 45.
Bd7 Rc3+ 46. Ke2 Rc4 47. Ke3 Rc3+ 48. Kd2 Rf3 49. Rxb2 Rxf4 $11) 16... Bd6 (
16... Re8 {is also possible.} 17. Nc2 (17. d6 Bf8 18. Nc2 Re6 19. Bc5 Ned7 20.
Ba3 Ne8 $11 {Black will retrieve the pawn soon, keeping an active position.})
17... b4 18. Ne4 Nxd5 $11) 17. Nc2 $1 {The only move keeping White in the game.
} (17. Ne4 $2 {weakens the kingside.} Nxe4 18. fxe4 Qh4 19. Bf4 Nc4 20. Bg3 (
20. Nxc4 Bxf4 21. g3 Bxg3 22. hxg3 Qxg3+ 23. Kh1 bxc4 $19) (20. Bxc4 Bxf4 21.
g3 Bxd2 22. gxh4 Be3+ {An important intermediate move.} 23. Kg2 bxc4 $19) 20...
Nxd2 21. Bxh4 Nxe4 22. Bf3 Rae8 $17 {Ehmann,T (2095)-Milov,L (2468) Arber op
4th 2015 (3) 0-1}) (17. Nab1 b4 18. Ne4 Nxe4 19. fxe4 Qh4 $17) 17... Re8 (17...
b4 $6 {allows} 18. Ne4 Nxe4 19. fxe4 Qh4 20. Bf4 Nc4 21. Bxc4 Bxf4 22. g3 Bxd2
23. gxh4 $16 {The bishop on c4 is not hanging. Even if it was, there would be
no intermediate check on e3.}) 18. a3 Rc8 19. Kh1 Ng6 $5 $146 {One of the
possible moves, maintaining Black's compensation.} (19... Nh5 $2 {releases the
pressure in the centre, allowing White to consolidate.} 20. Nd4 Rxc3 21. bxc3
Qh4 22. Nf5 Qxh2+ 23. Kxh2 Nxf3+ 24. Kh1 Nxd2 25. Bxh5 {Jurasek,M (2305)
-Pachmann,A (2270) CZE-chT 9697 1996 (11) 1-0}) (19... Ned7 $5 $146 20. Bf1 Nc5
21. Qf2 Nb3 22. Bb6 Qd7 23. Rab1 Qf5 $44) 20. Rac1 (20. Nd4 Bc5 21. Nf5 Bxe3
22. Nxe3 Qb6 23. Nf5 Re5 24. Bd3 Nxd5 $11) 20... Be5 21. Nb4 Qd6 22. h3 (22. g3
$2 Bxg3 23. hxg3 Qxg3 24. Bf1 Rxe3 25. Qxe3 Ng4 26. Qd2 Nf2+ $19) 22... Nf4
$132 *

