1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nb5 d6 6. c4 Nf6 7. N1c3 a6 8. Na3
Be7 9. Be2 O-O 10. O-O b6 11. Be3 Bb7 12. Qd2 Ne5 13. Qd4 {This is how White
could react to an earlier knight jump to e5, but here it loses a tempo.} Ned7
14. Rfd1 ({In the event of} 14. f3 {Black has a choice.} Re8 {reinforces the
threat by creating indirect pressure along the e-file.} (14... d5 {
equalises at once.} 15. cxd5 exd5 16. Nxd5 (16. exd5 Bc5 17. Qd2 Bxe3+ 18. Qxe3
Re8 19. Qd2 b5 20. Nc2 Qb6+ 21. Rf2 Rad8 22. Rd1 Ne5 23. Qe3 Qxe3 24. Nxe3 Ng6
25. Nc2 Nxd5 $11 {Gaprindashvili, N-Kushnir,A World-ch (Women) 1969 (8) 1-0})
16... Nxd5 17. exd5 Re8 18. d6 Bxd6 (18... Bf6 19. Qd2 b5 20. Rfe1 Bxb2 21.
Qxb2 Rxe3 22. Nc2 Re5 $13) 19. Qxd6 Rxe3 20. Bc4 $11 {Botalova,Y (2103)
-Gerasimova,O (2189) Zelenograd 2007 (3) 1/2-1/2}) 15. g4 $2 {This is
precisely what White should refrain from! Wasting a tempo and weakening the
kingside plays into Black's hands.} d5 $1 16. cxd5 exd5 17. g5 Nxe4 $5 18. fxe4
Bc5 19. Qd2 Qxg5+ 20. Kf2 Qf4+ 21. Ke1 (21. Bf3 dxe4 $19) 21... Qxe3 22. Qxe3
Bxe3 23. exd5 Nf6 $19 {Mukhin, M-Kayumov, D Tashkent 1974 0-1}) 14... Re8 {
Even though the f-pawn has not advanced to f3 yet, this move is useful. In the
long run, White cannot do without f2-f3 and then Black will be ready for
breaking in the centre under optimal circumstances. I remember that when
consulting the first volume of the B volume of the Encyclopaedia of Chess
Openings, more than 30 years ago, this was one of the lines (based on the game
Adorjan-Portisch below), ending with the evaluation =/+, slightly getter for
Black. My understanding at the age of 16 was not such, but now I can see that
the author of the respective chapter was not far from the truth.} 15. Nc2 {
This is one of the last things White does in this line, but with the queen on
d4, it seems that he faces some micro problems anyway. The idea of the last
move was to over-defend the bishop on e3 since he could not delay f2-f3 for
too long.} (15. Rac1 Rc8 16. f3 (16. Bf1 Ng4 $15) 16... d5 $1 17. exd5 exd5 18.
Bf2 Bd6 $15 {The c-pawn is pinned and the kingside is a bit in danger.} 19. Rc2
(19. cxd5 $2 Rxc3 $1 $19) 19... Be5 20. Qh4 (20. Qd2 Qc7 21. g3 d4 $1 $17 22.
Bxd4 $2 Bxg3 23. hxg3 Qxg3+ 24. Kf1 Ng4 25. Bg1 Bxf3 26. Bxf3 Qxf3+ 27. Bf2
Qh3+ 28. Kg1 Nde5 $19) 20... Bxc3 21. bxc3 Qe7 22. Nb1 dxc4 23. Bxc4 Ne5 24.
Be2 b5 $15 {with active play for Black.}) 15... Qc7 16. Rac1 Rac8 {Black
simply completes his development and invites his opponent to come up with a
plan.} 17. Kh1 {This move was played one year after the Encyclopaedia was
published.} ({The game quoted in the book went} 17. f3 $6 d5 $1 $15 18. cxd5 (
18. exd5 exd5 19. Bf4 Qd8 20. Kh1 dxc4 21. Bxc4 b5 22. Bb3 Nc5 $15) 18... exd5
19. Nxd5 Nxd5 20. exd5 Bf6 21. Qb4 (21. Qd2 Bxb2 $19 {We can notice that
Na3-c2 spoiled White's coordination.}) 21... Qe5 $1 {Attacking b2 and
threatening ...Rxc2.} 22. f4 (22. Bc4 b5 23. Bd4 Qf4 24. Bf1 Bg5 25. Qb3 Nf6
$17) 22... Qxb2 23. Bg4 Rxc2 24. Qxb2 Rxb2 25. Bxd7 Rxe3 26. Rc7 Bd4 27. Kh1
Rd2 28. Rb1 g6 29. Rxb7 Bc5 30. Bc6 Ree2 31. d6 Rxd6 32. Bf3 Rxa2 33. f5 a5 {
Adorjan,A-Portisch,L Hoogovens Wijk aan Zee 1972 (10) 0-1}) 17... h6 {
Apparently hesitant, but in fact a potentially useful move. Hard to believe
that Taimanov foresaw its merits, but his intuition told him to play it.} (
17... h5 $5 {may lead to similar play as in lines examined before.}) (17... Ne5
18. Na3 (18. Qxb6 Qxb6 19. Bxb6 Nxc4 $15) 18... Qb8 19. Qxb6 (19. f3 d5 20.
exd5 exd5 21. Qxb6 dxc4 $11) 19... d5 $5 (19... Nxe4 20. Nxe4 Bxe4 $11) 20.
cxd5 Neg4 21. f4 Nxe3 22. Qxe3 Bd6 23. Rf1 (23. e5 Bxa3 24. exf6 Bxb2 25. Qg3
