1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nb5 d6 6. c4 Nf6 7. N1c3 a6 8. Na3
Be7 9. Be2 O-O 10. O-O b6 11. Be3 Bb7 12. f3 Re8 13. Qb3 {The critical
continuation, aiming to prove that f2-f3 was more useful than ...Re8.} d5 $1 {
This move allows Black to make use of the weakening of the g1-a7 diagonal,
caused by f2-f3.} (13... Nd7 {is also possible, of course.} 14. Rfd1 Nce5 $5 (
14... Nc5 15. Qc2 Bf6 {is the old main line, similar to that after 12.Qb3.
Black somewhat loses flexibility.}) 15. Rac1 h5 {with the usual kingside play.}
) 14. cxd5 ({The immediate capture does not change the evaluation.} 14. Bxb6
Na5 $1 $146 (14... Qb8 $2 15. cxd5 exd5 16. Nxd5 Nxd5 17. Qxd5 Bd6 18. Qh5 $16
{Stein,L-Taimanov,M URS-chT Republics 09th Group3 1963 (2.2) 1-0}) 15. Bxd8 (
15. Bxa5 Qxa5 16. Qxb7 Rab8 17. Qc6 Bxa3 18. bxa3 Qxc3 $17) 15... Bc5+ {
Now is when the weakness of the diagonal is important. Without this check,
Black would lose a piece.} 16. Kh1 Nxb3 17. axb3 Raxd8 18. e5 Nd7 19. cxd5 exd5
20. f4 d4 21. Na4 g5 $11) 14... exd5 15. Bxb6 {Saiz Rodriguez,D (2256)-Neyra
Ferrer,J (2211) Moncada Cup-C 2018 (4) 1/2-1/2} Na5 $1 16. Bxa5 (16. Bxd8 Bc5+
17. Kh1 Nxb3 18. axb3 Raxd8 19. exd5 Nxd5 20. Nxd5 (20. Ne4 Bd4 21. Nc4 Nf4 22.
Bd1 Nd3 $11) 20... Rxe2 21. Nc3 Rxb2 22. Na4 Bxa3 23. Rxa3 Re2 24. Nc5 Bc8 25.
Raa1 Bh3 $5 26. gxh3 Rdd2 $11) 16... Qxa5 17. e5 $1 {The only way to maintain
approximate equality.} (17. exd5 Bxd5 18. Nxd5 Nxd5 $17) (17. Bd3 Rab8 $17) (
17. Qxb7 Qc5+ 18. Kh1 Reb8 19. b4 Qd6 20. e5 Qxe5 21. f4 Qe6 22. Qc7 Bd6 23.
Qc6 Rc8 24. Qb7 Rab8 25. Qxa6 Rxc3 $17) 17... Bxa3 18. exf6 {This leads to
an interesting play, where Black is not worse, due to his strong dark-squared
bishop.} (18. bxa3 Rac8 19. Rfc1 Rxe5 $11) 18... Bc5+ 19. Kh1 Rab8 20. fxg7 Bd6
21. Rad1 Qd8 22. Qa4 Ba8 23. Qg4 Re6 24. Bd3 Rh6 25. h3 Rxb2 $13 *

