1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nb5 d6 6. c4 Nf6 7. N1c3 a6 8. Na3
Be7 9. Be2 O-O 10. O-O b6 11. Be3 Bb7 12. Rc1 {As far as I understand, this is
White's best chance to maintain the structure as it is for a longer time, not
allowing the freeing ...d6-d5.} Re8 {The best way of remaining flexible.} (
12... Ne5 {transposes to the 11...Ne5 move order.} 13. f3 (13. Qd4 $5) 13...
Re8) 13. Qb3 {The critical continuation. Since White did not weaken the g1-a7
diagonal, Black does not have dynamic resources anymore. Any other reasonable
move would transpose to a previous line.} Nd7 14. Rfd1 Rc8 {The main advocate
of this flexible move order in the mid-'80s used to be the original Ukrainian
grandmaster Oleg Romanishin.} 15. Rd2 {Preparing a coherent regrouping.} (15.
Qc2 {may be answered in the same way.} Nce5 16. Qd2 (16. Qb1 Qc7 {Still
inviting the opponent to commit himself.} 17. f4 Ng6 18. Bf3 Nh4 19. Be2 {
Chatterjee, S (1974)-Romanishin, O (2543) Kolkata op 2004 (2) 0-1} g5 $5 20. fxg5
Bxg5 $15 21. Bxg5 Qc5+ 22. Kh1 Qxg5 $17) (16. f4 Ng6 17. g3 Rc7 {Georgiev, K 
(2605)-Ribli, Z (2595) Goodricke op 03rd 1992 (9) 1/2-1/2} 18. Bf3 Qa8 19. Bg2
Rec8 20. Qe2 Ngf8 $11) 16... Nf6 (16... g5 $5) 17. f3 Bf8 (17... h5 $5) 18. Bf2
Qc7 19. Bf1 Ned7 (19... Nfd7 {would restore Romanishin's usual setup in the
games below.}) 20. Nc2 Ne5 21. Nd4 Qb8 22. Na4 Ba8 23. b4 {We can notice that
in this game, Romanishin played without a clear plan, a bit like Andersson.
But his reaction to White's queenside plan is a bit more accurate than Ulf's.}
Nxc4 $5 24. Bxc4 b5 25. Bb3 (25. Nb6 bxc4 26. Nxc8 Rxc8 $44) 25... bxa4 26.
Bxa4 Red8 27. Bc6 d5 $11 {Savon, V (2455)-Romanishin, O (2585) UKR Spartakiad
8th 1983 1/2-1/2}) 15... Nce5 {This is Romanishin's favourite regrouping.} ({
I will include an old famous game, lost by Karpov in his first tournament as a
World champion. He won the tournament, by the way. Black's play was not sound,
but the course of the game reveals the practical chances yielded by the
sacrifice of the central pawn.} 15... Qc7 16. Qd1 Qb8 17. f3 Ba8 18. Qf1 Nce5
19. Nab1 Nf6 {Black is just moving around with his pieces, without undertaking
anything concrete.} 20. Kh1 h6 21. Rdd1 Bf8 22. Nd2 Rcd8 23. Qf2 Ned7 24. a3
$14 {Karpov regrouped systematically and can count on a stable advantage
already. The concrete way of making progress is not obvious yet, but Black
might have feared that Karpov would find a molesting long plan.} d5 $6 25. cxd5
exd5 26. exd5 Bd6 27. Nf1 Rxe3 $5 {What a lack of respect! You are playing
against the world champion and you are supposed to be a positional and
defensive player. The first name is Ulf.} 28. Nxe3 Bxh2 29. Nf1 Bf4 30. Rc2 b5
31. Bd3 Nb6 32. Be4 Nc4 33. a4 Re8 34. axb5 axb5 35. Re2 Be5 36. Qc5 Nd6 {
Many years later, Andersson managed to draw against Kasparov by defending a
fortress where he was an exchange down with equal pawns. He might have
achieved that here, too, but Karpov kindly invited him to do better than that.}
37. Na2 $2 Ndxe4 38. fxe4 Bd6 39. Qc2 Re5 $19 {Suddenly, Black has a winning
attack.} 40. g3 Qe8 41. Rde1 Bb7 42. Kg1 Nh7 43. Nc1 Ng5 44. Nd2 Bb4 45. Kf2
Bxd2 46. Rxd2 Nxe4+ 47. Rxe4 Rxe4 $19 {Karpov,A-Andersson,U Milan 1975 (8) 0-1}
) 16. Qd1 Ng6 {Another part of the plan.} ({In a later game, Romanishin
delayed this move just a bit, which did not change the position greatly.} 16...
Qc7 17. Kh1 Ng6 18. Qg1 Bf6 ({In fact, Black has other good plans, too,
depending on the concrete details of the position. For instance, here he could
try} 18... Nh4 19. f3 f5 $132) 19. Nab5 $5 (19. Nab1 {allowed Romanishin to
carry out his plan on dark squares.} Qb8 20. Rcd1 Be5 21. f3 Bc6 22. Bd4 Bf4
23. Be3 Be5 24. Bd4 b5 25. cxb5 axb5 26. b4 Bf4 27. Be3 d5 28. exd5 exd5 29.
Bxf4 Nxf4 30. Bf1 Ne5 $17 {Imanaliev,T (2385)-Romanishin,O (2570) Frunze
International 1985 (8) 0-1}) 19... axb5 20. Nxb5 Qb8 21. Nxd6 Bc6 22. b4 Be7
23. Nxc8 (23. Nxe8 $2 Bxb4 $19) 23... Qxc8 $13) 17. Bf1 (17. Qf1 Qc7 (17... Nc5
18. f3 f5 {is another way of breaking on the kingside.} 19. exf5 exf5 20. Rcd1
Bf6 {If anything, the rook stands well on e8.} 21. Nc2 Qe7 22. Rxd6 Bxc3 23.
bxc3 f4 24. Bxc5 bxc5 25. R6d2 Nh4 $44) 18. Rdd1 Qb8 19. f3 Bf6 20. Nab1 Bd8
21. Kh1 {Psakhis, L (2555)-Romanishin, O (2560) Szirak 1986 1/2-1/2}) 17... Qc7
18. Rdc2 Bf6 19. Nab1 Qb8 20. f3 Be5 21. h3 {Obiously fearing ...d6-d5, but
weakening the kingside for nothing is worse than the possible effects of the
threat.} (21. g3 Nf6 22. Bf2 h5 $15) ({In fact, ...d6-d5 was not a big threat
yet, but Black could prepare it with} 21. Kh1 $5 h5 (21... d5 22. cxd5 exd5 23.
Nxd5 Rxc2 24. Rxc2 Bxh2 25. Nbc3 {leads to complicated play. Black could
retreat with his bishop or else go for the ultra-complicated line} b5 26. f4 b4
27. Ne2 Bxd5 28. Qxd5 Nf6 29. Qf5 $1 b3 $1 {Black needs to prepare his
queenside counterplay, too. This is possible with the rook on c2.} 30. axb3 h5
$1 31. Rc4 {Without the intermediate advance of the b-pawn, this would yield
White an advantage, but things are unclear here after} Ng4 32. Bc1 Qxb3 $13)
22. Qe1 h4 $15) 21... Rcd8 (21... Nf6 $15) 22. Rd2 Ba8 23. Kh1 Nf6 24. Qb3 Bf4
25. Bxf4 Nxf4 26. Rcd1 N6h5 27. Kg1 Ng3 $11 28. Kf2 $2 d5 $1 29. cxd5 (29. Kxg3
Nd3+ 30. Kh4 Qf4+ 31. g4 g5+ 32. Kh5 Qf6 $19) 29... exd5 30. Nxd5 Bxd5 31. exd5
Nf5 (31... Qe5 32. Kg1 Rd6 $19) 32. d6 b5 33. Kg1 Qb6+ 34. Kh2 Ne3 35. d7 Re6
36. Rc1 Rd6 37. Qb4 Nfd5 38. Qh4 R6xd7 39. Bd3 g6 $19 {Marjanovic,S (2515)
-Romanishin,O (2580) Dortmunder Schachtage-10 1982 (11) 0-1} *

