{[%evp 0,24,29,37,39,37,59,35,35,35,35,29,47,35,35,9,42,-3,5,26,61,44,38,30,
122,27,23]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 {In this line, we will
deal with several developing moves, which do not involve the previous 5.Nc3.
All these lines are mainly meant to avoid the Paulsen main systems, but have a
lower impact on our Scheweningen repertoire.} 5. Be3 (5. f4 {is simplest
answered with} d5 (5... d6 {preparing ...Nf6 under optimal circumstances allows
} 6. c4 {but this can be met with} d5 $11 {, when one can feel that WHite is a
bot over-expanded and underdeveloped.}) (5... Nf6 6. e5 Nd5 {should be fine,
but leads to a structure that is unfamiliar to us.}) 6. e5 (6. Bb5 Bd7 {
leaves White hanging.}) 6... Bd7 $5 {Anticipating Bb5.} 7. Be3 Nxd4 (7... Qb6
$5 8. Nc3 Bc5 9. Na4 Qa5+ 10. Nc3 Nxd4 11. Bxd4 Nh6 12. Bxc5 Qxc5 13. Qd2 Bc6
14. Ne2 Nf5 $132) 8. Bxd4 Ne7 9. Nd2 Nc6 10. Bf2 g5 $15) (5. Be2 {may be the
most bothering for Paulsen players but not for us.} Nf6 6. Nc3 (6. f3 Bc5 $5
7. Nb3 (7. Be3 Qb6 $19) 7... Bb6 $15) 6... d6 $1 {Since the system with Be2 
(the classical system) is not dangerous, we can transpose to it without trying
to take advantage of White's move order.} (6... Bb4 {is usually met with a
sound pawn sacrifice:} 7. O-O (7. f3 d5 $15) (7. Qd3 d5 8. exd5 Nxd5 9. Nxc6
bxc6 10. Bd2) 7... Bxc3 8. bxc3 Nxe4 {with just good compensation for the pawn.
Black is OK objectively, but this is a position that should concern Paulsen
players and not us.})) (5. g3 {is examined in Line 19.}) 5... Nf6 6. Nc3 (6.
Bd3 d5 $11) (6. Nd2 d5 7. Bb5 Bd7 8. Bxc6 (8. exd5 Nxd5 9. Bxc6 bxc6 10. Qe2 {
Koch,C (1930)-Ziegler,M (2138) Regionalliga NW 1415 2014 (9.2) 1/2-1/2} c5 11.
N4b3 Qc7 12. Nc4 Be7 $15) 8... bxc6 9. e5 Ng8 10. N4b3 Qc7 11. f4 c5 $17) (6.
f3 d5 7. exd5 Nxd5 8. Nxc6 (8. Bf2 Bc5 $15) 8... bxc6 9. Bf2 Rb8 10. Bc4 (10.
Qc1 Qf6 11. c3 Qe5+ 12. Kd1 Qc7 13. Kc2 e5 14. Nd2 Bf5+ $19 {Sanon,M (2120)
-Stefansson,H (2585) Olympiad-39 Khanty-Mansiysk 2010 (1.1) 0-1}) (10. b3 {
Krapchetov,D (1699)-Petrov,N (2562) Tuapse Blitz op 2021 (1) 0-1} Qa5+ $19)
10... Rxb2 11. Bb3 Bb4+) 6... Bb4 {Against Be3, we can play this move, since
there are fewer dangers for Black than in a similar position with Be2 instead
of Be3. The first thing is that with the white king two moves away from
castling, the threat is ...Nxe4 and not ...Bxc3.} (6... d6 {is fine, of course,
but it may take us to the relatively dangerous English Attack.}) 7. Bd3 d5 8.
exd5 Nxd5 {Besides, the bishop is exposed on e3.} 9. Nxc6 Nxe3 {I could not
resist taking this bishop.} (9... bxc6 10. Bd2 O-O 11. O-O {is also playable.})
10. fxe3 bxc6 11. O-O Qb6 (11... O-O 12. Rxf7 Kxf7 13. Qh5+ Ke7 14. Qh4+ {
Melnikov,V-Luchin,M URS ol Soviet Union 1967 1-0} Kf7 15. Qxb4 Kg8 $13) (11...
g6 12. Qg4 Qe7 13. Qd4 O-O 14. Rf6 c5 15. Qh4 c4 $1 16. Bxc4 Bb7 17. Raf1 Rac8
18. Bd3 Bc5 $15 {Pina Fernandez,J (2287)-Troia,E (2275) Webchess op5 sf05
email 2014 1/2-1/2}) 12. Qf3 O-O $15 {Karaivanova,P (1841)-Nurgali,N (2192)
Belgrade Serbia op 2023 (6) 0-1} *

