{[%evp 0,24,30,37,47,51,44,34,34,15,25,17,12,11,14,20,21,21,34,32,32,16,25,12,
24,33,32]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. g3 {When playing this
move, White may wish a bit more than transposing to the fianchetto system.} d5
$1 {The most resolute way of taking advantage of White's move order.} (5... Nf6
6. Bg2 d6 7. c4 {leads to an active version of the hedgehog structure.}) 6. Bg2
(6. exd5 $2 Qxd5 7. Nxc6 Qxc6 8. Rg1 Bd7 $15) (6. Nc3 Nf6 7. exd5 Nxd5 (7...
exd5 8. Bg2 Bg4 9. Qd3 Bc5 10. Be3 Qb6 $11) 8. Bg2 (8. Nxc6 bxc6 9. Bg2 Ba6 $11
) 8... Nxc3 9. bxc3 Bd7 $11) (6. Bb5 {is not very logical after g2-g3.} Bd7 7.
exd5 exd5 8. O-O Nf6 9. Re1+ Be7 10. Bxc6 bxc6 11. Qe2 c5 12. Nb5 O-O 13. Bf4
Bxb5 14. Qxb5 h6 15. Nc3 Bd6 16. Bxd6 Qxd6 $11 {Tudela Corbalan,C (2175)
-Andersson,U (2542) Granada op 2006 (2) 0-1}) 6... dxe4 7. Nxc6 Qxd1+ 8. Kxd1
bxc6 9. Bxe4 Bb7 10. Nd2 {We have an interesting queenless ending. Black has a
weak pawn on c6, but also a mobile kingside majority. Besides, the white king
will need some time to reach a comfortable position.} Nf6 11. Bf3 (11. Bg2
O-O-O 12. Ke2 Be7 13. b3 Bb4 14. c4 Bc3 15. Rb1 c5 16. Bxb7+ {Gavrikov,V (2539)
-Yakovich, Y (2534) Excelsior Cup 2001 (2) 1/2-1/2}) ({Surprisingly,} 11. Bd3 $5
$146 {was never tried.} c5 12. Re1 Ng4 $5 13. Ke2 Nxh2 14. f3 O-O-O {Will
White be able to trap the knight?} 15. Be4 (15. Rh1 {allows} Ng4) 15... Ba6+
16. Kf2 h5 17. Kg2 {Yes, he will, but Black will have excellent compensation
for it, due to White's exposed king and delay in development.} h4 18. Kxh2 (18.
g4 Bd6 19. Rh1 h3+ 20. Kf2 f5 21. gxf5 Rdf8 22. fxe6 Ng4+ $19) 18... hxg3+ 19.
Kg1 $1 {White has to be careful.} (19. Kxg3 Bd6+ 20. f4 g5 21. Kf2 gxf4 22. Nf3
c4 23. c3 Rdg8 24. Bd2 f5 25. Bc6 e5 26. Bxf4 exf4 27. Rh1 Kc7 $15) (19. Kg2 g5
$17 20. Rh1 Rxh1 21. Kxh1 Bd6 $17) 19... c4 20. Nf1 f5 21. Bf4 (21. Bc6 c3 {
[%cal Ga6f1]} 22. f4 Bc5+ 23. Be3 cxb2 24. Bxc5 bxa1=Q 25. Rxa1 Bxf1 26. Rxf1
Rd2 $15) 21... fxe4 22. Rxe4 Rd5 23. Kg2 g5 24. Bxg3 Bb7 25. Rxc4+ Rc5 26.
Rxc5+ Bxc5 27. Be5 (27. Nh2 Rd8 $44) 27... Rf8 28. Nh2 g4 29. Nxg4 Rxf3 30. Kh2
Be4 $11) 11... h5 $5 $146 {The relative weakness of White's kingside is too
inviting for me.} (11... O-O-O 12. Ke2 e5 13. c4 e4 14. Bg2 Bd6 15. Nf1 Be5 16.
Rb1 Ba6 17. Ne3 Rhe8 18. Bd2 {Vitiugov,N (2721)-Van Wely,L (2653) Vladimir
Petrov Memorial op rapid 2016 (4) 0-1 White has managed to get coordinated and
later even got the more pleasant position. Black should have undertaken
something concrete now.} Nd5 19. Bxe4 Nxe3 20. Bxe3 Bxc4+ 21. Kf3 Bd5 22. Bxd5
Rxd5 23. Rbc1 Re6 $11) 12. Ke2 (12. h3 O-O-O 13. Ke2 h4 14. g4 Ba6+ 15. Ke1 (
15. c4 Nd5 $17) 15... Nd5 $15) (12. h4 Ng4 $11) 12... Ng4 13. b3 O-O-O 14. h3
Ne5 15. Be4 Bb4 16. Nc4 Ba6 17. Bd3 Nxd3 18. cxd3 Rd5 $11 *

