{[%evp 0,34,29,37,39,32,32,21,21,35,35,29,62,47,47,47,43,36,42,28,28,17,25,12,
3,-42,-10,-82,-53,-158,-123,-123,-47,-69,-58,-122,-86]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3.
d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e6 5. Nc3 d6 6. g4 {This continuation, typical for the
Scheveningen Keres Attack remains an important option for White. True, there
will be no knight to attack on f6, but White can nevertheless build up a
massive kingside space advantage. It is worth mentioning that the last move
was played for the first time by the Yugoslav grandmaster Bozidar Ivanovic in
1979 and slightly later in 1981. A few years after that, Karpov used it against
Kasparov in the 14th game of their second match. It might have been more
correct to name it the Ivanovic Attack, but I thought that by using the Keres
name the mental association with the system based on g2-g4 would be more
natural.} Nge7 {This way of developing partly takes the steam out of White's
attack. Black prepares to exchange on d4, followed by ...Nc6 and possibly ...
Be7. Such a plan is typical for the Taimanov Paulsen (5...a6 6.Be3 Nge7). True,
there are certain differences between the two systems. More about it later. It
is worth mentioning that in the proper Scheweningen (with ...Nf6), the knight
would need by two tempi more to reach c6 (usually via d7-e5-c6).} 7. Be3 {
White prepares to meet ...Nxd4 with Qxd4 and if ...Nc6, then Qd2.} (7. Ndb5 $6
$146 {is ineffective due to} Ng6 {, preventing Bf4. The least Black can do
later is playing ...a7-a6 and returning with the knight to e7, but it is
possible that the knight searches for other horizons, too, for instance by
moving to h4.}) (7. g5 $6 {allows} Nxd4 8. Qxd4 Nc6 {, when the queen does not
have adequate squares for retreating. If} 9. Qd3 a6 10. Be3 b5 {the queen will
be permanently exposed on d3.}) (7. Nb3 {does not have much of an independent
value.} a6 8. h4 {Neglecting the development for the sake of carrying out the
pawn attack is not the best idea.} (8. Be3 {is better, but after} b5 {, we
transpose to Line 24.}) 8... b5 9. Bg2 Bb7 10. g5 Rc8 11. Qe2 (11. h5 Ne5 12.
Qe2 b4 13. Nd1 d5 14. f4 Nc4 $11) 11... h5 $5 (11... Na5 12. h5 b4 13. Nd1 Nec6
$15) 12. a4 b4 13. Na2 g6 (13... Ng6 14. f4 Na5 $15 15. Nxb4 $2 d5 16. Nd3 dxe4
17. Bxe4 Rxc2 18. Qxc2 Bxe4 19. Rh3 Bb4+ 20. Kf1 O-O $19) 14. Bf4 Bg7 15. Rd1
Ne5 16. Nxb4 Nc4 17. Nd3 Qb6 18. O-O O-O 19. Nd2 Rfd8 20. Nxc4 Rxc4 $44 21. Ne5
(21. b3 Rc3 $44) 21... dxe5 22. Be3 Rcd4 23. c3 Bc6 24. b3 (24. Qc2 Rc8 25.
cxd4 exd4 26. Bf4 Be8 $44) 24... Qxb3 25. cxd4 exd4 26. Bf4 Qxa4 27. Qf3 Bb5
28. Ra1 Qb4 $15 {Nakamura, H (2789)-Van Wely, L (2672) Tata Steel-A 76th 2014 (7)
0-1}) 7... a6 {Now and later, Black should not hurry with the exchange in the
centre.} ({With the queen on its initial square,} 7... Nxd4 8. Qxd4 Nc6 9. Qd2
{gains a tempo for White.}) 8. g5 {Continuing the pawn attack after having
consolidated the centre a bit. The queen remains on d1, in order to inhibit ...
Nxd4.} (8. f4 {is examined in Lines 22 and 23.}) (8. Nb3 {is the subject of
Line 24.}) 8... b5 9. h4 Bb7 10. Bg2 {I have chosen this natural developing
move as the main line because it was played in a top-level game. Its merits
are questionable, though. True, over defending f3 is important, but leaving c4
undefended may cause problems.} (10. h5 $146 {wastes much time and Black can
already play} Nxd4 (10... Rc8 {is also worth mentioning.}) 11. Qxd4 Nc6 12. Qd2
Qa5 13. Rh3 (13. f4 b4 14. Ne2 d5 15. exd5 Rd8 16. Bg2 Ne7 $11) (13. a3 b4 14.
Na2 bxa3 15. Qxa5 Nxa5 16. bxa3 Bxe4 17. Rh4 d5 18. Nc3 Bxc2 19. Rc1 Bb3 20.
Nb5 Rd8 21. Nc7+ Kd7 22. Rf4 Bxa3 23. Ra1 Nc4 24. Rxf7+ Kd6 $13 25. Bxc4 $2
Bb4+) 13... h6 14. g6 (14. gxh6 gxh6 15. Rg3 Be7 $132) 14... fxg6 15. hxg6 Be7
$11) (10. Rg1 {has the same drawback as 10.h4.} Nxd4 (10... Rc8 $5 $146) 11.
Qxd4 Nc6 12. Qd1 {A curious decision, rejecting the offered extra tempo.} (12.
Qd2 Qa5 {is comfortable for Black, though, since White cannot castle.} 13. f4
Be7 14. Qf2 Bd8 15. h5 Rc8 $13) 12... g6 (12... Rc8 13. h5 Be7 14. Rg3 h6 $5
$11) 13. Bd4 Nxd4 14. Qxd4 Rg8 15. O-O-O Rc8 ({The immediate} 15... Bg7 $1 {
is better} 16. Qxd6 Qxd6 17. Rxd6 Ke7 $15 18. Rb6 $2 Rab8 19. Ne2 Be5 $19) 16.
a4 Bg7 17. Qxd6 Qxd6 18. Rxd6 {A similar position as above, but with the black
queenside under pressure.} Ke7 (18... Bxc3 19. bxc3 Ke7 20. e5 Rxc3 21. axb5
axb5 22. Bxb5 Be4 23. Rd7+ Kf8 24. Bd3 Bxd3 25. Rxd3 Rc4 26. Rh1 Kg7 27. h5
gxh5 28. Rxh5 Rgc8 $44) 19. Rb6 Rb8 (19... Rc7 20. axb5 {[%cal Gb6b7,Gb5a6]} a5
21. Ne2 Bxe4 22. c3 Rd8 23. Bg2 Bd3 24. Re1 $14 {Budisavljevic,L (2509)
-Perunovic,M (2566) SRB-chT Premier 2021 (3.3) 0-1}) 20. axb5 {If Black
attacks the rook with his bishop, Rxb7 followed by bxa6 is strong.} a5 $1 21.
Ne2 Be5 $13 {White will soon have to sacrifice the exchange, with just normal
compensation.}) 10... Rc8 ({Since Bg2 is not such an important gain of time} 
10... Nxd4 11. Qxd4 Nc6 {is also possible, for instance} 12. Qd2 Ne5 13. b3 Qa5
$11) 11. Qd2 (11. Nxc6 {Now and in many other moments, this willing exchange
simplifies Black's task a bit. It sort of transposes to the sequence ...Nxd4,
Bxd4 ...Nc6, Be3, thus giving up the chance of gaining a tempo with Qd1xd4
and Qd2.} Nxc6 12. f4 Na5 {Black has easy play.} 13. Bd4 Nc4 14. b3 e5 (14...
Na3 $5 15. O-O h6 $5 $132) 15. bxc4 (15. Bf2 Na3 16. Rh3 b4 17. Qc1 Qa5 $19 {
Mateo, R (2427)-Ter Sahakyan, S (2563) Cappelle op 29th 2013 (3) 0-1}) 15... exd4
16. Nd5 Rxc4 $11) (11. Nb3 Ne5 $15 {reveals the drawbacks of Bf1-g2.}) 11...
Ne5 (11... Nxd4 12. Bxd4 Nc6 13. O-O-O (13. Be3 Ne5 $17) 13... Qa5 $132) 12. b3
$6 (12. O-O-O {is better but not appealing at all.} Nc4 (12... h5 $5 13. gxh6
gxh6 $11) 13. Qe1 b4 14. Nce2 Nxe3 (14... a5 15. Ng3 Nc6 $138) 15. fxe3 Qa5 16.
Kb1 Nc6 $11) 12... Ng4 $1 $146 {Exchanging the bishop after White has weakened
the light squares is even stronger than in the line above.} (12... Qa5 13. Nce2
Qxd2+ 14. Bxd2 h6 15. a4 bxa4 16. Rxa4 Nd7 17. Nc3 g6 $11 {Svidler,P (2710)
-Polgar,J (2665) Haifa act rapid 1998 1/2-1/2}) 13. O-O-O Nxe3 14. Qxe3 Qc7 15.
Kb2 g6 $1 {Preparing ...Bg7 but also preventing Nf5 after ...e6-e5.} 16. h5 b4
17. Na4 (17. Nce2 e5 $17) 17... gxh5 $17 {[%cal Gf8g7] followed by ...Bg7.} *

