1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e6 5. Nc3 d6 6. g4 Nge7 7. Be3 a6 8. f4
b5 9. g5 {This move corresponds the spirit of the Keres/Ivanovic attack best.}
Bb7 10. Bg2 {After having over-expanded a bit, White needs to defend the long
diagonal. Unsurprisingly, it is the only move tried in practice.} (10. Nb3 {
may be answered in the same way as in the main line.} h6 $5 11. gxh6 Rxh6 12.
Qe2 Na5 $11) (10. h4 {allows the central break.} d5 (10... Nxd4 11. Qxd4 d5 {
is another possible move order, bearing some similarity with the line
introduced by 10...Nxd4 below.} 12. O-O-O dxe4 13. Qe5 Qb8 14. Qd4 {Facing the
threat ...Nf5 and needing to retrieve the pawn on e4, White has to offer a
draw by repetition. Black can accept it or continue playing, even though the
position remains equal in any case.} Bc6 15. Bh3 Qc7 16. Rhe1 Rd8 17. Qxd8+
Qxd8 18. Rxd8+ Kxd8 19. Nxe4 $11 {Finally retrieving the pawn. Black has many
good continuations, including} Bxe4 20. Bb6+ Kd7 21. Rxe4 Nf5 $11) 11. Nxc6 Bxc6
12. Bg2 b4 13. exd5 Bb7 14. Ne4 Nxd5 15. Bd4 Qc7 16. Be5 Qb6 17. Bd4 Qc7 18.
Qf3 Nxf4 19. Nf6+ gxf6 20. Qxb7 Rc8 21. Bxf6 Qxc2 22. O-O Ne2+ 23. Kf2 (23. Kh1
Ng3+ $19) (23. Kh2 Bd6+ $19) 23... Nd4+ 24. Kg1 (24. Kg3 Bd6+ 25. Kh3 O-O $17)
24... Ne2+ $11) 10... h6 {A principled move, immediately questioning White's
kingside space advantage. It works because White's pawn expansion has cost him
important developing tempi.} (10... Nxd4 11. Qxd4 d5 {practically yields White
an extra tempo with respect to the line with h2-h4 above, but remains playable
anyway.} 12. O-O-O dxe4 13. Qe5 Qb8 14. Nxe4 Nf5 15. Bb6 Be7 16. Rhg1 O-O 17.
Qxb8 Raxb8 18. Ba7 Ra8 19. Bf2 Kh8 20. Ng3 {Nakamura,H (2670)-Sokolov,A (2594)
FRA-chT Top 16 GpA 2008 (3) 1-0} Bxg2 21. Nxf5 exf5 22. Rxg2 f6 23. Rd7 Rfe8
$11) (10... Rc8 $5 {is also worth trying.}) 11. h4 {The most consistent try.} (
11. gxh6 {is a bit of a structural and territorial concession.} Rxh6 $1 {
Suggested by Smirin. Black does best by removing the kingside tension and
aiming to enjoy his more compact structure.} (11... Ng6 $2 {Shirov, A (2690)
-Polgar,J (2645) Madrid Magistral 6th 1997 (1) 1-0} 12. f5 Nh4 13. Rg1 Nxg2+
14. Rxg2 Nxd4 15. Qxd4 e5 16. Qd3 gxh6 17. Nd5 $18) (11... g6 $2 {Chuprov,D 
(2520)-Balashov, Y (2426) RUS-ch Higher League 64th 2011 (7) 1/2-1/2} 12. Qd2
Bxh6 13. Nxc6 Nxc6 14. O-O-O $16) 12. f5 (12. Qd2 Nxd4 13. Bxd4 Nc6 14. Be3
Qh4+ $5 15. Bf2 Qg4 {[%csl Ge1]} 16. Bg3 g5 $132 17. fxg5 Rg6 18. Bf4 b4 19.
Nd1 e5 20. Be3 Nd4 {[%cal Ga8c8]} 21. Bxd4 Qxg5 $17) 12... Nxd4 13. Qxd4 (13.
Bxh6 $2 Nexf5 $1 14. exf5 Bxg2 15. Qxd4 Bxh1 $17 {Smirin}) 13... Nxf5 $1 14.
exf5 Bxg2 $13 {Smirin} 15. Rg1 Rh4 16. Qd3 Bh3 17. fxe6 (17. Bg5 $2 Be7 18.
Bxh4 Bxh4+ 19. Kd1 Bxf5 $19) 17... Bxe6 18. O-O-O Qa5 $132) 11... hxg5 12. hxg5
Rxh1+ 13. Bxh1 Rc8 14. Nxc6 (14. Qd2 Nxd4 15. Bxd4 Nc6 16. Bf2 Na5 {Smirin} 17.
b3 d5 $132) (14. Nce2 $5 Nxd4 15. Bxd4 e5 $132 16. fxe5 $2 Nc6 $17 {leaves the
white king exposed.}) 14... Nxc6 15. Qg4 Qa5 {(?! Smirin) In fact, there is
nothing wrong with this move, but there are worthy alternatives to it, too.} (
15... Na5 16. g6 f5 {Smirin is too optimistic when evaluating that Black is
better here. He is not worse, either, which is good news, of course.} (16...
Nc4 17. gxf7+ Kxf7 18. Bd4 e5 19. Bf2 Nxb2 20. Nd5 Qe8 21. f5 Bxd5 22. exd5 Be7
23. f6 Bxf6 24. Be4 Ke7 $13) 17. Qh3 b4 18. Ne2 Qf6 $11 19. Bd4 Qxg6 20. Bb6 (
20. Bf3 Qh6 $15) 20... fxe4 $1 (20... Nc4 $2 21. exf5 $18 {leaves the bishop
on b7 hanging.}) 21. Bxa5 Rxc2 22. Bxb4 a5 23. Bxa5 Ba6 {Black has enough play
for the piece.} 24. Bd2 Be7 25. Rc1 Rxb2 26. Rc7 Qf5 $5 $11) ({The relatively
"quiet"} 15... b4 $5 16. Ne2 (16. Na4 Na5 {[%csl Gc2][%cal Ga5c4]} 17. Bb6 Qd7
18. b3 Nc4 $17 {[%cal Gb7c6,Gc4a3]}) 16... g6 {is entirely possible.} 17. Qh3 (
17. O-O-O $2 b3 $1 $17 18. axb3 $6 Qa5 $19) 17... Qa5 18. f5 Ne5 19. fxe6 (19.
Nd4 b3+ 20. Bd2 Qa4 21. c3 exf5 22. exf5 Bxh1 23. Qxh1 bxa2 24. fxg6 fxg6 25.
Qb7 Nd3+ 26. Kf1 Qc4 $13) 19... Rxc2 20. exf7+ Kxf7 $13) 16. g6 b4 17. gxf7+
Kxf7 18. Ne2 (18. Nd5 $5 exd5 19. exd5 Re8 20. dxc6 Rxe3+ 21. Kd2 (21. Kf2 Bc8
22. Qxc8 Qc5 $19) 21... Qc5 22. Rg1 Bxc6 23. Bxc6 Re6 24. f5 Re5 25. f6 g5 $13)
18... b3+ 19. Kf2 (19. Bd2 $2 Qxa2 $19 {Smirin}) 19... bxc2 (19... bxa2 $5) 20.
Rg1 {The position remains complicated, offering chances to both sides.} Qxa2 (
20... Ke7 $5) (20... Ne7 $5) 21. e5 {Shabalov, A (2585)-Smirin, I (2600) Los
Angeles 1997 1/2-1/2} Qxb2 22. exd6 (22. Qh5+ Ke7 23. exd6+ Kxd6 $19) 22... Qf6
$11 *

