1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e6 5. Nc3 d6 6. g4 Nge7 7. Be3 a6 8. Nb3
{This knight retreat tries to question the viability of Black's developing
plan. The knight on e7 will need some time to enter the play. In the
positional systems of the Taimanov Paulsen, the knight's trajectory usually is
...Ne7-c8-b6 (after ...b7-b5 and ...Bb7, of course). Things are a bit more
complicated here since Black has spent a tempo on ...d7-d6 and White's setup
is more aggressive. However, precisely the latter offers Black additional ideas,
as we will see.} b5 {A natural neutral move, preparing to develop the
queenside.} 9. f4 {A consistent move, preventing ...Ne5 and preparing
manoeuvres such as Qe2-f2 or even Qf3, while also maintaining the structural
flexibility. It is by far the most popular continuation, but there are many
alternatives worth investigating.} (9. g5 {is relatively harmless, since it
does not create immediate threats and offers Black a free tempo for developing.
} Bb7 10. Qe2 (10. h4 b4 11. Na4 Ne5 12. Nd2 h5 13. gxh6 Nf5 $13) (10. Qd2 $2
Ne5 $17) (10. f4 h6 $5 $11) 10... b4 {Black has to use White's relative lack
of coordination as quickly as possible.} (10... Qc7 $6 {is too slow.} 11. f4
Nc8 12. Qf2 Be7 13. Bg2 Bd8 14. a4 b4 15. Nb1 O-O 16. N1d2 $14 {Iordachescu,V 
(2589)-Bischoff,K (2533) EU-ch 2nd Ohrid 2001 (3) 1/2-1/2}) (10... Ne5 {
threatening both ...Nc4 and ...b5-b4 is also good.} 11. f3 Nc4 12. O-O-O Nxe3
13. Qxe3 h6 14. gxh6 g6 $5 $11) 11. Na4 Ne5 12. f3 (12. O-O-O Bxe4 13. Bb6 Bf3
14. Bxd8 Bxe2 15. Bxe2 Rxd8 16. Bxa6 Kd7 $11) (12. f4 Nd7 $15) 12... Bc6 13.
Nb6 Rb8 14. f4 $1 {White needs to play energetically.} (14. Qf2 $2 Bxe4 $1 15.
fxe4 Ng4 16. Bxa6 {Otherwise, White would be simply worse after ...Nxe3.} Nxf2
17. Bb5+ Nc6 18. Bxc6+ Ke7 19. Nd5+ exd5 20. Bxf2 dxe4 21. O-O-O Qc7 22. Bxe4
g6 23. Rhe1 Bg7 24. Bxg6+ Kf8 25. Bd3 Re8 $17) 14... Bxe4 15. fxe5 Bxh1 16.
Qxa6 Nc6 {Parrying Na5.} 17. O-O-O Be7 18. exd6 Bxg5 19. Bxg5 (19. d7+ Kf8 20.
Bxg5 Qxg5+ 21. Kb1 g6 $17) 19... Qxg5+ 20. Kb1 O-O 21. Nd7 Ra8 $5 22. Qb5 Qg4
23. Be2 Bf3 24. Bxf3 Qxf3 25. Rf1 Na7 26. Rxf3 Nxb5 27. Nxf8 Kxf8 $11) (9. Qd2
{allows} Ne5 10. Be2 h5 $1 11. g5 (11. gxh5 Nc4 12. Bxc4 bxc4 13. Nd4 Rxh5 14.
O-O-O Qc7 $132 {With all the major pieces ready to join the slow queenside
attack, Black has a good position, despite the relatively undesirable capture
on c4 with a pawn.}) 11... Ng4 $1 $146 (11... Bb7 {Berelowitsch,A (2571)-David,
A (2591) BEL-chT 0506 2005 (11) 1-0} 12. f4 $1 Nc4 13. Bxc4 bxc4 14. Nd4 $16)
12. O-O-O (12. Bxg4 hxg4 $15) 12... Nxe3 13. Qxe3 {Strategically, Black is
doing fine after the exchange on e3, but he needs to catch up in development.}
Rb8 {Preparing both ...Qb6 and ...b5-b4. After the latter, the b6-square would
be defended.} 14. Kb1 (14. f4 Qb6 15. Qd2 b4 16. Na4 Qc7 17. Qxd6 Qxd6 18. Rxd6
Ng6 $11) 14... b4 (14... Qb6 15. Qd2 $16) 15. Na4 Qc7 16. Nd2 Bd7 17. b3 (17.
Nc4 Ng6 18. b3 e5 $11 {highlights the weakness on f4.}) 17... d5 18. Bxa6 g6
19. Qd4 {White needs to fight for the initiative, as otherwise, Black would
have just great play on dark squares.} e5 20. Qc5 Nc6 21. Qxd5 Be6 22. Qd3 Rd8
23. Qe3 Nd4 24. Bc4 Be7 {Black has lost two pawns, but is ready to get castled
and has fantastic play on dark squares. Here is a possible continuation.} 25.
c3 bxc3 26. Qxc3 Qb7 27. Bxe6 fxe6 28. Qg3 O-O 29. Qxe5 Kh7 $1 {Play is
unclear, offering chances to both sides. The idea behind the last move is
revealed after} 30. Nc4 Nf3 31. Qxe6 {Without check.} Nxg5 32. Qe5 Nf3 33. Qc3
Qxe4+ 34. Qc2 Qg4 $44 {Black has a strong bishop and a clear advantage on the
kingside. White cannot advance his queenside pawns without exposing his king.})
(9. Qe2 {deprives the c3-knight of the e2-square.} Bd7 {Preparing the next
move.} 10. O-O-O (10. a3 Na5 $11) 10... b4 11. Na4 (11. Nb1 {is more passive
and time-consuming.} Qc7 12. N1d2 Nc8 13. f4 a5 14. Nd4 a4 15. Nb5 Qb8 16. Kb1
Be7 17. g5 {Rohonyan,K (2334)-Majdan,J (2284) Olympiad Women-38 2008 (9) 0-1}
O-O 18. h4 N8a7 19. Nxa7 Nxa7 20. Nc4 Bc6 $1 21. Nb6 Qb7 $1 22. Nxa8 Bxe4 23.
Rh2 b3 24. Qa6 bxc2+ 25. Rxc2 Bxc2+ 26. Kxc2 Qe4+ 27. Rd3 Rxa8 28. Bxa7 Bf8 29.
h5 g6 $44 30. h6 a3 31. b4 {The queen cannot take the pawn, as this would allow
...Rc8+ with a decisive attack.} Qxf4 32. Rxa3 d5 33. Ra4 e5 {with very
unclear play.}) 11... Nc8 12. Qd2 {Pranav, S (2124)-Himanshu, S (2408) Gujarat
op 2nd 2019 (3) 1-0} Qc7 13. f4 Rb8 14. g5 (14. e5 Nxe5 15. fxe5 Bxa4 16. exd6
Bxd6 17. Nc5 Bb5 18. Nxa6 Bxa6 19. Bxa6 O-O $15) 14... Nd8 {White loses the
knight without real compensation.} 15. Nac5 dxc5 16. Nxc5 Bxc5 17. Bxc5 e5 18.
f5 a5 $17) (9. Bg2 $2 {allows} Ne5 10. Nd2 N7g6 $17) (9. a3 {weakens the
defence of the knight on b3 and the queenside in general.} Bb7 10. f4 Na5 $1
11. Nxa5 Qxa5 12. Bg2 Nc6 (12... d5 13. O-O Rd8 $11) 13. O-O Qc7 (13... Be7 14.
g5 Qc7 {Ivanovic,M (2262)-Perunovic,M (2542) SRB-ch 17th Senta 2023 (8) 0-1}
15. Qh5 $16) 14. g5 g6 15. f5 (15. Qd2 Bg7 16. f5 Ne5 17. f6 Bf8 $15) 15... Ne5
16. Bd4 (16. f6 h6 17. h4 hxg5 18. hxg5 d5 $19) 16... Be7 17. fxe6 fxe6 18. Bh3
Bc8 19. Qd2 Bd7 20. Rad1 Rf8 21. Rxf8+ Bxf8 22. Rf1 O-O-O $11) (9. h4 Rb8 $1
$146 {Defending the b6-square before the knight emerges on a4.} (9... Bb7 10.
Rh3 Nc8 11. Qe2 Na5 12. O-O-O Nxb3+ 13. axb3 Be7 14. f4 b4 15. Na4 $16 {
Kulon,K (2290)-Tsirulnik,M (2121) EU-ch (Women) 23rd 2023 (5) 1-0}) (9... b4
10. Na4 Rb8 11. Qe2 Bd7 12. O-O-O $16) 10. f4 (10. Qe2 Ne5 11. O-O-O Nc4 $132)
10... b4 11. Na4 (11. Ne2 d5 12. e5 h5 13. Ned4 hxg4 14. Qxg4 a5 15. h5 a4 16.
Nxc6 Nxc6 17. Nd4 Nxd4 18. Bxd4 Qa5 19. Rh3 Ba6 20. Bxa6 Qxa6 21. O-O-O Rc8 $11
) 11... Bd7 12. Qd3 (12. Qe2 e5 13. O-O-O Nd4 $13) 12... e5 {Preparing ...Nd4.}
13. O-O-O (13. f5 Nd4 14. c3 Bb5 15. Qd1 Ndxf5 $13) 13... Bxg4 (13... Nd4 $2
14. fxe5 dxe5 15. Bxd4 exd4 16. Nac5 $18) 14. Be2 exf4 15. Bxf4 Ng6 16. Bxg4
Nxf4 17. Qxa6 Ne5 18. Nd4 Qc7 19. Nb5 Qc6 20. Nxd6+ Bxd6 21. Qxc6+ Nxc6 22.
Rxd6 Ne5 {White has got the best possible out of his advance in development,
but Black retains adequate compensation for the pawn, due to his better
structure and the active knights.} 23. Rf1 $5 (23. Bd1 Ke7 $11) 23... Nfg6 24.
Bh5 Ke7 25. Rd5 f6 26. Rc5 Rhd8 $44) 9... g5 $1 {The critical continuation,
