{[%evp 0,64,13,17,37,37,45,35,35,29,35,51,51,56,48,46,46,15,15,3,4,0,8,0,10,14,
4,2,2,26,21,0,38,12,34,50,74,54,64,53,53,50,56,42,42,18,13,13,13,13,1,-4,-9,1,
7,-8,-14,-31,-34,-20,-20,-34,0,-40,-17,-17,-24]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4
4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Be3 {This flexible developing move is critical in
several Sicilian variations. In the Najdorf and the Scheveningen systems, it
usually is an introduction to the dangerous English Attack, while in the
Dragon is the absolute main line, introducing the Rauzer Attack. All these
lines are based on f2-f3 and g2-g4.} Nf6 {Unlike after the committal 6.g4,
Black does not have anything better than transposing to a proper Scheveningen.}
({Given the flexibility of 6.Be3, which does not create an obligation to
continue with g2-g4,} 6... Nge7 $6 {is less adequate.} 7. f4 a6 8. Be2 {
White switches to the classical system. With the pawn on d7, the Taimanov
Paulsen is playable, but in the actual position, Black is likely to run into
problems.} Nxd4 (8... b5 9. f5 Nxd4 10. Bxd4 $1 Nc6 11. fxe6 $1 Bxe6 {After 11.
..fxe6, 12.Bh5+ is annoying.} 12. O-O Ne5 13. a4 b4 14. Nd5 $16 {with
considerable advance in development.}) 9. Qxd4 b5 (9... Nc6 10. Qb6 $16) 10. a4
Nc6 11. Qd2 b4 12. Na2 Rb8 {Ostermeyer,P-Jansa,V Zonal Reykjavik 1975 (5) 1/
2-1/2} 13. b3 Be7 14. O-O-O O-O 15. Kb1 Qc7 16. g4 $16) 7. Qd2 (7. f3 Be7 8. g4
Nd7 {is likely to transpose.}) (7. f4 {is examined in Lines 33 to 38.}) (7. Be2
{transposes to the classical system, examined in the Lines 39 to 52.}) (7. Bc4
{transposes to the Sozin Attack, examined in Lines 53 to 57.}) 7... Be7 (7...
Ng4 {is premature due to} 8. Bg5) 8. f4 {A rare continuation.} (8. O-O-O {
allows} Ng4 9. Ndb5 (9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. Bf4 e5 11. Bg3 Be6 $11) 9... a6 10. Nxd6+
Bxd6 11. Qxd6 Qxd6 12. Rxd6 Nxe3 13. fxe3 Ke7 14. Rd2 b5 {Black has obvious
compensation for the pawn.} 15. Be2 Ne5 16. Rhd1 Bb7 (16... Bd7 $5 {
over defending b5 and preparing to sustain a queenside attack, is also good.})
17. Rd4 Bc6 18. a4 Rhb8 19. axb5 axb5 20. b4 Be8 {Threatening ...Nc6.} 21. Rd6
Nc4 {This leads to clear equality.} ({Black's position is so solid that he
could play any neutral move, including} 21... h5 $5 $11 {possibly followed by .
..f7-f6 (and surely by ...h5-h4 if allowed), since} 22. Bxh5 $2 {runs into} Rc8
{White cannot defend the knight because of ...Nc4+.} 23. Nb1 Ra2 24. c3 Nc4 25.
R6d2 Ra1 $19) 22. Bxc4 bxc4 23. R6d4 (23. b5 Bxb5 $5 24. Nxb5 Rxb5 25. Rd7+ Kf6
26. Rf1+ Rf5 $5 27. exf5 Ra1+ 28. Kb2 Rxf1 29. fxe6 fxe6 $11) 23... Rxb4 24.
Kd2 Ra5 25. Rb1 Rxb1 26. Nxb1 {The pawn on b5 is in danger, but White, too,
has problems on the other half of the board.} Rh5 27. h3 Rg5 28. g4 h5 $11 {
Ni, H (2701)-Timofeev, A (2681) CHN-RUS Summit Men 6th Rapid 2009 (7) 1/2-1/2}) (
8. f3 {is the main continuation, examined in Lines 26 to 32.}) 8... Ng4 {
In the Scheveningen systems based on ...Nc6 rather than ...a7-a6, Black is
well developed and can think of such active moves at an early stage. These
positions are bordering the Classical Sicilian, of course. The last move
prepares the typical central break ...e6-e5.} (8... e5 9. Nf3 (9. Nb3 Ng4 $11
10. Bg1 exf4 11. Qxf4 Bg5 12. Qf3 O-O $19) 9... Ng4 {is a less effective move
order, since} 10. O-O-O $1 {leaves Black behind in development.} Nxe3 11. Qxe3
exf4 12. Qxf4 O-O 13. Nd5 $16) 9. Bg1 Nxd4 10. Qxd4 O-O 11. O-O-O (11. Qd2 e5
12. O-O-O {transposes below.} (12. h3 $2 Bh4+ 13. Kd1 Nf6 $17)) 11... e5 12.
fxe5 (12. Qd2 exf4 13. Kb1 Bf6 14. h3 (14. Qxd6 Qxd6 15. Rxd6 Be5 16. Rd2 Be6
$11) (14. Qxf4 $6 {may be answered with} Bxc3 15. bxc3 Be6 16. Rxd6 Qa5 17. Bd4
Qxa2+ 18. Kc1 Rfd8 {with initiative.}) 14... Ne3 15. Bxe3 fxe3 16. Qxe3 Be6 17.
Nd5 Be5 $11 {With such a dominating dark-squared bishop, Black does not have
anything to complain about, of course.}) 12... Nxe5 {Black has achieved his
first aim, occupying e5 with the knight. This is a typical Scheveningen
structure, but here we have a couple of contradictory details. It may seem
that White is better developed and exerts pressure in the centre, but his
dark-squared bishop and king's rook still need to get into play.} 13. Be2 {
A bit unnatural, since it develops an already active piece, but the most
restrictive continuation.} ({The neutral} 13. Kb1 {allows} Bg4 {, solving
Black's developing problems.} 14. Rd2 (14. Re1 Bh4 $11) (14. Be2 Bxe2 15. Nxe2
Bf6 16. Qxd6 Qxd6 17. Rxd6 Nc4 $11) 14... Nc6 $5 {White can maintain the
pressure on d6 in order to prevent ...Bg5 and ...Bf6 only by agreeing to a
move repetition.} 15. Qd3 (15. Qa4 Bg5 $11) 15... Ne5 16. Qb5 Bg5 $11) (13. Nd5
Bg5+ 14. Kb1 Bg4 15. Re1 Qa5 $132) 13... Be6 14. Kb1 {A useful prophylactical
move, anticipating a later ...Bg5(+).} (14. Nd5 {can be answered with} Nc6 (
14... Bxd5 $2 15. Qxd5 $16 {Whitehead, P (2320)-Christiansen, L (2520) CalChess
Masters 1983 (8) 1-0 is passive for Black. The white queen enjoys great
perspectives in the centre while being absolutely safe.}) 15. Qd2 (15. Nxe7+
Qxe7 {improves Black's development.} 16. Qxd6 {Otherwise, ...Rfd8 followed by .
..d6-d5 might yield Black the initiative, while the pawn on a2 could also
become an issue.} Qg5+ 17. Qd2 Qxg2 18. Bc5 Rfd8 $11) (15. Qd3 Re8 16. Kb1 Bf6
17. Nxf6+ Qxf6 18. Qxd6 Rad8 19. Qg3 Bf5 20. exf5 Rxe2 21. Rxd8+ Qxd8 22. Be3
Qd5 $36) 15... Bg5 16. Be3 (16. Ne3 $2 Bxa2 $17 17. b3 $2 Qf6 $19) 16... Bxe3
17. Qxe3 Re8 $11 {After the bishops' exchange, Black does not have the least
problem. He could consider taking on d5 at any time, but does not need to
hurry with it.}) 14... Re8 {A constructive developing move, over defending the
bishop, putting latent pressure on e4 and preparing ...Bf8 for certain cases.}
15. Nd5 (15. Bb5 Nc6 {is fine for Black.} 16. Qa4 (16. Qd2 Qa5 $11) 16... Rc8 (
16... a6 $5 17. Bxc6 bxc6 18. Qxc6 Rc8 19. Qxa6 Rxc3 20. bxc3 Qc7 {Black has
fantastic compensation for the exchange. Since ...Bg5+ is an issue in many
lines,} 21. h4 {seems to be the only move keeping White in the game.} Bf8 $44
22. Bd4 Rb8+ 23. Kc1 Bc4 24. Qa7 Rb7 25. Qa4 d5 $36) 17. Nd5 a6 18. Be2 Bxd5
19. Rxd5 (19. exd5 Ne5 $15 {is very pleasant for Black, who does not have
problems on d6 anymore. Besides, White's coordination is imperfect.}) 19... Bf6
$11 {Black is well developed and has excellent chances for counterplay.}) 15...
Nc6 $5 $146 {To my understanding, it is useful to drive the enemy queen away
from its optimal square. White faces a wide, but uneasy choice.} (15... Bf8 {
Fleck, J (2365)-Ginsburg, M (2395) ECI 10th Jubilee 1983 (3) 1/2-1/2} 16. Bb5 $14
) ({The engines have a slight preference for} 15... a6 $5 $146 {, but
personally, I do not find Black's position easy to play at the end of the line.
} 16. Bf2 (16. Nxe7+ Rxe7 $11 17. Qxd6 $2 Rd7 $19) (16. Nb6 Rb8 17. Bf2 Nd7 18.
Nd5 Bf8) 16... Rc8 (16... Bg5 17. Qb4 b5 18. Bb6 Qd7 19. Nc7 $16) 17. Nxe7+
Qxe7 18. Qxd6 Qf6 19. Bg3 Nc4 $11 {Engines claim equality, which may be true,
but I prefer to have the e5-square just for myself. It may be a question of
style.}) 16. Qe3 (16. Qd2 Bg5 $11 {is comfortable for Black, for instance} 17.
Qe1 Bxd5 18. exd5 Nb4 $5) (16. Nxe7+ Rxe7 $11 17. Qxd6 $2 Rd7 $19) (16. Qf2 {
Prevents ...Bf6, but is unnatural.} Bxd5 ({Engines may be right that} 16... Rc8
17. c3 Bh4 18. g3 Bf6 19. Nxf6+ gxf6 {is equal. White has weakened his light
squares and his regrouping is imperfect. Black may continue with ...Ne5 and ...
Qa5. Optically, I remain a bit skeptical, though.}) 17. exd5 (17. Rxd5 Bf6 18.
Qe3 Qe7 $11) 17... Ne5 18. h4 $5 {Restricting the black bishop and allowing a
later rook lift to h3.} (18. g4 Bh4 $11) 18... Qc8 {Preventing g2-g4.} 19. Qg3
Bf6 20. Bd4 Nd7 21. Bg4 (21. Bb5 Be5 22. Qg4 Rd8 23. h5 Bxd4 24. Rxd4 Ne5 25.
Qf4 h6 26. Rh3 a6 27. Rc3 Qxc3 28. bxc3 axb5 $11) 21... Bxd4 22. Qxd6 (22. Rxd4
Qc7 $11) 22... Bxb2 (22... Bf6 23. Qxd7 Qc4 $44) 23. Bxd7 (23. Qxd7 Qc4 24.
Kxb2 Rad8 25. Qf5 Qb4+ 26. Kc1 Qa3+ $11 27. Kd2 $4 Qe3#) (23. Kxb2 Nb6 $1 24.
Qxb6 Qxg4 $11) 23... Be5 $5 $11) 16... Bf6 {The most consistent.} (16... Bxd5
17. Rxd5 Bf6 18. Bf2 $14) (16... Bg5 17. Qf2 Bxd5 18. exd5 Ne5 19. h4 Bf6 20.
g4 $36) 17. Bf2 (17. Nxf6+ Qxf6 $11 18. Rxd6 $2 Bxa2+ $19) 17... Be5 {Black
has completed his regrouping and has good play, despite White's space
advantage.} 18. a3 $5 {A generally useful move, taking measures against ...
b7-b5 among others.} (18. Rhf1 b5 $5 (18... Qa5 19. a3 b5 20. Be1 $14) 19. Bxb5
Rb8 $1 $132 20. Bxc6 (20. a4 Bxb2 21. Kxb2 a6 22. c4 Ne5 $36) 20... Rxb2+ $1 (
20... Bxb2 $11 {threatens to both win the queen and deliver a perpetual check.}
21. c3 Bxc3+ 22. Kc2 Be5 23. Bxe8 Qxe8 $44) 21. Kc1 Qc8 22. Ba4 Bxd5 23. Rxd5 (
23. exd5 Bc3 24. Qd3 Rxa2 $19) 23... Rxa2 24. Bb3 Ra1+ 25. Kd2 Rxf1 $19) (18.
Rhe1 {deprives White of a later Be1, allowing} Qa5 19. a3 b5 $132) 18... Rb8 $5
{Black intends to advance his b-pawn anyway.} (18... b5 $2 {does not work with
the pawn on a3.} 19. Bxb5 Rb8 20. Bxc6 $1 Rxb2+ (20... Bxb2 21. Nb4 $18) 21.
Kc1 Qc8 22. Ba4 Bxd5 23. Rxd5 Ra2 {This move does not attack the bishop
anymore.} 24. Kd2 $18) (18... Rc8 {is natural, but less to the point.} 19. Rhf1
Qa5 20. Qb3) 19. Rhf1 (19. Rd2 Qa5 $11) 19... b5 20. Bg3 Rb7 21. Rd2 Qb8 22. b3
Bxd5 23. Rxd5 Bxg3 24. Qxg3 Ne5 25. Rfd1 Rb6 {White seems to retain some
pressure, but Black is solid and his knight is very stable. If the position opens,
the white king is not that secure.} 26. Qe3 h6 27. g4 a6 28. Qd2 Qb7 (28... Re6
$5 29. h4 Rc6 30. g5 Qb6 $13) 29. g5 (29. Rxd6 Rxd6 30. Qxd6 Qxe4 $11) (29. h4
Rc6 {possibly followed by ...Rec8.}) 29... hxg5 30. Qxg5 Rc6 31. h4 Rc5 32.
Rxd6 (32. Rg1 g6 33. h5 Rxd5 34. exd5 Qe7 35. Qg3 Kg7 $11) 32... Qxe4 $13 *

