{[%evp 0,52,17,10,37,45,45,35,35,35,35,56,62,52,48,46,41,41,52,52,38,29,37,36,
36,33,35,35,45,38,26,21,51,24,13,14,41,50,26,-143,-143,-113,-91,-114,-72,-166,
-135,-72,59,34,39,-33,-33,-72,-69]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6
5. Nc3 d6 6. Be3 Nf6 7. Qd2 Be7 8. f3 {The starting point of the English
Attack.} O-O 9. O-O-O ({White does not achieve much by committing himself
before evacuating the king from the centre.} 9. g4 a6 10. g5 Nd7 11. h4 Nxd4
12. Bxd4 b5 13. Rg1 b4 14. Na4 Bb7 $11 {Black will have a choice between ...
Bc6 and ...d6-d5.}) 9... a6 {One may argue that the combination between ...Nc6
and ...a7-a6 is not very modern. I would answer that at a certain moment, it
was part of Kasparov's repertoire. Besides, combining natural development with
the usual queenside expansion cannot be wrong.} (9... d5 {is quite popular,
but after having lost a tempo with his d-pawn, Black remains under certain
pressure.}) 10. g4 Nd7 {It is a matter of move order, this one being a bit
more restrictive.} 11. h4 {The most consistent continuation, preparing the
advance of the g-pawn under safe circumstances.} (11. g5 Nxd4 12. Qxd4 (12.
Bxd4 Bxg5 13. f4 e5 14. fxg5 exd4 15. Nd5 Ne5 16. h4 Be6 17. Qxd4 Rc8 18. Kb1
Bxd5 19. Qxd5 Qb6 $11 20. Qxd6 $2 Rfd8 $19) 12... Bxg5 (12... b5 13. h4 {
is not an exact transposition to the main line.}) 13. f4 Be7 14. Rg1 g6 15. h4
e5 $5 $146 16. Qd2 exf4 17. Bxf4 Nf6 18. Be2 Be6 19. h5 Rc8 $132 {The
permanent threat ...Rxc3 reduces White's attacking potential.}) 11... Nxd4 {
A necessary exchange, in order to prepare the next move.} 12. Qxd4 {White
activates his queen, defending b4 and maintaining the pressure on d6. On the
other hand, the queen is exposed in the centre.} (12. Bxd4 {is examined in
Lines 27 to 32.}) 12... Ne5 {The secret behind Black's move order. He
continues to activate his knight with a gain of time, taking advantage of the
fact that f3-f4 is not possible yet.} 13. Be2 b5 14. Kb1 {Necessary
prophylaxis, as a direct consequence of the knight's presence on e5.} (14. f4 {
runs into} Nc6 15. Qb6 (15. Qd2 $6 Qa5 $1 16. a3 b4 17. Nb1 Bb7 $19) 15... Qe8
16. Bf2 (16. Qc7 b4 17. Na4 d5 {[%cal Ge7d8,Gd8e7]} 18. exd5 $2 exd5 $19) 16...
b4 17. Na4 e5 18. f5 Rb8 19. Qe3 Nd4 20. b3 Bd7 21. Nb2 Nxe2+ 22. Qxe2 Bb5 23.
Qf3 Rc8 24. g5 Rc3 25. Nd3 Qc6 $17) (14. g5 {allows the same.} Nc6 15. Qb6 (15.
Qd2 Qa5 16. a3 Rb8 17. Na2 b4 $15) 15... Qd7 (15... Qe8 16. Qc7 $14) 16. Bf2
Rb8 17. Qe3 Qc7 18. Kb1 Bd7 19. f4 {Elias,B (1752)-Quaresma,L (2401) POR-Cup18
H email 2010 1/2-1/2} b4 20. Na4 Na5 21. Nb6 Bb5 22. Bxb5 axb5 23. h5 Nc4 24.
Nxc4 bxc4 25. g6 Bf6 $11) 14... Bb7 15. g5 Nc6 {The same idea, even though
White is better prepared against it.} 16. Qd2 (16. Qb6 $146 Qxb6 17. Bxb6 Rfc8
18. Rhg1 Ne5 $11) 16... Qa5 17. a3 (17. Bd3 {Bozanic,I (2240)-Golubovic,B 
(2385) Pula op 10th 1996 0-1} b4 18. Ne2 d5 $132 19. exd5 Ne5 $1 20. Nf4 Nxd3
21. Qxd3 Rad8 22. Qe4 Rfe8 $11) 17... Rfc8 $1 $146 {This move not only
strengthens the queenside pressure but also clears the f8-square for the
bishop.} ({The natural} 17... Rac8 $6 {Sorensen,V (1680)-Degerfeldt,S (1935)
Helsingor Xtracon op 2017 (4) 0-1} {may run into} 18. h5 b4 19. axb4 Nxb4 20.
h6 g6 21. Qd4 e5 22. Qb6 $16) (17... b4 {is premature.} 18. axb4 Qxb4 (18...
Nxb4 19. Bc4 $16 {This is why Black needs a rook on c8 before breaking on the
queenside.}) 19. Na2 $5 $14 {AFter Black has weakened his queenside structure,
the position without queens favours White.}) 18. h5 b4 19. Nd5 $1 {White's
best chance.} (19. axb4 Nxb4 20. h6 {is ineffective due to} Bf8 $17 {with a
very strong attack.}) (19. Na2 bxa3 20. Qxa5 Nxa5 $15) 19... exd5 20. exd5 Ne5
(20... bxa3 21. dxc6 Qxd2 22. Rxd2 Rxc6 23. b3 d5 $11) 21. h6 (21. axb4 Qc7 22.
h6 g6 $17 23. f4 Nc4 24. Qd4 Bf8 $17) 21... Qa4 $5 (21... g6 $2 22. f4 Nd7 (
22... Nc4 23. Qd4 $18) 23. axb4 Qc7 24. Bg4 $16) (21... Bf8 $5 $13) 22. hxg7
Bxd5 23. Bd3 Nxd3 24. Qxd3 Qxc2+ $1 {Simplifying to an equal endgame.} 25. Qxc2
Rxc2 26. Kxc2 (26. Rxd5 Re2 27. Bd4 bxa3 28. bxa3 Rb8+ $132) 26... Bxf3 $11 *

