0,0,0]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Be3 Nf6 7. Qd2
Be7 8. f3 O-O 9. O-O-O a6 10. g4 Nd7 11. h4 Nxd4 12. Bxd4 {The most natural
and popular capture. White targets g7 and keeps his queen safe, but after
Black's next move, ...b5-b4 will be a threat.} b5 ({The same plan as in the
previous line,} 12... Ne5 {does not make sense now, since White can defend the
pawn with the flexible} 13. Qf2 $16 {threatening to both win a piece with Bxe5
and block the queenside pawns with Bb6.}) 13. Kb1 {A prophylactical move,
defending a2 in anticipation of ...b5-b4, Na4 ...Qa5, b2-b3 ...Nc5. White has
tried several other continuations.} (13. Bd3 $6 {exposes the bishop and
obstructs the d-file.} Ne5 $1 $146 {There is no drawback of this move now.} 14.
Qf2 Bd7 $15 {Parrying Bxe5 followed by Bxb5. With the pawn on b5, the enemy
bishop's intrusion into b6 is not dangerous. From d7, the black bishop controls
a4, reinforcing the threat ...b5-b4. Besides, after a2-a3, Black could prepare
...a7-a5, maintaining his pawn attack going.}) (13. Qf2 {is the start of a
harmonious regrouping, but offers Black a tempo for developing his attack.} Qa5
14. Kb1 b4 15. Ne2 e5 $1 {With the knight gone from c3, this ensures Black the
needed stability in the centre.} (15... Nc5 {allows the white knight to step
closer to the d5-square with} 16. Nf4 $14) 16. Be3 Nc5 17. Ng3 (17. Nc1 Be6 18.
g5 Qb6 19. h5 a5 20. g6 {Nowacki,A (2055)-Niedzwiedz,M (2061) POL-chT U19 2nd
League 2007 (5) 1-0} a4 21. Bh3 Qc6 $13) 17... Be6 18. b3 Rfc8 19. Nf5 Bf8 20.
Bxc5 (20. Nxd6 $2 Na4 $1 21. bxa4 Qxa4 22. Nxc8 Qxa2+ 23. Kc1 Rxc8 24. Bd3 b3
25. Kd2 Rxc2+ 26. Bxc2 bxc2 27. Bc5 cxd1=Q+ 28. Kxd1 Qb1+ 29. Ke2 Qb5+ {
Jamrich,G (2295)-Peredy,F (2305) Budapest FS12 IM 1996 (3) 0-1}) 20... Rxc5 21.
Ne3 Rac8 22. Bc4 {Degraeve,J (2375)-Wojtkiewicz,A (2550) Ostend op 1990 1-0}
Rxc4 $1 {Ending White's hopes to establish a blockade on light squares.} 23.
bxc4 Rxc4 24. Nxc4 Bxc4 25. c3 bxc3 26. Qc2 {Black has obvious compensation
for the two exchanges. Any neutral move would maintain the situation, but for
practical reasons, it makes sense to force the matters a bit.} d5 (26... g6 $11)
27. Rxd5 $1 (27. exd5 Ba3 28. Rh2 Bb2 $19) 27... Bxd5 28. exd5 Qb5+ (28... Qxd5
29. Qxc3 e4 $44) 29. Ka1 (29. Qb3 Qd3+ 30. Qc2 Qxf3 31. Re1 g6 $44) 29... Qxd5
30. Qxc3 e4 $44) (13. a3 {is examined in Line 28.}) ({For} 13. h5 {see Line 29.
}) (13. g5 {is the subject of Lines 30 to 32.}) 13... b4 14. Na4 (14. Ne2 {
is more passive.} Ne5 15. f4 (15. Rh3 a5 16. f4 Nxg4 17. Rg3 e5 18. Bh3 {
Kubala,L (2245)-Kolek,P (2393) SVK-ch21 final email 2011 1-0} Nf6 $19) (15. Qe3
Qc7 16. Qf2 a5 17. g5 a4 18. f4 Nc4 19. f5 e5 20. f6 Bd8 21. fxg7 Re8 22. Be3 {
Kollen,Z (2118)-Warmelink,E (2058) Borne Euro Chess op-A 2011 (5) 1/2-1/2} Be6
23. g6 hxg6 24. h5 b3 $19) 15... Nxg4 16. Rg1 e5 17. Bh3 {Chandler,M (2505)
-Arnason,J (2470) Olympiad-27 Dubai 1986 (8) 1-0} Nh2 $1 {Threatening ...Nf3.}
18. Qd3 exd4 19. Bxc8 Rxc8 20. Rg2 Re8 21. Rxh2 Bf8 22. Qxd4 a5 $11) 14... a5 {
Defending b4.} ({With the king on b1,} 14... Qa5 $2 {does not work out well.}
15. b3 Bb7 (15... Nc5 16. Nb2 d5 17. exd5 exd5 18. Nd3 Ne6 19. Bb2 d4 20. Bg2
Bb7 {Predojevic, B (2624)-Arakhamia Grant, K (2451) Olympiad-39 Khanty-Mansiysk
2010 (10.2) 1/2-1/2} 21. a4) 16. g5 Bc6 17. Nb2 d5 18. g6 $1 dxe4 (18... fxg6
19. Bh3 Nc5 20. h5 g5 21. h6 g6 22. Nd3 $18) (18... e5 19. Be3 Nf6 20. gxh7+
Kxh7 21. Qg2 Rad8 22. Rg1 Rg8 23. Qg5 $18 {Diaz,S (2385)-Giannetto,S (2410)
Champion's League 07/D5 email 2007 [1] 1-0}) (18... hxg6 19. h5 $18) 19. Nc4
Qh5 20. gxf7+ Rxf7 21. Bh3 $18 {Jaworski,M (2417)-Ciesielski,S (2574) POL-ch
50th email 2007 1-0}) 15. g5 (15. Bb5 {is a typical idea, trying to freeze the
queenside. The bishop's exposure allows Black to gain time for his counterplay,
though.} Rb8 16. Qe2 (16. c4 Qc7 17. g5 Nc5 {transposes below}) 16... Qc7 17.
b3 Qb7 18. Bc4 Ne5 19. Bxe5 (19. Nc5 Qc6 20. Bxe5 dxe5 21. Nd3 Qc7 22. Qh2 a4
23. Qxe5 Bd6) 19... dxe5 20. Nb2 Bc5 $132 {Severiukhina,Z (2321)-Oleksienko,M 
(2543) Voronezh op-A 14th 2010 (8) 0-1}) 15... Qc7 16. h5 (16. Bb5 Nc5 $146 17.
c4 (17. g6 fxg6 18. h5 h6 19. hxg6 Bg5 $13 {defends the kingside properly.})
17... e5 18. Be3 Rb8 {Threatening ...Rxb5.} 19. b3 Ne6 20. Qf2 f5 21. gxf6 Rxf6
22. Nb6 Bb7 $132 {A complicated position with mutual weaknesses and blockade.})
16... Nc5 {The only constructive way of fighting against the blockade.} 17. g6
(17. h6 g6 18. Nxc5 dxc5 19. Bf6 Bxf6 20. gxf6 Ba6 (20... Qe5 $2 21. Qd6 $1
Qxf6 22. e5 $1 Qg5 23. f4 $1 Qxf4 24. Qe7 Qxe5 25. Bg2 $18 {followed by Rd8.})
21. Bxa6 Rxa6 22. Qe2 Rc6 23. e5 c4 24. Rd4 a4 {Optically, White has some
advantage, but Black's queenside space advantage is an element, too.} 25. Rhh4
Qb6 (25... Rc8 $5) 26. Qd1 a3 27. Rxc4 Rxc4 28. Rxc4 Rd8 29. Qc1 Qb5 30. Re4
Qa5 31. Re3 axb2 32. Qf1 b3 $5 33. cxb3 Rc8 34. Qe2 Qc5 35. Qc4 Qf8 36. Qd4
Qxh6 $13) 17... h6 {The safest answer. Black does not need to clear kingside
files.} (17... fxg6 18. hxg6 h6 19. Qh2 $1 {Threatening to win a piece due to
the pin along the h2-b8 diagonal.} (19. Bxg7 $2 Bg5 $1 {keeps Black in the game.
} 20. Qxg5 Qxg7 (20... hxg5 21. Bxf8 $18) 21. Qc1 Nxa4 22. Rxd6 Rxf3 $13) 19...
Ra7 20. Bxg7 $1 $18) 18. Bxc5 (18. Nxc5 dxc5 19. Be3 Rd8 20. Qc1 (20. gxf7+
Kxf7 21. Qc1 Rxd1 22. Qxd1 a4 $13) 20... Rxd1 21. Qxd1 {Nechepurenko,R (2439)
-Seeman, T (2412) Moscow Aeroflot op-B 2006 (6) 1-0} fxg6 {After exchanging
several pieces and dismantling White's attacking mechanism, , this is possible.
} 22. hxg6 Ba6 $5 23. Bh3 Bc4 24. b3 Qe5 $1 25. bxc4 Rd8 26. Qe1 Bf6 27. c3
bxc3 28. Kc2 Qd6 29. Qd1 Bd4 $44 {The exposure of the white king compensates
for the sacrificed piece.}) 18... dxc5 19. Bc4 Ra7 ({This is more to the point
than} 19... Rb8 {, since the rook can be useful along the seventh rank, by
providing the king with the needed defence after a later ...Bf6.} 20. Rhf1 {
I admit that the course of the following correspondence game is not easy to
follow logically, but Black's problems were caused by not having the rook on
the seventh rank.} fxg6 (20... Qc6 21. gxf7+ Rxf7 22. Rg1 Kh8 23. Rg6 $16) 21.
hxg6 Qc6 22. Rh1 Rb7 (22... Ba6 23. Rxh6 $1 $18) 23. b3 Rxf3 24. Rdf1 $36 {
