1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Be3 Nf6 7. Qd2 Be7 8. f3
O-O 9. O-O-O a6 10. g4 Nd7 11. h4 Nxd4 12. Bxd4 b5 13. a3 {In the English
Attack, this move has to be permanently counted with. If Black has committed
himself strongly, the modest pawn's advance could leave his efforts at a dead
end. This is not the case when the black bishop is on c8, keeping the b-file
clear and making the attack with ...b5-b4 easier to organize.} Ne5 $1 {It
cannot harm to spoil White's coordination a bit.} (13... Rb8 $6 {is less
accurate, since the threat ...b5-b4 is not that strong.} 14. f4 Bb7 (14... b4
15. axb4 e5 {As revealed soon, it is best to drive the bishop away from d4
before taking on b4. If Black takes it at once, Nd5 will be even stronger.} (15...
Rxb4 16. Nd5 $16 Ra4 17. Nxe7+ Qxe7 18. b3 $18) 16. Be3 Rxb4 17. Nd5 Ra4 {
With the bishop on d4, White would have b2-b3 with a clear advantage.} (17...
Rxe4 18. Bg2 {speeds up White's development.} Ra4 19. b3 Ra1+ 20. Kb2 Rxd1 21.
Rxd1 Bxh4 22. g5 h6 23. gxh6 g6 24. f5 $40) 18. Kb1 $14) 15. g5 Nc5 16. Bg2 $6
{In vain weakening the pressure on b5.} (16. Rh3 $1 $16 Nxe4 17. Nxe4 Bxe4 18.
Bxg7 Kxg7 19. Qd4+) (16. Qe3 $5 $16) 16... a5 17. Bxc5 (17. Nxb5 Bxe4 18. Bxe4
Nxe4 19. Qd3 d5 20. h5 f6 21. g6 h6 $13) 17... dxc5 18. Qxd8 Rfxd8 19. Nxb5
Bxe4 20. Bxe4 Rxb5 $11 {Ponomariov,R (2727)-Kasparov,G (2838) Linares 19th
2002 (6) 1/2-1/2}) 14. Be2 (14. Qf2 Nc6 15. Bb6 Qd7 16. f4 Rb8 17. e5 d5 18.
Bc5 b4 {Black has strong initiative already.} 19. axb4 Nxb4 20. Rh3 Bxc5 21.
Qxc5 Qb7 22. b3 Bd7 23. Rd2 Rfc8 24. Qa5 {Pikula,D (2455)-Arsovic,Z (2460)
YUG-ch Podgorica 1996 (13) 1/2-1/2} Qa7 $5 $19 {To his queenside worries,
White has to add the danger of a queen intrusion to g1.} 25. Rg3 Rc5 {
Revealing the second idea behind the last move.} 26. Qa3 Qc7 $19 {followed by .
..Rc8 with a decisive attack.}) ({In the event of} 14. f4 {Black should not
take on g4, since this would open the g-file for White's attack. Instead,} Nf3
$1 15. Qe3 Nxd4 {solves all his problems.} 16. Qxd4 Rb8 17. g5 Qb6 $11) 14...
Qa5 $5 $146 {In this position the move is new, but play may transpose later.} (
14... Nc6 15. Be3 Rb8 (15... Qa5 16. Kb1 b4 {transposes below}) 16. Na2 d5 (
16... a5 {De Pinho,J (2368)-Vostrotin,V (2332) W-ch28 sf09 email 2004 0-1} 17.
Kb1 $14) 17. exd5 exd5 $132 18. Qxd5 $2 Qxd5 19. Rxd5 Be6 $17) 15. g5 $5 (15.
Kb1 Nc6 16. Be3 b4 $132 17. axb4 (17. Na2 bxa3 18. Qxa5 Nxa5 19. b3 Bb7 $11)
17... Qxb4 18. Bg5 Rb8 19. b3 f6 20. Bf4 Ne5 21. Qd4 (21. Na2 Qb7 22. g5 a5 23.
gxf6 Rxf6 24. Bxe5 dxe5 25. Qxa5 Rf7 26. Qc3 Ra8 $36 {Krueger,H (2267)-Tsenkov,
L (2392) LSS WC-2012-S-00002 2009 0-1}) 21... Qa5 (21... a5 22. Bc1 Qb7 23. g5
Bd7 24. f4 Nc6 25. Qd2 Nb4 $132 {Borisovs,L (2207)-Matin,B (2255) LSS
CP-2007-Q-00005 2009 0-1}) 22. Bc1 Nc6 23. Qe3 Bd7 24. Bb2 Nb4 25. h5 Rfc8 26.
Rd2 h6 27. f4 Be8 28. f5 e5 29. Qa7 Qd8 30. Qe3 Bf7 $17 {Sadowski,M (2198)
-Calugaru,V (2354) LSS WC-2011-T-00005 2010 1/2-1/2}) 15... Nc6 16. Bf6 $1 $146
(16. Be3 b4 17. Nb1 Rb8 18. b3 d5 $1 $146 19. exd5 exd5 20. Qxd5 Qxd5 21. Rxd5
bxa3 22. Nc3 Be6 $17 {with strong initiative.}) (16. Kb1 Nxd4 17. Qxd4 {
The queen's presence in the centre ensures White only temporary initiative,
while the vulnerability of the dark squares persists.} Rb8 18. h5 b4 19. h6 e5
20. Qd5 Qb6 21. axb4 Qxb4 22. Qb3 Qxb3 23. cxb3 Be6 24. Bc4 Bxg5 25. Rxd6 (25.
Rdg1 Be3 26. Rxg7+ Kh8 27. Rg2 Rg8 $11) 25... Bxh6 26. Rxa6 Be3 27. Kc2 Bd4 $15
{Korneev,O (2619)-Komljenovic,D (2506) Dos Hermanas op 2000 (7) 0-1}) 16... b4
$1 {This partly spoils White's attacking mechansim.} (16... gxf6 $2 17. gxf6
Bxf6 18. Rhg1+ Kh8 19. Qh6 Qd8 20. Rxd6 $1 Qe7 21. Nd5 $1 {White has found all
the elements of the puzzle.} exd5 22. Rxf6 Rg8 23. Rxg8+ Kxg8 24. Rxc6 $18) 17.
axb4 (17. Na2 $2 {With the knight far from the kingside, the bishop on f6 is
edible.} gxf6 18. gxf6 Bxf6 19. Rhg1+ Kh8 20. Qh6 Qd8 21. Rxd6 Qe7 {There is
no Nd5 now to conclude White's attack.} 22. Rxc6 bxa3 23. Nc3 Bd4 $19 {It will
be Black who will have a decisive attack soon.}) (17. Bxe7 bxc3 18. Qxd6 Nxe7
19. Qxe7 Rb8 (19... cxb2+ $5 20. Kb1 Rb8 21. Rd3 Rb7 22. Qd6 Bd7 23. Rhd1 Ba4
$13) 20. b3 Rb7 21. Qd6 Rb6 $11 {with a draw by repetition, since the queen
needs to keep a3 defended.}) 17... Qa1+ 18. Nb1 gxf6 19. gxf6 Bxf6 20. Rhg1+
Kh8 21. c3 Nxb4 $1 22. Qh6 Na2+ 23. Kc2 (23. Kd2 Qxb2+ 24. Ke1 (24. Ke3 Qb6+
25. Kd3 Qd8 $19) 24... Bxc3+ 25. Nxc3 Qxc3+ 26. Kf2 Bb7 27. Rd3 Qb2 28. Rd2 Qc3
$11) 23... Nb4+ 24. Kd2 Qxb2+ 25. Ke3 (25. Ke1 Bxc3+ 26. Nxc3 Qxc3+ 27. Kf2 Bd7
$19) 25... Nc2+ 26. Kd3 (26. Kf2 $2 Qb6+ 27. Kf1 Ne3+ (27... Qd8 28. Rxd6 Qe7
$19) 28. Ke1 Qd8 29. Rxd6 Bxh4+ (29... Qe7 $19) 30. Kd2 Qxd6+ $19) 26... Nb4+
27. Ke3 Nc2+ $11 {with a draw by perpetual.} *

