e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Be3 Nf6 7. Qd2 Be7 8. f3 O-O 9. O-O-O a6
10. g4 Nd7 11. h4 Nxd4 12. Bxd4 b5 13. h5 $5 {This is a cunning alternative to
13.g5, examined later. It may seem that it does not matter which pawn White
advances first, but it does.} h6 $5 {Played only once, this seems to me the
most reliable continuation. It takes advantage of the specific move order and
prevents White from doing so. White is kindly invited to come up with an
attacking plan after the kingside structure has been partly blocked.} ({
The deep point behind h4-h5 is revealed after} 13... b4 14. Na4 Qa5 15. b3 Nc5
16. a3 Nxa4 17. axb4 Qc7 18. h6 $1 g6 19. bxa4 {With the g7-square under
certain pressure, Black does not have enough compensation for the pawn.} Bd7 (
19... e5 20. a5 $1 $14 exd4 21. Qxd4 f6 22. Qd5+ $18) 20. a5 Rfc8 21. c4 Bb5 {
In any similar position without h5-h6 on board, this would yield Black
dangerous initiative, but here it runs into} 22. Qc3 $16 Bxc4 $2 23. Bb6 $18)
14. Be3 $146 {Starting to prepare g4-g5.} (14. a3 Rb8 15. Be3 Ne5 16. Be2 f6
17. f4 Nf7 $11 {[%cal Gc8d7] with similar play as below.}) (14. Kb1 Bb7 15. f4
b4 16. Na4 e5 $1 {The best way of taking advantage of the weakness on e4.} (
16... Bxe4 {A bit premature.} 17. Bg2 Bxg2 (17... Bh7 18. Bxa8 Qxa8 19. Qxb4
Qc6 20. Nc3 Rb8 $44) 18. Qxg2 Qa5 19. b3 Rad8 {Ferrari,C (1685)-Ramos Correa,G
(1918) Montevideo Autumn op 2nd 2019 (2) 0-1} 20. g5 $18) 17. fxe5 dxe5 18. Be3
Nf6 $17) 14... Bb7 15. Rg1 Ne5 16. Be2 f6 {Preparing a harmonious regrouping.}
17. f4 Nf7 {Black has a very solid position and maintains the possibility of
advancing his queenside pawns. White does not have a clear way of carrying out
g4-g5. His main plan is based on f4-f5, weakening the d5-square.} 18. Bd3 (18.
f5 Qd7 19. fxe6 Qxe6 20. Nd5 Rae8 {Preparing a harmonious setup, while
maintaining the threat on e4 in reserve.} (20... Qxe4 {is also possible.}) 21.
Bd3 Bd8 $11) 18... Bc6 19. Kb1 Qc7 {Still preparing the queenside attack.} 20.
f5 e5 $1 (20... Qd7 {works less well now since after} 21. fxe6 Qxe6 22. Nd5 $14
{Black cannot complete his harmonious regrouping:} Rae8 $2 23. Nc7 $18) 21. Be2
{Preparing to maintain the piece control over d5.} Rfc8 22. Rc1 Qb7 23. Rgd1
Ng5 $5 (23... a5 24. Nd5 Bd8 $11) 24. Bxg5 hxg5 25. Nd5 Kh7 {[%cal Gh7h6]} 26.
