1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Be3 Nf6 7. Qd2 Be7 8. f3
O-O 9. O-O-O a6 10. g4 Nd7 11. h4 Nxd4 12. Bxd4 b5 13. g5 b4 14. Na4 Qa5 15. b3
Nc5 16. Nxc5 dxc5 17. Bb2 Rd8 18. Qh2 {Played only twice, this move induces
some differences with respect to the previous line.} Rxd1+ 19. Kxd1 Qd8+ 20.
Kc1 a5 ({The same method as in the main line does not work here.} 20... Bd7 21.
g6 $1 fxg6 22. h5 {Now is when the queen is useful on h2.} h6 23. hxg6 Qf8 24.
Bc4 Bf6 25. Be5 $16) 21. g6 $1 {Not tried yet, this is the most logical and
dangerous continuation. I can understand why it escaped the attention of the
correspondence players. At this moment, the engines think that several other
continuations offer a small pluss, while this is "completely equal".} (21. Qg3
a4 $132) (21. Bc4 $5 Ba6 {Black needs to exchange the active white bishop.} (
21... a4 $2 22. Rd1 Qb6 23. Qe5 Bf8 24. g6 hxg6 25. h5 $18) 22. Rd1 Qf8 23.
Bxa6 Rxa6 24. Be5 (24. Qc7 {Moll,R (2558)-Punzon Moraleda,J (2384) W-Cup14
final email 2009 1-0 is easier to meet.} Bd6 25. Qb7 Bf4+ 26. Kb1 Ra8 27. Qd7
h5 $5 28. gxh6 Bxh6 $11) 24... c4 25. bxc4 Rc6 26. Rd7 (26. Qe2 f6 27. gxf6
Bxf6 28. Bxf6 Qxf6 29. Kb1 Qxh4 $11) 26... Rxc4 27. Qe2 Rc6 28. Kb1 Rc5 29. f4
Qe8 30. Ra7 Bf8 31. h5 a4 32. Qa6 Qd8 {Due to his king's exposure, White
cannot display all the activity he would like.} 33. Qd3 Qe8 34. Rd7 Qa8 35. Bd6
Rc3 36. Qd4 Rh3 37. a3 Rh1+ 38. Kb2 bxa3+ 39. Kxa3 Rh3+ 40. Kb4 Rh1 41. Bxf8
Qxf8+ 42. Qd6 Rb1+ 43. Kc4 Rb8 44. Kc3 Qe8 45. Qe7 {Pokrivac,I (2152)-Kuteneva,
G (2180) BdF-Smaragd 06 email 2015 1/2-1/2}) (21. Be5 a4 22. Bb5 axb3 23. axb3
Qb6 24. Ba4 c4 $132) 21... hxg6 (21... fxg6 22. Bc4 $16) 22. h5 Bf6 23. Bxf6 (
23. e5 Bg5+ 24. f4 Bb7 (24... Bh6 25. hxg6 Bb7) 25. Rg1 (25. fxg5 Qxg5+ 26. Kb1
Bxh1 27. Qxh1 Rd8 28. Be2 gxh5 $11) 25... Bh6 26. hxg6 a4 27. gxf7+ Kxf7 $132)
(23. hxg6 Bxb2+ 24. Kb1 Qd1+ 25. Kxb2 Qd4+ $11) 23... Qxf6 24. e5 {Preventing .
..Qa1+.} Qg5+ 25. f4 Qh6 (25... Qxh5 $2 26. Qg2 $18) 26. Bg2 {The engines
suddenly change their mind sometime in this phase and claim a clear advantage
for White. This may be the reason why Black avoided this line in very recent
games, but once again engines are wrong.} Rb8 27. Qh4 Ba6 28. Bf3 {White has
sacrificed a pawn but retains consistent pressure.} gxh5 {The simplest way of
dealing with the tension.} ({The active} 28... c4 {is interesting, but at
least risky.} 29. Qg3 (29. bxc4 $2 {in vain provides the bishop with new
horizons.} Bxc4 30. Qg3 Bxa2 31. hxg6 Qxg6 32. Qh2 Qh6 33. Qd2 {This is
ineffective now since Black's back rank is defended.} Qg6 34. Qh2 Qh6 35. Qd2
b3 $5 {an interesting try if Black does not wish to make a draw at once.} 36.
Kb2 Qg6 37. Qh2 bxc2+ 38. Kxa2 c1=N+ $1 39. Rxc1 Qd3 40. Bd1 Qd5+ 41. Ka1 Qd4+
42. Ka2 Qd5+ 43. Ka3 Qd4 $11 {Black has good compensation for the piece anyway,
but it does not make much sense to refrain from the draw by repetition.}) 29...
cxb3 30. axb3 Bb7 (30... Rc8 31. Rh4 Bd3 32. c4 $1 $18) 31. hxg6 Qxg6 32. Qh2
Qh6 33. Qd2 {Due to the threat Bxb7 followed by Qd8#, Black has to sacrifice
the queen.} Qxh1+ 34. Bxh1 Bxh1 {This would be a comfortable position for
Black, if he was given a free tempo. After ...g7-g6 followed by ...Bd5, White
cannot be better. However, White can use the available tempo to create big
problems.} 35. f5 $1 exf5 (35... Rf8 36. f6 Be4 37. c4 bxc3 38. Qxc3 {is at
least incomfortable for Black.}) 36. e6 $1 fxe6 37. Qh2 Rb5 38. Qxh1 Rd5 {
With the f-pawn less advanced, this would be a simple fortress. I am not sure,
though, whether Black can hold after} 39. Qh5 {He will have to either give up
one of the pawns on g7 and e6 soon or allow the white king to get out. I
would be worried with black in this endgame.}) 29. Bxh5 Bb7 30. Rh3 (30. Rh2 {
offers Black additional possibilities.} g6 31. Qg3 Rd8 32. Bf3 Qxh2 $5 33. Qxh2
Bxf3 $11) 30... g6 31. Qg3 Qg7 32. Bf3 Bxf3 33. Qxf3 {The engines indicate a
clear advantage for White. However, they do not come up with any plan and only
move around with the pieces, maintaining the "advantage" intact after many
moves. Black has an extra pawn and a solid position, but the king remains
exposed and the queen is passive. The only thing he should be worried about is
the break with f4-f5, but he can take measures against it.} Re8 {With the rook
on e8, f4-f5, ...exf5 does not yield White anything.} 34. Qc6 Qf8 35. Kb2 Rc8
36. Qh1 Qg7 37. a4 {Clearing some space for the king.} (37. Qb7 Qf8 38. f5 {
runs into} Qd8 $11) 37... Rb8 {Preventing Qb7.} (37... bxa3+ $5) 38. Ka2 (38.
Qc6 Qf8 39. f5 {With the queen on the sixth rank, this break is not dangerous.}
exf5 40. e6 Re8 $11) 38... Re8 {The rook simply has to use the e8 and
b8-squares to keep Black out of trouble.} (38... Rc8 39. Kb1 Rb8 40. Kb2 Rc8
$2 (40... Re8 $1) 41. Qb7 Qf8 42. f5 $1 exf5 43. e6 Kg7 44. Qd5 $40) 39. Kb1
Rb8 40. Kb2 Re8 {I would evaluate this position as a "positional draw".} *

