{[%evp 0,50,20,31,52,45,56,44,44,44,49,49,86,65,63,38,49,15,32,24,13,31,31,31,
26,16,47,44,125,141,141,125,170,-40,-26,-14,-25,-29,-29,-34,-23,-83,-22,-23,
-16,-16,-16,-22,-22,-28,-29,-36,-27]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6
5. Nc3 d6 6. Be3 Nf6 7. f4 Be7 8. Qe2 {This rare move was mentioned by
Kasparov and Nikitin in their old book on the Scheveningen, published in
Russian in 1984. They write that its main merit is that there is almost no
theory behind it. Things did not change much but moves like Qe2 are tried in
several Sicilians, for instance in the 6.Bg5 Najdorf, too. Of course,
developing the queen in front of the bishop cannot cause Black serious
problems.} e5 (8... Nxd4 9. Bxd4 e5 $5 $146 {is worth investigating, too. The
main difference with respect to the similar position after 8.Qf3 is that White
does not have the molesting Bb5+.} 10. fxe5 dxe5 11. Bxe5 (11. Qb5+ Nd7 $11 12.
Bxe5 a6 13. Qd5 Nxe5 14. Qxe5 O-O 15. Rd1 Qe8 16. Qg3 Bf6 $15) 11... O-O $44 {
Due to White's problems completing his development, Black has good
compensation for the pawn.}) 9. Nf3 {Almost always played.} (9. Nf5 Bxf5 10.
exf5 exf4 11. Bxf4 d5 12. O-O-O O-O $11) (9. Nb3 exf4 10. Bxf4 Bg4 11. Qf2 Nh5
12. Bd2 Bf6 13. Bd3 O-O 14. O-O Be5 $11) 9... O-O 10. O-O-O Bd7 {Eliminating
the pin along the d-file and continuing the development.} 11. Kb1 Rc8 12. Qd2
Re8 $5 $146 {Black still prepares ...exf4.} (12... exf4 {is a bit premature.}
13. Bxf4 Be6 14. Be2 $14 {Wunderlich,H (2602)-Dothan,Y (2630) Ragozin Memorial
email 2008 1/2-1/2}) 13. f5 {A critical decision.} (13. Bc4 Na5 14. Bd3 Qc7 15.
Rhf1 a6 $11) (13. Be2 Qa5 (13... a6 $5 14. Rhe1 b5 $132) 14. Rhe1 exf4 15. Bxf4
Ne5 $11) 13... d5 $1 {Black should not delay his counterplay in the centre.}
14. exd5 (14. Nxd5 Nxe4 $17) 14... Nb4 15. d6 $1 {White has to defend
carefully.} (15. a3 $2 Bxf5 $1 16. axb4 Bxb4 $17 {yields Black a very strong
attack.} 17. Bd3 Bxd3 18. Qxd3 (18. cxd3 Nxd5 19. Rc1 Rc6 20. Rhe1 Ra6 $19)
18... Bxc3 19. Qb5 (19. bxc3 e4 $19) 19... Qa5 $17) 15... Bxf5 16. Bd3 $1 (16.
dxe7 $2 Qa5 17. Bd3 e4 $17) 16... e4 17. Nxe4 Nxd3 18. dxe7 Qxe7 19. Nxf6+ gxf6
20. Nh4 Bg4 21. Qxd3 Bxd1 22. Nf5 Bxc2+ 23. Qxc2 Rxc2 24. Nxe7+ Rxe7 25. Kxc2
Rxe3 $11 {Black's extra pawn does not count for much, unfortunately, but it
still is White who is struggling a bit.} *

