{[%evp 0,46,20,31,52,48,56,44,44,44,49,49,78,58,56,38,45,18,23,29,29,2,-26,-54,
-38,-60,-9,0,41,-12,28,-29,0,0,0,-39,2,2,22,-123,26,26,26,26,0,73,65,-73,-40]} 
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Be3 Nf6 7. f4 Be7 8. Qf3
{This is the most interesting and main continuation. Play will soon turn
fascinating. The reason why I mentioned the Kasparov and Nikitin book is that
I was curious to check how much was known about this line four decades ago.} e5
(8... Nxd4 9. Bxd4 e5 {runs into} 10. Bb5+ $1 (10. fxe5 dxe5 11. Bxe5 O-O $44)
10... Bd7 11. Bxd7+ Nxd7 12. Be3 Rc8 13. O-O exf4 14. Bxf4 Bf6 15. Nd5 Be5 16.
Qg4 O-O 17. Bxe5 dxe5 18. Rf2 $14) 9. Nf5 {This seemingly active move yields
Black active play in the centre.} (9. Nb3 {is most actively met with} Bg4 $5
$146 (9... exf4 10. Qxf4 O-O $11 {is also fine.}) 10. Qf2 (10. Qg3 O-O 11. h3
Nxe4 12. Qxg4 Bh4+ 13. g3 Bxg3+ 14. Kd1 f5 $17) 10... d5 11. fxe5 Nxe4 12. Nxe4
dxe4 $11) (9. Nde2 {may run into the same.} Bg4 $5 $146 (9... exf4 10. Nxf4 O-O
11. h3 Ne5 12. Qf2 {Bronstein, D-Furman, S Match/City Moscow-Leningrad 1965 1-0}
Be6 13. O-O-O Rc8 $13 14. Bxa7 $2 Rxc3 15. bxc3 Qa5 $19) 10. Qg3 O-O 11. O-O-O
Qa5 12. Kb1 Rfc8 $132) (9. fxe5 dxe5 (9... Nxe5 $6 10. Bb5+ $16) 10. Nf5 $6 (
10. Nxc6 bxc6 {Transposes to Line 36.}) 10... Bxf5 11. exf5 O-O $15 (11... Nd4
12. Bxd4 exd4 13. O-O-O {is given as good for White by Kasparov and Nikitin,
but Black is doing fine here, too.} O-O 14. Bc4 Qb6 15. Ne2 Rad8 $11) (11...
Qa5 12. O-O-O Bb4 13. Nd5 {Cocozza,M (2285)-Perry,R Olympiad-26 Thessaloniki
1984 (1) 1/2-1/2} Qxa2 $13 14. Nc7+ $2 Kf8 15. c3 Ba3 16. bxa3 Qxa3+ 17. Kc2
Qa2+ 18. Kc1 Na5 $19) 12. Ne4 (12. Rd1 Nd4 13. Bxd4 exd4 $19) 12... Qa5+ 13. c3
Rad8 $15 14. Bc4 Nd4 15. Nxf6+ Bxf6 16. Qe4 b5 17. Bd3 b4 $15 18. cxd4 $2 exd4
$19) (9. Nxc6 {is examined in Lines 36 to 38.}) 9... Bxf5 10. exf5 Nd4 {
This is the main drawback of the knight jump to f5. Black has gained time for
his development and got control over d4.} (10... Qa5 {is also good.}) 11.
Qd1 (11. Bb5+ {helps the king get onto a better square while exposing the
bishop a bit.} Kf8 12. Qd1 Nxf5 13. Bf2 h5 $1 (13... exf4 14. Qf3 $14 {Oral,T 
(2503)-Svoboda,V (2426) CZE-chT 1617 2016 (6.3) 1-0}) 14. O-O (14. fxe5 dxe5
15. Qxd8+ Bxd8 $17) ({With the king on e8} 14. Bd3 {would be good, but here
Black has} Qd7 $15 {[%cal Rd3b5,Rb5e8] without losing the queen.}) 14... exf4
15. Qf3 Ne3 16. Bxe3 fxe3 17. Qxb7 d5 18. Be2 {Popov, I (2650)-Turkin, V (2285)
Nezhmetdinov Memorial 36th 2014 (1) 1/2-1/2} (18. Nxd5 e2 19. Rf5 g6 20. Qxe7+
Qxe7 21. Nxe7 gxf5 22. Nxf5 Rd8 23. Bxe2 Rd2 24. Bd3 Rg8 $17) 18... Qb8 19. Qc6
Rh6 $19) (11. Bxd4 exd4 12. Nb5 (12. Ne4 Qa5+ 13. Kf2 O-O-O $11) 12... Qa5+ 13.
c3 dxc3 14. Qxc3 Qxc3+ 15. Nxc3 O-O-O 16. Kf2 d5 $11) 11... Nxf5 12. Bf2 $146 (
12. Bb5+ {transposes above after} Kf8) 12... Qa5 (12... O-O $5 13. g4 Nd4 14.
g5 Nh5 $1 15. Qxh5 Nxc2+ 16. Kd2 Nxa1 17. Bd3 g6 18. Qf3 d5 19. Nxd5 exf4 20.
h4 Rc8 21. Rxa1 Bc5 22. Bxc5 Rxc5 23. Nf6+ Kg7 24. Qxf4 Rf5 25. Qe3 Qa5+ 26.
Ke2 Re5 27. Be4 h6 $13) 13. g4 (13. Bb5+ Kf8 14. O-O h5 15. Bd3 Nd4 $11) 13...
Rc8 $3 (13... Nd4 14. Bxd4 exd4 15. Qxd4 $16) 14. gxf5 Rxc3 15. bxc3 Qxc3+ 16.
Ke2 Qc6 {Black has enough compensation for the rook.} 17. Kd2 (17. Rg1 Qe4+ 18.
Kd2 Qb4+ 19. Kc1 Qa3+ 20. Kb1 Qb4+ 21. Kc1 Qa3+ 22. Kd2 Qb4+ 23. Ke2 Qe4+ $11
24. Be3 $6 exf4 25. Qd3 fxe3 26. Qxe4 Nxe4 27. Kxe3 d5 $15) 17... Ne4+ (17...
Qxh1 $2 18. Bb5+) 18. Ke1 O-O 19. Bg2 (19. Qf3 Bd8 $19) 19... Qc3+ 20. Kf1 Nxf2
21. Kxf2 Bh4+ 22. Kf1 e4 $44 {Black is completely undeveloped and the
opposite-coloured bishops yield Black a consistent attack.} 23. Bxe4 Re8 $17 *

