{[%evp 0,90,19,38,40,41,41,32,50,22,15,39,87,63,65,9,49,49,15,18,0,5,17,23,21,
34,31,37,63,63,124,66,18,26,26,14,57,79,225,113,115,124,184,114,147,122,112,
109,137,98,100,98,112,120,120,120,156,84,96,73,102,97,144,114,132,132,224,196,
155,145,197,197,198,197,280,281,364,99,105,98,121,106,110,110,110,107,135,149,
122,132,122,132,158]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 d6 6.
Be3 Nf6 7. f4 Be7 8. Qf3 e5 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. f5 {It is only after this move
that the big fight starts. Everything depends on the mutual speed of attack.
White plans to attack with g4-g5 and Black should prepare the central break.}
Rb8 {Attacking b2 and evacuating the long diagonal, thus preparing the central
break.} (10... d5 11. exd5 cxd5 12. O-O-O {leaves the d5-pawn under a double
pin.} Bb7 13. Bc4 e4 14. Qh3 O-O 15. Bb3 Bb4 16. Bd4 $16) 11. O-O-O (11. b3 $2
d5 12. exd5 cxd5 (12... Qa5 $19) (12... Bb4 $19) 13. O-O-O d4 $19 {There is no
rook hanging on a8 now.}) (11. Bc4 Rxb2 $1 $146 ({All the available games went
} 11... Qa5 {with a possible transposition to the main line.}) 12. Bb3 d5 13.
Bc1 (13. O-O-O Ba3 $19) 13... dxe4 14. Qg3 (14. Nxe4 Bb4+ 15. c3 Nxe4 16. cxb4
Qh4+ 17. g3 Nxg3 18. hxg3 Qxb4+ 19. Kd1 Qd4+ 20. Ke1 Rxb3 21. axb3 Qxa1 22.
Qxc6+ Bd7 23. Qc5 Qd4 $15) 14... Rxb3 15. axb3 h5 $15) 11... Qa5 12. Bc4 {
Increasing the control over d5 and preparing to consolidate the queenside.} (
12. g4 $2 {loses quickly.} Rxb2 $1 (12... d5 13. exd5 Rxb2 $19) 13. Kxb2 Qb4+
14. Kc1 Qxc3 15. Kb1 (15. g5 d5 $1 $19) 15... d5 $19) (12. Bf2 {avoids the
catastrophee, but wastes a tempo.} d5 $5 (12... Qb4 13. b3 O-O $15 14. g4 $6 d5
) 13. exd5 cxd5 14. Nxd5 Qxa2 15. Bb5+ Kf8 16. Nxe7 Qa1+ 17. Kd2 Qa5+ 18. Kc1 (
18. c3 Qxb5 $19) (18. Ke3 Qxb5 $19) 18... Qa1+ (18... Qxb5 19. Qa3 $19) 19. Kd2
Qa5+ 20. Kc1 {Milliet,S (2374)-Gallagher,J (2510) Mitropa Cup 30th 2011 (3) 1/
2-1/2}) 12... O-O (12... d5 {is mentioned by Kasparov and Nikitin as
interesting. They add that at the time they were writing, it did not seem to
work, but they rhetorically asked themselves which would be the evaluation in
the future. The latter part is interesting. Nowadays, with engines that become
stronger day by day, no one seems to ask such questions and the tendency is to
believe what the engines of the moment are saying. This leads to funny changes
in evaluations within a relatively short period. The modern search for the
truth... Anyway, the book lines go} 13. exd5 Rxb2 14. d6 (14. Kxb2 Qa3+ 15. Kb1
Qxc3 16. Bb3 cxd5 17. Bg5 Qc7 18. Bxf6 Bxf6 19. Ba4+ Kf8 20. Qxd5 $16 {
Balashov, Y (2600)-Andersson, U (2560) (GER-ch) International05 1979 (5) 1-0})
14... e4 15. Nxe4 Rxc2+ 16. Kxc2 Bxf5 17. Rd4 Bxd6 18. Rf1 Bg6 19. Rxd6 Bxe4+
20. Qxe4+ $18 {Engines suggest several alternatives on the way, but the old
analysis is correct.}) 13. Bg5 (13. g4 $2 {is too slow.} d5 $1 14. exd5 ({
Awarded by Kasparov and Nikitin with an exclamation mark, this runs into} 14.
g5 Rxb2 $1 $19 {, just the most resolute of several winning moves.}) (14. Bb3
d4 15. g5 Ne8 $19) 14... Rxb2 15. d6 Qxc3 16. Bb3 Rxb3 $5 $146 (16... Bd8 $19)
17. axb3 Bxd6 18. Rxd6 e4 $19 {and White cannot keep both the bishop and the
rook on h1 defended at the same time.} 19. Qe2 Qa1+ 20. Kd2 Qxh1) (13. Bd2 Qb6
14. b3 {Volkmann, F (2409)-Wallner, A (2272) AUT-chT2O 1011 2010 (10.3) 1-0 is
solid but a bit passive.} Bb7 15. g4 d5 $11 16. Bd3 (16. g5 dxc4 17. gxf6 Bxf6
18. Na4 Qa6 $11) (16. exd5 cxd5 17. Nxd5 Nxd5 18. Bxd5 Qd4 $19) 16... Nxe4 $5 {
The most consistent way of creating counterplay, requiring certain accuracy
from White.} (16... dxe4 17. Nxe4 c5 18. g5 Nxe4 19. Bxe4 c4 $11) 17. Nxe4 c5
18. Be3 $1 {Pinning the c-pawn.} (18. g5 $2 c4 $19) (18. f6 dxe4 19. Bxe4 Bxf6
$15) 18... Qa5 19. f6 $1 {Another forced move.} dxe4 20. Bxe4 Bxf6 21. Bxb7 Qa3+
22. Kd2 (22. Kb1 e4 23. Bc1 Qxc1+ 24. Kxc1 exf3 25. Bxf3 Rfd8 $11) 22... Qb4+
23. c3 Qxb7 24. Qxb7 Rxb7 25. Bxc5 Rc8 26. Be3 Be7 27. c4 f6 28. Kc2 Kf7 29. h4
Ke6 30. h5 a6 $11) ({The most consistent continuation is} 13. Bb3 {, examined
in Line 38.}) 13... Ba6 $1 $146 {The best way of fighting against the exposed
white bishop.} (13... Rb4 $2 14. Bb3 Rd8 15. h4 h6 16. Bxf6 Bxf6 17. Qh5 d5 18.
g4 Rxb3 19. cxb3 dxe4 20. g5 Rxd1+ 21. Rxd1 hxg5 22. hxg5 Be7 23. Rh1 {Weiss,
M-Bashen, G USA-ch06 prel 13 corr 1982 1-0}) 14. Bb3 (14. Bxa6 Qxa6 15. h4 d5 {
Easier to carry out without the white light-squared bishop.} 16. Bxf6 $2 {
Trying to refute Black's plan.} ({The solid} 16. Qd3 {is better.} Qb7 17. b3 d4
18. Bxf6 Ba3+ 19. Kb1 gxf6 20. Na4 Kh8 $13) 16... Bxf6 17. exd5 cxd5 (17... e4
$5 18. Qxe4 Qb6 $19) 18. Rxd5 e4 19. Qxe4 (19. Qe3 Rxb2 20. Kxb2 Qb7+ 21. Kc1
Bxc3 $19) 19... Bxc3 20. bxc3 Qh6+ 21. Rd2 Qb6 $19) 14... c5 $1 {Consequent
and strong.} 15. Bxf6 Bxf6 16. Bd5 Qb4 17. b3 Qa3+ 18. Kb1 (18. Kd2 Rb4 19. Ke1
Rd4 20. h4 Bd8 $17) 18... c4 19. h4 Rfc8 20. g4 {A thrilling fight with mutual
attacks on the opposite wings.} cxb3 (20... Bd8 $5 21. f6 $8 Ba5 22. fxg7 Rc7
