Ke1 Bh5+ 42. Kd2 Rd8+ 43. Kc3 Rc8+ 44. Kb4 Rb8+ 45. Kc5 Bf7 $11 {Technically
speaking, White has five pawns for the bishop. However, he cannot advance his
queenside pawns without losing one of them, while the pawn on g7 keeps the
rook busy on g3. The game should end in a draw. This whole fascinating system
