{[%evp 0,36,18,8,51,51,51,42,42,49,54,45,50,57,57,45,10,-5,26,3,-7,-7,21,7,23,
23,22,3,18,-27,26,8,20,17,44,15,-7,-65,-54]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4.
Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Be2 {This apparently modest developing move introduces
the Classical System. White does not intend to question the viability of
Black's opening. Instead, he prefers to develop harmoniously, hoping to
maintain his theoretical initial advantage until late in the middlegame.} Nf6 (
{For the same reasons as after 6.Be3,} 6... Nge7 {is not recommendable.}) 7. g4
{An interesting hybrid between the Classical System and the Keres Attack. This
would work better if Black had played ...a7-a6 instead of ...Nc6, the latter
being a sound-developing move, putting pressure in the centre.} (7. Bg5 {
is examined in Lines 40 to 42.}) ({For} 7. Be3 {, see Lines 42 and 43.}) (7.
O-O {is the main classical line, covered in Lines 44 to 52.}) (7. f4 Be7 {
does not have much of independent value, being likely to transpose to any of
the last two systems mentioned above.}) 7... h6 {Slowing down the advance of
the g-pawn with this modest move is one of the normal reactions to the Keres
Attack. In order to justify the weakening of his kingside, White needs to
commit himself even more.} 8. h4 {Still hoping to drive the knight away with
g4-g5 followed by hxg5, but this needs preparing still.} (8. Rg1 {is a slow
move, allowing} e5 $5 $146 {, in the spirit of the Boleslavsky system.} 9. Nf5
{The critical continuation.} (9. Nb3 Be6 10. f4 {Otherwise, Black could open
the centre with ...d6-d5 soon.} exf4 11. Bxf4 d5 $11) (9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. Bc4 {
Preventing ..d6-d5.} Rb8 11. Qe2 Be7 12. Bb3 Be6 13. h4 Nh7 $11) 9... Be6 10.
Ne3 (10. Be3 g6 11. Ng3 d5 $11) 10... Nd4 $11) (8. Be3 e5 9. Nf5 h5 $5 $146 (
9... g6 10. Ng3 Be6 11. O-O Rc8 12. f4 exf4 13. Bxf4 Be7 14. Nd5 Bxd5 15. exd5
Ne5 16. Bb5+ Kf8 17. Be2 Kg7 $11 {Chambers, C-Silva Lucena, C (2252) Titled
Tuesday intern op 03rd Aug blitz 2021 (7) 1/2-1/2}) 10. g5 (10. gxh5 Bxf5 11.
exf5 d5 12. Bg5 Bb4 $11) (10. f3 g6 11. Ng3 Be6 $15) 10... Nxe4 11. Nxg7+ Bxg7
12. Nxe4 d5 13. Ng3 d4 14. Bd2 h4 15. Ne4 Be6 16. Bg4 Qd5 17. Qf3 O-O-O $13) (
8. g5 hxg5 9. Bxg5 {is inoffensive. The tempo spent on Be2 makes a difference
with respect to the Keres Attack.} Qa5 $5 $146 10. Bb5 (10. Qd2 $2 Nxd4 $1) (
10. Bxf6 gxf6 11. Qd3 Bd7 12. O-O-O Nxd4 13. Qxd4 Bh6+ 14. Kb1 Bf4 {[%cal
Ge8e7]} 15. Qxf6 Be5 16. Qf3 Rc8 17. Rd3 Qc5 $15 {[%cal Ge8e7,Gb7b5] followed
by ...Ke7 and ...b7-b5.}) 10... Bd7 11. Nb3 Qb6 {[%cal Gf6e4]} 12. Qe2 Rh3 13.
Be3 Qc7 14. O-O-O a6 15. Bxc6 Qxc6 16. f3 b5 $11) 8... Be7 (8... e5 {partly
justifies h2-h4, but is playable, too.} 9. Nf5 g6 (9... Be6 {runs into} 10. h5
$14) 10. Ne3 Be6 11. Ned5 Nd4 12. Nxf6+ Qxf6 13. Nd5 Qd8 14. h5 Bxd5 15. exd5
Nxe2 16. Qxe2 Qa5+ 17. Bd2 Qxd5 18. O-O-O Rc8 (18... Qxa2 19. Qb5+ Kd8 20. Ba5+
