This move transposes to the Classical Sicilian Rauzer Attack. However, in the
Rauzer, the topical continuation is 7.Qd2, something we definitely avoid with
our repertoire, while 7.Be2 is a rare and not very dangerous move. Some
coverage of this line is needed, though.} Be7 8. Qd2 ({The rarer} 8. Qd3 {
is likely to transpose, since in the main line we usually play ...Nxd4 soon.
Here are the possible transpositions:} O-O 9. f4 (9. Rd1 Nxd4) (9. O-O-O Nxd4)
9... h6 10. h4 Nxd4) (8. f4 {is a bit premature, allowing} h6 {in a favourable
version.} 9. Bh4 {The bishop is exposed now.} Qb6 10. Ndb5 (10. Nb3 Nxe4 $1 $17
) (10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. Qd3 d5 12. e5 Ne4 13. Bxe7 Qf2+ 14. Kd1 Qxg2 $17) 10...
Nxe4 $1 11. Nxe4 Bxh4+ 12. g3 Be7 13. Nexd6+ Kf8 {Black has lost the right to
castle, but White does not have enough development to continue his attack.
Black has two bishops and White has somewhat weakened his position.} 14. a4 Qc5
15. Qd2 a6 16. Ne4 Qb6 17. Nbc3 f5 18. Nd6 Qxb2 19. Rb1 Qa3 20. Nc4 Qc5 21. a5
Rb8 $15 {Salazar Moran,A (1376)-Pandey,M (2067) SE-2018-0-00273 0-1}) (8. O-O {
is examined in Line 41.}) 8... O-O 9. f4 {Even though White seems to have good
development and normal coordination, his choice is not that wide.} (9. O-O-O {
runs into} Nxd4 10. Qxd4 Nxe4 $1 {The point is that after} 11. Bxe7 Nxc3 $1 {
The bishop on e2 is hanging. This may seem like a detail but is typical for
the Rauzer lines with an early Be2.} 12. Qh4 $1 (12. Bxd8 $2 Nxe2+ 13. Kb1 Nxd4
$19) 12... Nxe2+ 13. Kb1 (13. Kd2 Qb6 14. Bxf8 Nd4 15. Bxg7 (15. Be7 Qxb2 $19)
15... Nf5 16. Qf6 Nxg7 $17) 13... Qb6 $1 14. Rxd6 Nc3+ 15. Kc1 (15. Ka1 Qa5 16.
bxc3 Re8 17. Kb2 e5 $17) 15... Qb4 $5 (15... Nxa2+ 16. Kb1 Nc3+ $11) 16. Rd8 (
