{[%evp 0,44,20,28,33,50,66,50,50,50,50,50,50,45,42,43,43,43,35,30,41,34,34,28,
28,16,28,-7,17,9,9,-12,0,-15,-18,-9,0,-39,-20,-30,-27,-25,-25,-36,-36,-32,-23]
} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Be2 Nf6 7. O-O Be7 8.
Be3 O-O 9. f4 {We finally reach the main classical system setup. White gains
space in the centre without wasting time on moves he could play later.} e5 {
Since Black did not spend a tempo on ...a7-a6, he can counterattack in the
centre at once. I remember that this system was popular at a high level during
my teen-age. I am glad to find out that it did not lose its validity up to
today. Black's main idea is to get the e5-square for his knight, something
typical for the Najdorf.} (9... Nxd4 10. Bxd4 b6 {allows Black to complete his
development quickly with} 11. Qd3 Bb7 12. Rad1 {[%cal Gd3g3] followed by Qg3.})
(9... Bd7 {is another important line, when White's most principled answer is}
10. Nb3 {, preventing ...Nxd4 followed by ...Bc6 and leaving the bishop
somewhat passive on d7.}) (9... a6 {transposes to a difficult system, where
White's attacking chances should not be neglected.} 10. Qe1 Nxd4 11. Bxd4 b5
12. a3 Bb7 13. Qg3 {with a lot of theory.}) 10. Nxc6 {Exchanging the knight
that was designed for the e5-square.} (10. Nf5 $2 {offers Black an advantage
in the centre.} Bxf5 $1 11. exf5 exf4 {The knight on f6 is a very stable piece
now.} 12. Bxf4 (12. Rxf4 {does not change much.} d5 13. Kh1 {Prventing ...
d5-d4.} Re8 14. Bg1 Bb4 15. Bf3 Qd6 16. Rh4 {Chernobay,A (2401)-Timofeev,A 
(2664) Moscow op-A 04th 2008 (1) 0-1} Rad8 17. Nb5 Qe7 18. Nd4 Bc5 $17 {
With a perfect version of the French Isolani. Black does not have a "bad"
bishop and is perfectly mobilized, while the square on e4 is weak.}) 12... d5
13. Bf3 d4 14. Ne4 Qb6 15. Kh1 Rad8 16. Nxf6+ Bxf6 17. Qd3 Rd7 $15 18. g4 $6 h6
$17) (10. Nf3 {runs into} Ng4 11. Bc1 exf4 12. Bxf4 Bf6 {with comfortable play.
} 13. Kh1 Re8 (13... Bxc3 $5 14. bxc3 Nge5 15. Nd4 Be6 $11) 14. Bc4 (14. Qxd6
