1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Be2 Nf6 7. O-O Be7 8.
Be3 O-O 9. f4 e5 10. fxe5 {I vividly remember the intense theoretical dispute
in this line sometime in the early '80s. The exchange on e5 is a small
concession, but White gets the bishops' pair.} dxe5 11. Nf5 Bxf5 12. Rxf5 (12.
exf5 {weakens the control in the centre.} Bb4 $5 $15) 12... Qxd1+ {Strictly
speaking, this is a small concession, speeding up White's development. With
the actual structure, though, the black queen does not have an optimal square,
so it is better to exchange it, though.} ({The young Kasparov preferred} 12...
Qa5 13. Kh1 Rad8 {Geller,E (2545)-Kasparov,G (2675) Interzonal-12c 1982 (4) 1/
2-1/2} 14. Bd3 Nd4 15. Rf1 Qb6 16. a3 Qd6 {Frolov,A (2164)-Esipenko,A (2289)
Dvorkovich Memorial op 2014 (3) 1-0} 17. Qe1 $5 $14 {[%cal Ga1d1] followed by
Rd1.}) 13. Rxd1 {White has the d5-square for his knight and the light-squared
bishop may become active. Black's control on d4 is relative, since there is a
white pawn on c2 still. Black's main trump is his control on dark squares and
his more compact structure. The latter could be detailed by saying that the
pawn on e4 needs constant care.} g6 (13... Nd4 $2 {loses a pawn to} 14. Rxe5
$16) (13... Rad8 {is a less popular, but entirely playable move, though.}) 14.
Rf2 {Maintaining the possibility of doubling the rooks on the f-file, while
also overdefending the bishop on e2.} (14. Rff1 {is more passive.} Nd4 (14...
Rfd8 $11) 15. Bd3 (15. Rd2 Rac8 16. Bd1 Kg7 17. g4 h6 18. Kg2 Ne6 {White needs
to count with ...Rxc3 and the square on f4 is weak.} 19. Nd5 {Abramovic, B 
(2475)-Paunovic,D (2320) Vrnjacka Banja International-14 1983 (10) 1-0} Nxe4 $1
20. Nxe7 Nxd2 21. Bxd2 Rcd8 {White needs a few only moves in order to avoid
troubles connected with his far-advanced knight.} 22. Bb4 $1 Rfe8 23. c4 $1 {
Preparing Ba4.} a5 24. Ba3 Rd2+ 25. Kh1 e4 26. Ba4 Red8 27. Nd5 {This is why
the pawn had to advance to c4.} b5 $1 28. Bxb5 Nd4 29. Be7 Rxd5 $1 30. cxd5
Nxb5 31. Bf6+ Kf8 32. Rc1 Ke8 33. Rc4 Nd6 34. Rc7 Rf2 $13) (15. Bxd4 exd4 16.
Nb5 Nxe4 17. Nxd4 Bg5 $11 {Rajkovic,L-Vogt,L (2485) Opatija op 1984 (5) 0-1})
15... Ng4 16. Nd5 (16. Bc1 Bc5 17. Kh1 Ne6 18. Rd2 Nf4 $11) 16... Nxe3 17. Nxe3
Bc5 (17... Bg5 {Ljubojevic,L (2600)-Timman,J (2655) Olympiad-25 Luzern 1982 (9)
1/2-1/2} 18. Nc4 $14) 18. Kh1 Kg7 {Both sides start improving their positions
slowly.} 19. Nd5 a5 20. a3 a4 21. g4 h6 22. c3 Ne6 23. h4 Rfd8 24. Kg2 Rd6 $11
{Schrecke,V-Koch,M GER V0309 email 2008 1/2-1/2}) 14... Nd4 15. Bh6 Nxe2+ {
The simplest.} ({A famous game went} 15... Nxc2 $2 16. Bg5 $1 Nd5 (16... Kg7
17. Rdf1 Ng8 18. Bxe7 Nxe7 19. Bc4 $18) 17. Bxe7 Nxe7 18. Rd7 $18 {Geller,E 
(2575)-Tal, M (2620) URS-ch50 Final+ 1983 (1) 1-0}) (15... Rfd8 {is also
playable, but offers White a choice.} 16. Bc4 {is the most ambitious
continuation.} (16. Rdf1 {plays into Black's hands.} Rac8 17. h3 (17. Rxf6 Bxf6
18. Rxf6 Rxc3 19. bxc3 Nxe2+ $19) 17... Nxe2+ {After White has spent a tempo
on h2-h3, this exchange works even better than in the main line.} 18. Rxe2 Nh5
(18... Rc6 19. Bg5 Kg7 20. g4 Rd7 21. Kg2 Ne8 $11) 19. Kh2 Bh4 20. Rf3 {
Bielczyk, J (2410)-Boudy Bueno, J (2335) Capablanca Memorial-18 Group A 1983 1-0}
Rd6 21. g3 Bd8 22. g4 Ng7 23. Bxg7 Kxg7 24. Nd5 Rdc6 25. c3 Bh4 $11 {[%cal
Gb7b5] followed by ...b7-b5.}) 16... Ne6 17. Rxd8+ (17. Bxe6 $2 Bc5 18. Rxd8+
Rxd8 19. Bd5 Bxf2+ 20. Kxf2 Ng4+ $19) 17... Rxd8 18. Nd5 (18. Rd2 Nc5 $5 $11)
18... Nxd5 $1 19. exd5 Nf4 $1 20. Bxf4 exf4 21. Rxf4 {The endgame should have ended
in a draw, but Black later lost the thread.} Bc5+ 22. Kf1 Bd6 23. Rf3 h5 24. h3 Re8
25. Be2 f5 (25... Re5 $6 {Provoking a useful move and misplacing the rook.} 26.
c4 Bc5 27. a3 Re3 (27... a5 28. Rb3 b6 29. Rb5 $16 a4 30. Bd1) 28. b4 Rxf3+ 29.
Bxf3 Bd4 30. Ke2 Bb2 31. Kd3 {Popescu,P-Andreassen,A EU-chT3 corr8392 1983 1-0}
) 26. c4 b6 27. a3 a5 $11 {Black's active pieces and control over the dark
squares yield him enough compensation for the pawn. In some cases, ...Bc5
followed by ...Re3 leads to an immediate draw.} 28. Rb3 Bc5 29. Rb5 a4 30. Bd1
Ra8 $11 {The rook is caged on b5.} 31. d6 Kf7 32. Bf3 Rd8 $11) 16. Rxe2 Rfd8
17. Rf1 Rd7 18. Bg5 Ne8 19. Bxe7 Rxe7 20. Nd5 Rd7 21. c4 {White has reached
the maximum he could dream of, but the position remains equal. The pawn on e4
and the square on d4 are weak.} Rc8 22. b3 Kg7 23. g4 h6 24. Kg2 (24. Kf2 {
allows} Nf6 25. h3 Nxd5 26. exd5 b5 27. Re4 bxc4 28. bxc4 Rdc7 29. Rc1 Rc5 30.
Rxe5 Kf6 31. Re4 Rxd5 $11 {Maki,V (2405)-Kiik,K (2400) FIN-chT Finland 1994 1/
2-1/2}) 24... Nc7 25. a4 $5 (25. h4 b5 26. Nxc7 Rcxc7 27. cxb5 Rb7 28. a4 a6
$11) (25. Ref2 Nxd5 26. exd5 b5 27. cxb5 Rc5 $11) 25... Ne6 $5 $11 {Here are
some illustrative lines:} 26. h4 (26. a5 Rc5 27. Ra2 Nd4 28. Ra3 f5 (28... Nc6
29. Rfa1 Rd6 $5 $11) 29. gxf5 gxf5 30. exf5 Rcxd5 31. cxd5 Nc2 $11) 26... g5 (
26... Nc5 27. Rf3 b6 28. h5 Rc6 29. Kf2 a5 $5 $11) (26... Rd6 27. Kg3 a5 $11)
27. Kg3 Nf4 28. Ref2 a6 29. hxg5 (29. h5 b5 30. Nb6 Rd3+ 31. Rf3 Rcd8 $11) (29.
a5 gxh4+ 30. Kxh4 Rc5 31. Ra2 Ne6 32. Kg3 Ng5 $11) 29... hxg5 30. a5 Rh8 $11 *

