{[%evp 0,34,27,18,55,50,50,50,50,57,36,36,53,52,52,57,57,34,34,50,42,30,23,28,
28,26,21,-37,41,-11,-11,-23,-24,-32,-35,-27,-38]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 ({It is
useful to compare the position arising after 12 moves with that one from the
following game:} 2... d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be2 e5 7. Nb3 Be7
8. O-O O-O 9. Be3 Be6 10. f4 {The old-fashioned continuation.} (10. Qd2 {
became more popular later.}) 10... exf4 $1 ({There have been times when the
main continuation was} 10... Qc7 11. a4 Nbd7 12. a5) 11. Bxf4 (11. Rxf4 Nc6 {
is a closely related tabiya.}) 11... Nc6 {Black has an extra tempo (...a7-a6)
with respect to our repertoire line. This could be good or bad, depending on
the circumstances. More about it later.} 12. Kh1 Rc8 13. Qe1 {I had the
following game as a model for my repertoire and I suspect that it also
determined 9...e5 in our repertoire to become popular soon.} Ne8 {The start
of an elegant regrouping.} 14. Rd1 Bh4 {Preventing Qg3.} 15. Qd2 Bf6 16. Be3
Be5 17. Nd4 Nxd4 18. Bxd4 Nf6 19. Bxe5 dxe5 20. Qg5 Nd7 21. Qg3 Qb6 22. Bg4
Bxg4 23. Qxg4 Nf6 24. Qg3 Qxb2 25. Rd3 {Pritchett,C (2390)-Portisch,L (2655)
Olympiad-24 Valetta 1980 (1) 0-1} Rxc3 26. Rxc3 Nxe4 $19) 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4
Nc6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Be2 Nf6 7. O-O Be7 8. Be3 O-O 9. f4 e5 10. Nb3 {The most
typical knight retreat in most Sicilian lines and the main line in our current
variation. White simply maintains his overall harmony and space advantage.}
exf4 {The same as in the Najdorf, White has a choice now.} 11. Rxf4 {This move
avoids losing a tempo (Bc1-e3xf4) and overdefends e4, in order to make Nd5 an
issue. After an exchange on d5, the rook could navigate to the queenside. Not
least, in the event of ...d6-d5, Black should count with Rxf6. On the other
hand, the rook is slightly exposed here.} (11. Bxf4 {is examined in Lines 50
to 52.}) 11... Be6 {A natural developing move, increasing the control over d5.
We have now reached the aforementioned Najdorf tabiya, with the only
difference being that the black pawn is on a7 instead of a6. Black has two main
approaches. He can keep the structure as it is, trying to activate his
dark-squared bishop and use the square on e5 for his minor pieces. In such
cases, the move ...a7-a6 could be useful, by preventing Nb5. It would also
avoid problems with the pawn hanging on a7 after, say, ...Ne5 and ...Rc8. On
the other hand, the relative weakness on b6 could sometimes cause small
problems. The second plan is breaking with ...d6-d5. In this case, the pawn is
better placed on a7, since after the exchanges in the centre, the weakness on
b6 could be relevant.} 12. Kh1 {is a flexible move, passing to Black the
responsibility of choosing a plan.} ({The developing} 12. Qd2 {allows} d5 {
equalizing at once.} 13. exd5 ({An important detail is that the sacrifice
mentioned below does not work here} 13. Rxf6 $2 Bxf6 14. exd5 Bxc3 $1 $19 {
This is the difference! Black wins material.}) 13... Nxd5 14. Nxd5 Qxd5 15.
Qxd5 Bxd5 16. c4 (16. Bc5 Rfe8 17. Bxe7 Rxe7 $11 {Bouaziz,S (2355)-Timman,J 
(2655) Interzonal-12a 1982 (7) 1/2-1/2}) 16... Be6 17. Nc5 Bc8 18. Rff1 {
Ljubisavljevic,Z-Paoli,E Imperia op 08th 1966 1-0} b6 19. Bf3 Bxc5 20. Bxc5
bxc5 21. Bxc6 Rb8 22. b3 Be6 $11) (12. Qe1 {prevents the central break, but
fails to reach the desired kingside attacking setup.} Nd7 (12... d5 $2 13. Rd1
$16 Bd6 $2 14. Rxf6 $1 Qxf6 15. exd5 Qe5 16. Qg3 Qxc3 17. bxc3 Bxg3 18. hxg3
Rfe8 19. dxc6 $18 {Vnukov,D-Bonthuis,S IECG L2.1999.0.00004 email 1-0}) 13. Rf1
(13. Qg3 {Tomczak,J (2448)-Panas,P (2226) Polanica Zdroj op-A 43rd 2007 (1) 1-0
} Bg5 $11) 13... Bf6 14. Rd1 Be5 {The bishop has reached an optimal square.
The knight on c3 cannot jump to d5 without leaving b2 undefended. Therefore,
now or in the near future, White needs to exchange it, which favours Black
strategically.} 15. Bf4 (15. Kh1 Rc8 16. Bf4 {Cuijpers,F-Greenfeld,A (2300)
EU-ch U20 Groningen 1981 (10) 1/2-1/2} Bxf4 17. Rxf4 Nde5 $11 {The temporary
weakness of the pawn on d6 is not a problem:} 18. Qd2 Qe7 19. Qxd6 Qxd6 20.
Rxd6 Nb4 21. Rd2 Rfd8 $11) (15. Nd4 Nxd4 16. Bxd4 Bxd4+ 17. Rxd4 Qb6 18. Qd2 {
Paquez,M-Sznek,J corr 1985 1-0} Qxb2 19. Rb1 Qa3 20. Rxb7 Rfc8 $11 21. Nd5 Rcb8
22. Rc7 Qxa2) 15... Qb6+ 16. Kh1 a5 17. Bxe5 Ndxe5 (17... dxe5 $11 18. Nd5 Bxd5
19. exd5 Nb4 $15) 18. Qf2 Qxf2 19. Rxf2 a4 20. Nc1 a3 21. bxa3 (21. b3 Nb4 $15)
21... Na5 22. Nb5 Rfc8 23. Rd2 Nac4 24. Bxc4 Nxc4 25. Rd3 h6 26. h3 Ra6 $11 {
Cuijpers,F-Salov,V EU-ch U20 Groningen 1981 (2) 1/2-1/2}) (12. Nd4 {The same
as in the Najdorf, this is the second most popular move. Personally, I feel
that the knight's return to the centre, a few moves after it has retreated,
offers Black some time.} Nxd4 13. Bxd4 (13. Qxd4 a6 14. Bc4 Qc8 15. Bxe6 Qxe6
16. h3 Rac8 17. Qd3 Nd7 18. Bd4 Ne5 19. Qg3 Qg6 20. Qxg6 hxg6 21. Nd5 Rfe8 22.
Rd1 Bg5 23. Rf2 (23. Bxe5 Rxe5 24. Rf2 Rxe4 $17 {Ivanovic,B (2415)-Kovacevic,A
(2575) MNT-chT Cetinje 2009 (2) 0-1}) 23... Nd7 24. Re2 f5 25. Rde1 fxe4 26. c3
Nc5 $11) 13... Nd7 14. Bg4 (14. Kh1 Ne5 15. a4 Nc6 16. Bg1 Bf6 17. Rf3 Be5 18.
Nd5 {Akash,G (2395)-Tukhaev,A (2516) Mumbai Wealth op 2nd 2016 (8) 0-1} Bxb2
19. Rb1 Be5 20. Rxb7 Qh4 21. Qd3 Rab8 22. Rb5 a6 23. Rxb8 Nxb8 24. a5 Qe1)
14... Bf6 15. Nd5 Bxd5 16. Bxd7 (16. exd5 Bxd4+ 17. Qxd4 Ne5 $15) 16... Be5 $1
17. Bxe5 dxe5 18. Rf5 Bxe4 (18... Qb6+ 19. Kh1 Bc4 20. b3 Rad8 21. bxc4 Qc7 22.
Qd5 Rxd7 23. Qxe5 Qxc4 $17) 19. Rxe5 Qb6+ 20. Kh1 Qg6 21. Qe2 Bxc2 $15 {
Dragovic,M (2405)-Cvetkovic,S (2500) Vrbas 1993 (7) 1/2-1/2}) (12. Nd5 {
is examined in Line 49.}) 12... Rc8 $5 $146 {Since in a similar Najdorf
position I had this move in my repertoire 30 years ago, I wanted to check the
way it works here.} (12... d5 {is possible, but Black has to take into account}
13. Rxf6 {The only challenging move.} (13. exd5 Nxd5 14. Nxd5 Qxd5 15. Qxd5
Bxd5 16. Rd1 Rfd8 17. c4 Be6 18. Nd4 Nxd4 19. Rfxd4 b6 20. Bf3 Rac8 {Kavalek,L
(2545)-Hort,V (2620) Interpolis-01 1977 (7) 1/2-1/2}) 13... Bxf6 14. exd5 Bxc3
15. dxc6 Bxb3 16. cxb3 $5 {For reasons explained below, trickier than the game
capture.} (16. axb3 Bxb2 17. cxb7 Bxa1 18. Qxa1 Rb8 19. Bf3 $13 {Adhiban,B 
(2406)-Mustafaev, J (2270) World ol U16 12th 2007 (4) 1/2-1/2}) 16... Bxb2 (
16... Qxd1+ $5 17. Bxd1 Rae8 18. Bf2 Be1 19. Bc5 Bh4 20. Bf3 bxc6 21. Bxf8 Kxf8
22. g3 Bf6 $11) 17. Rb1 Qe7 ({After axb3,} 17... Qxd1+ $2 {would work, too,
but here it does not.} 18. Bxd1 Rae8 19. Bf2 Bd4 {The only resource, as
otherwise cxb7 would yield White a stable advantage.} 20. Bxd4 Re1+ 21. Bg1
bxc6 {With the pawn on c2 instead of a2, White would have to spend a tempo on
22.c4, preparing Bc2. This would be met with 22...Rb8, causing White problems
with freeing himself. The game would be unclear. Here, White wins with} 22. Bc2
$18) 18. cxb7 Rad8 19. Qg1 Rfe8 20. Rxb2 Qxe3 21. Qxe3 Rxe3 22. Kg1 Rb8 23. Kf2
Rc3 24. Rd2 Rc7 25. Bf3 g6 $11 {It is a matter of taste. Personally, I would
not be keen to enter such forced lines with symbolic white initiative. Not if
there are positional alternatives available.}) (12... Ne8 {The same manoeuvre
as in Portisch' old game.} 13. Nd4 (13. Rf2 Bh4 14. Rf1 Bf6 {transposes}) (13.
Rf1 Bf6 14. Qd2 Be5 15. Bg5 {Felgaer, R (2539)-Solys, L (2304) Warsaw AIG Life
rapid 7th 2007 (12) 1-0} Nf6 $15) (13. Nd5 Bg5 $11) 13... Nxd4 (13... Bf6 14.
Nxe6 fxe6 $11) 14. Bxd4 Bg5 15. Rf1 Bf6 16. Bxf6 Nxf6 17. Qd4 Qe7 18. Rad1 Rfd8
19. Rd3 Ne8 (19... a6 20. Rg3 Kh8 21. a4 Rac8 $11 {[%cal Gc8c5]}) 20. Rdf3 a6
21. Bc4 Nf6 22. Bxe6 fxe6 23. e5 dxe5 24. Qxe5 Rac8 25. Re3 Rd2 26. Re2 Rxe2
27. Qxe2 e5 $11 {Onischuk,A (2625)-Leko,P (2635) Tilburg Fontys 1997 (5) 1/2-1/
2}) (12... Nd7 {also works.} 13. Rf1 Rc8 (13... Nde5 14. Nd5 Bg5 15. Bg1 Rc8
16. c3 Re8 17. a4 {Zhu,C (2350)-Kasimdzhanov,R (2435) Wch U20 Halle 1995 (13)
1-0} Nd7 18. Nd2 Nf6 19. Nxf6+ Bxf6 20. Nc4 d5 $11) 14. Qd2 (14. Nd5 Bxd5 $11
15. Qxd5 $2 Nb4 $17 {In this line, we see the usefullness of ...Rc8. I
remembered that in my old Najdorf repertoire, I had ...Rc8 before ...Ne8.}) (14.
Nb5 Nf6 $5 $11) 14... a6 15. Bf4 Nde5 16. Rad1 h6 17. Nd5 Bg5 18. Bxg5 Qxg5 $11
{Nimmy, A (2118)-Padmini, R (2331) IND-ch (Women) 41st 2014 (11) 0-1}) 13. Nd5 {
This seems to be the only move that tries to take advantage of the missing ...
a7-a6.} (13. Qe1 Ne8 $11 14. Rf1 Bh4 15. Qd2 Bf6 16. Rad1 Be5 $11) 13... Ne5 $5
{With the b6-square defended, Black does not have to hurry to take on d5.} ({
The point is that after} 13... Bxd5 14. exd5 Ne5 15. Rb4 {, both black
queenside pawns are hanging. With the pawn on a6, Black could defend with ...
Qc7, but here this runs into Bxa7. Therefore, he has to weaken his queenside
with} b6 16. a4 Qc7 17. c3 $14 {with consistent pressure.}) (13... Nd7 14.
Nxe7+ Qxe7 {is also playable. Despite White's bishops' pair, Black's position
remains very solid, while the pawn on e4 is a bit vulnerable. After allowing
his bishop to be exchanged, Black could also consolidate with ...f7-f6 if
needed.}) 14. Nxe7+ (14. c3 Ng6 15. Nxf6+ {Keeping the pawn on e4.} Bxf6 $11)
14... Qxe7 {Black's superior development compensates for White's bishops' pair.
In fact, White is exposed to both ...d6-d5, after which his rook and
the dark-squared bishop would be hanging, and ...Ng6, winning the e4-pawn.} 15. Bd4
(15. c3 Ng6 16. Rf1 Nxe4 $15) (15. Nd2 d5 $15) (15. Bxa7 Qc7 (15... Ng6 16. Rf1
Nxe4 $13) 16. Bd4 (16. c3 $2 b6 $19) 16... Qxc2 $11) 15... g5 {Why not? A pawn
is a pawn.} (15... a6 $5 16. Nd2 Nfd7 17. Nf1 Qg5 18. Be3 Nf6 19. Qxd6 Ng6 $11
{The hanging pawns on c2 and e4 and WHite's lack of coordination yield Black
good play.}) 16. Rf1 Nxe4 {and a central knight is a central knight. White
should have compensation, but not more.} 17. Bxa7 f5 {This already looks
active for Black.} *

