1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Be2 Nf6 7. O-O Be7 8.
Be3 O-O 9. f4 e5 10. Nb3 exf4 11. Rxf4 Be6 12. Nd5 {This move ends once and
for all Black's possible dreams of opening the centre with ...d6-d5. Both here
and in the Najdorf, it is the most popular continuation.} Bxd5 ({The same
reaction as in a similar position in the previous line (12.Kh1 Rc8 13.Nd5) is
entirely possible. It was played three times by Rainer Knaak, a specialist in
this line in his best years. He lost all three games, but not because of the
positions he got out of the opening.} 12... Ne5 13. Nxe7+ Qxe7 14. Bd3 (14. Nd2
d5 $15 15. Bd4 {Van der Wiel,J (2465)-Knaak,R (2535) Chigorin Memorial-14 1980
(9) 1-0 The only way of staying in the game.} Qd6 $1 {Black should maintain
his centralised position.} 16. exd5 Nc6 $1 17. Rxf6 Nxd4 18. Rf2 Bxd5 $15) (14.
Bd4 {The same as in the similar line mentioned before, Black could win a pawn
with ...g7-g5 or keep the structure as it is. Knaak chose the latter.} Nfd7 15.
Nd2 Rac8 16. b3 Nc6 17. Bb2 Qg5 18. Rf3 Qc5+ 19. Kh1 Nce5 20. Rc3 Qf2 $13 {
Burchardt,B-Knaak,R Meissen Junior-20 1975 (1) 1-0}) 14... Nfg4 (14... Ng6 {
introduces another straightforward line.} 15. Rf1 Bxb3 16. axb3 d5 17. Rxa7
Rxa7 18. Bxa7 dxe4 19. Be2 Rd8 20. Qc1 Nd5 21. c4 b6 22. cxd5 Qxa7 $11) 15. Bd2
Qc7 (15... Nxd3 16. cxd3 Ne5 $11 {If White defends the pawn with the queen, ...
d6-d5 equlises.} 17. Bc3 $6 {prevents that, but runs into} Qg5 18. Rf2 Qe3 $15)
16. Bc3 g5 (16... Bxb3 {hoping to deliver a deadly check on c5 or b6 next,
runs into} 17. Rxg4 $1 $11 Nxg4 $2 18. Qxg4 f5 19. exf5 Bd5 20. f6 $18) 17.
Bxe5 {White decides to change the course of the game.} ({In the event of} 17.
Rf1 {WHite can meet 17...Bxb3 with 18.Bxe5=, but} d5 $1 {putting the h2-square
and the white king in danger is more interesting.} 18. Qd2 h6 19. g3 Rad8 20.
Nd4 dxe4 21. Bxe4 Bd5 22. Rae1 Bxe4 23. Rxe4 f5 24. Ree1 {Black has certain
pressure after, say,} Qb6 {but White is well regrouped and should maintain 
equality. For instance:} 25. h3 {The only move since Black threatened ...f5-f4,
when the pawn would not be edible due to ...Nf3+ in the end.} Nc4 26. Qd1 {
Oagain the only move. The queen needs to defend d4 and stay safe.} Nge5 $5 27.
Kh2 Rd5 28. Re2 f4 29. gxf4 gxf4 $13) 17... gxf4 (17... Nxe5 $11) 18. Bc3 Qe7 (
18... Qd8 $1 {is better.} 19. Qd2 $6 Bxb3 20. axb3 Qb6+ $19) (18... Bxb3 $2 19.
Qxg4#) 19. Qf3 (19. Qd2 $44) 19... Qg5 20. Rf1 Ne5 21. Qxf4 Qxf4 22. Rxf4 Rfc8
23. Be2 a5 (23... Rxc3 24. bxc3 Rc8 $15) 24. a3 Bxb3 25. cxb3 Rc5 (25... Rxc3
26. bxc3 a4 27. b4 Rc8 28. c4 Nxc4 $11) 26. Rf6 $44 {Dolmatov,S (2545)-Knaak,R
(2495) Match/Club Leipzig SG-Moscow GU 1981 (2.2) 1-0 The game featured a
fierce fight and deserves serious examination, in order to understand both
sides' ideas.}) 13. exd5 Ne5 {The similar Najdorf position has by far more
practical material than the current one, but the evaluation is the same: Black
is doing fine. His key piece is the e5-knight and the bishop is also supposed
to play a part on the dark squares. White has more space in the centre and
certain queenside pressure. His main hope is to carry out c4-c5 under
favourable circumstances.} 14. Rb4 (14. c4 Nfd7 15. Rf2 Bg5 16. Bxg5 Qxg5 17.
Qd4 b6 18. Nd2 f5 19. Raf1 g6 20. Bd1 Nc5 21. Bc2 a5 22. b3 Rfe8 $15 {
Praggnanandhaa, R (2447)-Andreikin, D (2734) Reykjavik op 2017 (10) 0-1 Play is
rather one-sided.}) (14. a4 Nfd7 15. Rb4 Qc7 {transposes below.}) ({Completing
the development with} 14. Qd2 Nfd7 15. Rff1 {is an important alternative. With
his whole army displayed harmoniously, White intends to think of concrete
action later.} Nb6 {STarting queenside operations before White creates his own
threats.} (15... Re8 16. Kh1 a6 17. Na5 {Lutz, C (2590)-Bacrot, E (2545)
Pamplona 9798 8th 1997 (6) 1-0} Qc7 18. c4 b6 19. Nc6 Nxc6 20. dxc6 Ne5 21. Bd4
Qxc6 22. Qf4 Rf8 $11 {White does have compensation for the pawn, but not more
than that.}) 16. Na5 Qc7 17. b3 Rae8 $5 $146 {The start of a harmonious and
effective regrouping.} (17... Rfe8 18. c4 Bf8 {is too passive.} 19. Rac1 Rad8
20. b4 $16 {Janosevic,D (2360)-Vogt,L (2485) Opatija op 1984 (7) 0-1}) 18. c4
Bd8 (18... Nbd7 19. Rac1 b6 20. Nc6 Nxc6 21. dxc6 Qxc6 22. Bf3 Qc7 $11) 19.
Rac1 (19. c5 Nxd5 20. Qxd5 Qxa5 21. Qxd6 Nc6 {White's bishops are hanging.} 22.
Bd2 Qa3 {[%csl Ge2][%cal Gd8e7]} 23. Bc1 Qb4 $5 {Avoiding an immediate draw by
repetition.} 24. Bd2 Be7 25. Bxb4 Bxd6 26. cxd6 Rxe2 $13) 19... Nxd5 20. cxd5 (
20. Qxd5 Qxa5 21. Qxa5 Bxa5 $17 22. Bxa7 $2 Nc6) 20... Qxa5 21. Qxa5 Bxa5 22.
Bxa7 Re7 23. Bd4 g6 24. Rc2 f5 $11) 14... Qc7 15. a4 Nfd7 16. a5 (16. Nd4 g6
17. Nb5 {takes advantage of the fact that Black had not played ...a7-a6, but
fails to cause major problems.} Qa5 18. c3 a6 19. Na3 Qc7 20. a5 Rfe8 21. Kh1
Bf8 22. Bg1 Nc5 (22... Re7 23. Nc4 Rae8 $15) 23. Nc4 Bg7 24. Nb6 Rad8 25. Rf4
f5 26. Rf1 Ne4 $15 {Duda,J (2587)-Polgar,J (2685) HUN-POL m Budapest 2014 (6.3)
0-1}) 16... a6 {What can we do? We finally are a whole tempo down with respect
to the Najdorf. However, Black is well regrouped and has good play.} 17. c3
Rfe8 18. Nd4 g6 19. Qd2 Nc5 20. Nf3 Bf6 21. Nxe5 Bxe5 22. Bf3 Re7 23. Bg5 f6 (
23... Ree8 $11) 24. Bh4 Rae8 25. Qc2 Rf7 26. Rc4 Qb8 27. Bf2 (27. g4 b5 28.
axb6 Qxb6 29. Bf2 Qb5 30. Be2 Qb3 $11) 27... Nd7 (27... f5 28. Bxc5 dxc5 29. g3
Bd6 $15) 28. g4 Kg7 (28... Ref8 29. Be3 f5 $11 30. gxf5 Qe8 31. Qd2 Bg7 32. Re4
Ne5 33. Bg2 Rxf5 $11) 29. Rf1 Rfe7 30. Kh1 Rf7 31. Bg2 Qd8 32. b4 f5 33. gxf5
Rxf5 34. Bh4 Rxf1+ 35. Bxf1 Bf6 36. Bg3 Be5 37. Bh4 Bf6 {Honfi,K-Vogt,L (2495)
Baukombinat Leipzig 1982 (2) 1/2-1/2 Lothar Vogt used to be another specialist
of this line. He was a friend and an analyzing partner of Rainer Knaak for
many years. They both belonged to the Democratic German chess school, based on
fundamental concepts and principal lines.} *

