cause major troubles to the queen with ...Bh4.} 14. Nd5 Bh4 15. Qc3 Bxd5 16.
exd5 Rc8 $36) 13... Qc7 {The most natural move, but the alternatives are also
worth mentioning. None of them is without symbolic drawbacks, but all of them
are fine. On c7, the queen is exposed, as we will see.} (13... Qc8 {avoids the
problem, but gives up a pawn. True, after} 14. Bxe5 dxe5 15. Qxe5 Bd8 $44 {
Black will soon install the bishop on e5, with obvious compensation.}) ({
The drawback of} 13... Qb8 {is merely aesthetical. In fact, this move defends
e5 and avoids the mini-problem in the main line. The queen is not that passive,
as we can see in the following lines.} 14. Nd4 a6 15. Qb4 {Black has several
good moves here, for instance ...Qa7, reactivating the queen, ...b5, providing
her with more space or the straightforward} Nc6 16. Nxc6 bxc6 17. Qxb8 Rfxb8
18. Rab1 a5 $11) 14. Nd4 a6 (14... Bd7 15. Qb3 a6 16. Rad1 b5 $11) 15. Nxe6 Qc8
$1 (15... fxe6 16. Qb3 $14) 16. Qb4 (16. Nd5 Nxd5 17. Qxd5 Qxe6 18. Qxe6 fxe6
$11) 16... Nc6 17. Qb3 (17. Qb6 fxe6 18. Rad1 Nd7 19. Qb3 Nc5 20. Qa3 Ne5 $11)
17... fxe6 18. Rad1 b5 19. Bxd6 Nd4 $1 20. Rxd4 Bxd6 21. Kh1 Be5 $44) (12. Qe1
{is examined in Line 51.}) ({For} 12. Bf3 {see Line 52.}) 12... d5 {This is
played in the vast majority of the games. It leads to complete equality.} (
12... Rc8 {was played only once, but subjectively remains my favourite. It was
