{[%evp 0,38,28,45,47,45,52,45,42,28,28,45,104,69,59,59,47,48,68,47,48,33,40,3,
23,-9,11,-14,-8,14,13,5,5,5,5,27,45,57,57,57,57]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4
4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Be2 Nf6 7. O-O Be7 8. Be3 O-O 9. f4 e5 10. Nb3 exf4
11. Bxf4 Be6 12. Qe1 {This move prepares a harmonious regrouping based on Rad1
and Qg3.} d5 {Unlike in the line with 11.Rxf4, the pin along the d-file is not
dangerous, because of the possible check on b6. However, White's regrouping
remains consistent.} ({As usual, I would also consider the static plan, played
only once:} 12... Ne8 {In the Najdorf there are several games with it.} 13. Qg3
(13. Rd1 Rc8 14. Kh1 Bf6 15. Qg3 a6 16. Bxd6 Nxd6 17. Rxd6 Qe7 18. Nd5 Bxd5 19.
Rdxf6 Bxe4 20. c3 Rcd8 $11) (13. Nd5 Bg5 $11) 13... Bf6 (13... Bh4 14. Qe3 Bf6
$11) 14. Rad1 Be5 {This may be a bit premature. Now was a good moment to catch
up with the Najdorf setup.} (14... a6 15. Kh1 Rc8 $11) 15. Bxe5 Nxe5 16. Kh1 a6
{It is interesting to mention that we now reached a genuine Najdorf position.
In all the games reaching this position, White played f2-f4 with the bishop on
c1 and Black took on f4 at once, hence the missing tempo.} 17. Nd4 Nf6 18. Nf5
(18. Nf3 Nh5 $146 19. Qe1 Ng6 20. e5 Nhf4 21. exd6 Qb6 $44) 18... Bxf5 19. Rxf5
Qe7 (19... Re8 20. Rdf1 Re6 21. h3 Rc8 $11) 20. Rdf1 Nfd7 21. Nd5 Qd8 22. Qa3 {
Guimaraes,J-Cebalo,M (2510) Budva Zonal 1981 (15) 1/2-1/2} Nb6 23. Ne3 Qc7 $11)
