{[%evp 0,46,19,21,72,53,53,44,37,37,30,37,68,56,69,36,28,26,23,-26,-19,-12,-5,
-19,-13,-21,-18,-73,-69,-101,-95,-94,-77,-81,-23,-330,-253,-325,-363,-360,-400,
-379,-395,-390,-255,-541,-543,-597,-394]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4
Nc6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Bc4 {The Sozin Attack had its times of glory, starting with
the years when Fischer used it against all the traditional Sicilians (with the
exception of the Paulsen, of course) and continuing with Velimirovic'
successes with it. Fischer used to castle short, while Velimirovic preferred
the long cast;e. I remember that at some point, theory distinguished between
the Fischer-Sozin and the Velimirovic Attacks. The whole system can lead to
very entertaining play, but as active as White's plans may seem, it was
discovered that forced lines tend to petter out into equality. Moreover,
Black's play is many times easier to carry out. Suggestively, after coming
close to losing the fourth game of his match with Spassky in 1972, Fischer
never played the Sozin Attack again, switching to 1.c4 and 6.Bg5 in the
classical Sicilian. There are a few drawbacks making White vulnerable in the
Sozin Attack. In order to reach the stable b3-square, the bishop needs two
tempi, facing White with the risk of remaining a bit behind in development.
Moreover, the pawn on e4 and the entire long light diagonal lack one of their
natural defense. Sometimes, the g2-square may be hard to defend if White
breaks in the centre with e4-e5.} (6. Be3 Nf6 7. Bc4 {is another possible move
order, transposing to 7.Be3 below.}) 6... Nf6 7. Bb3 {Sooner or later, the
bishop would have to retreat, but move order can make a difference.} ({Keeping
it on c4 for too long with, say,} 7. O-O Be7 8. Be3 O-O 9. f4 $6 {typically
runs into} (9. Bb3 {transposes to any of the Sozin lines examined here, with
the exception of the Velimirovic Attack, of course.}) 9... d5 $1 {After this
well-timed break, f2-f4 is only a weakening move, leading to a very pleasant
version for Black of the Isolano.} 10. exd5 (10. Bd3 Bc5 $1 $17 11. Nf5 $2 Qb6
$19) (10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. exd5 exd5 $17) 10... exd5 11. Be2 (11. Bb3 Ng4 $17)
11... Re8 12. Bf2 (12. Kh1 Ba3 $17 13. Bc1 $6 Bc5 14. Nb3 Bb6 $19) 12... Bd6
13. f5 (13. Qd2 {Kinzel,A-Hartston,W Clare Benedict Cup-16 1969 (4) 0-1} Bb4
$15) 13... Ne4 (13... Be5 14. Bf3 a6 15. h3 Qd6 $17) 14. Nxe4 {Jashnev, D (2197)
-Vitiugov,N (2355) RUS-ch U16 Cherepovets 2001 0-1} Nxd4 15. Bxd4 (15. Qxd4
Rxe4 16. Qd2 Bf4 17. Qd1 Bxf5 $17) 15... Rxe4 16. Bf2 (16. c3 Qh4 17. h3 Qg3
$17) 16... Rf4 $17) (7. Be3 {is examined in Lines 55 to 57.}) 7... Be7 8. O-O
O-O 9. f4 {Typical for all kinds of systems, in the Sozin Attack, this move
speaks of White's intention to turn his pet bishop into an active piece with
f4-f5. Played at this moment, with the development incomplete yet, it allows
Black to deviate from the main lines, reaching very pleasant play.} ({In the
event of} 9. Be3 {we can stick to our main plan with} Bd7 ({One of the most
popular lines used to be} 9... a6 10. f4 Nxd4 11. Bxd4 b5 12. e5 dxe5 13. fxe5
Nd7 14. Ne4 Bb7 15. Nd6 Bxd6 16. exd6 {, where White surely maintains certain
pressure.}) 10. f4 {It is hard to imagine anything else useful. We have
transposed to Lines 57.}) (9. Kh1 {is examined in Line 54.}) 9... Nxd4 $1 (9...
a6 10. Be3 {takes us back into a line we avoid.}) 10. Qxd4 b6 $1 {Unlike in
the classical system, this apparently modest move aims at more than just
completing the development as quickly as possible with ...Bb7 (or ...Ba6). The
main threat is ...d6-d5 followed by ...Bc5. As strange as it may seem, Black's
position is preferable already.} 11. Kh1 {The most popular answer.} ({In the
event of} 11. Qd3 {the untested} a5 $5 $146 {seems to face White with serious
problems. The immediate threat is ...Ba6.} (11... Nd7 $11 {is the most popular
continuation, yielding Black normal play after ...Nc5.}) (11... d5 {is a bit
premature since after} 12. exd5 exd5 13. Nxd5 Bc5+ {White has} 14. Be3 $14 {
Compare with the similar line below, with the insertion of ...a7-a5 and a2-a4.}
) 12. Rd1 {offers Black a relatively wide choice.} ({The apparently solid} 12.
a4 {runs into} d5 $1 13. exd5 exd5 14. Nxd5 Bc5+ 15. Kh1 (15. Be3 $2 {does not
work here due to} Ba6 $1 16. c4 Qxd5 $5 $19) 15... Re8 {Black has a
considerable advance in development.} 16. Bd2 Ba6 17. Nxf6+ Qxf6 18. Bc4 Bxc4
19. Qxc4 Qxb2 $17) (12. Qf3 Bb7 13. a4 d5 14. e5 Ne4 $15) 12... Bb7 {is
probably the best.} (12... Ba6 13. Qf3 Bb7 14. a4 Rc8 $132) (12... b5 $5 13. a4
$1 (13. Qxb5 $2 a4 14. Bxa4 Ba6 15. Qc6 Ng4 16. h3 Qb8 17. hxg4 Rc8 18. Qd7 Ra7
$17) (13. Nxb5 $2 a4 14. Bc4 d5 15. exd5 exd5 16. Bxd5 Nxd5 17. Qxd5 Qb6+ $19 {
folowed by ...Bg4 and ...Rad8.}) 13... b4 14. Nb5 Bb7 15. Nxd6 Bxd6 16. Qxd6
Bxe4 17. Be3 Qxd6 18. Rxd6 Rfc8 19. Rc1 Bd5 $11) 13. h3 {Preparing Be3} (13. a4
d5 $15 14. exd5 Ng4 $17) (13. Be3 Ng4 $15) 13... b5 14. Qxb5 Bxe4 15. Nxe4 Nxe4
16. Qe2 d5 17. c4 Bc5+ 18. Kh2 (18. Be3 d4 19. Bc2 f5 20. Kh2 e5 $17 21. fxe5
$2 {Clearing the fourth rank to Black's favour.} Qh4 $19 22. Bxe4 Qxe4) 18...
Qh4 19. Qf3 a4 20. Bc2 Qf2 21. Bxe4 (21. Qxf2 Nxf2 22. Rd2 dxc4 $15) 21... dxe4
22. Qxe4 (22. Qxf2 Bxf2 23. Rd2 Bb6 24. Re2 f5 $15) 22... Rad8 23. Rh1 {
Sadly the only move.} (23. Re1 Rd3) 23... h5 $17) 11... Ba6 {It is not easy to
find a good square for the rook.} 12. Rf3 {Played in the vast majority of
games, but creating a feeling of lack of coordination.} (12. Re1 Ng4 13. Be3 {
Sad necessity.} (13. h3 $2 d5 $1 14. hxg4 Bc5 $19 {threatening ...Qh4, either
with a mate or winning the rook on e1.}) 13... Bh4 14. Red1 Bf6 15. Qd2 Rc8 16.
Bg1 {Ankerst,M (2155)-Grabics,M (2145) EU-chT (Women) 1st 1992 (3) 0-1} Bxc3
17. bxc3 Bb7 18. Qe1 Qc7 19. Qg3 Nf6 20. Bd4 Kh8 21. Re1 Rg8 22. Qf3 e5 23. Bf2
Qc6 $15) (12. Bc4 Bxc4 13. Qxc4 d5 14. exd5 exd5 15. Qd3 Bc5 $5 $146) 12... d5
13. e5 (13. exd5 Bc5 14. Qd1 exd5 {yields Black a decisive advance in
development. Among others, White's back rank is weak.} 15. Nxd5 (15. f5 d4 16.
Ne2 Re8 17. Ng3 h6 18. Bf4 Qd7 19. h3 Rad8 $19 {and White can barely find
moves.}) 15... Nxd5 16. Qxd5 {Civin,T (2360)-Kisimenko,N (2000) IECG CM.1999.0.
00091 1/2-1/2} (16. Bxd5 Re8 $19) 16... Bb7 $1 17. Qxd8 Raxd8 18. Rf1 Rfe8 {
Tragically, White cannot defend his pawn on g2.} 19. Bc4 Rd6 20. f5 Rd4 21. Bd3
Rg4 $19) 13... Ne4 14. f5 (14. Be3 Bc5 15. Qd1 Bxe3 16. Nxe4 Bxf4 17. Rxf4 dxe4
18. Rxe4 Bb7 $15) (14. Nxe4 $2 dxe4 $19 {leaves White hanging.}) (14. Qd1 Bc5
15. Be3 Rc8 $15) 14... Bc5 15. Qa4 {Gaining a tempo, but exposing the queen.} (
15. Qd1 Qh4 $5 16. Nxe4 Qxe4 17. Rg3 g6 18. Bh6 Qxf5 19. Bxf8 Rxf8 20. Qe1 (20.
Qd2 Qxe5 $19) 20... Bf2 $19) 15... Bb7 16. f6 a6 $1 {Trapping the queen soon.}
17. Bg5 g6 18. Be3 b5 19. Nxb5 axb5 20. Qxb5 Ba6 21. Qc6 Qc8 22. Bxd5 exd5 23.
