Qb8 9. a4 (9. Bf4 Ne5 10. Bb3 a6 11. Nd4 Be7 12. Qd2 b5 $17 {Godlewski,A (2195)
-Kowalska,E (2015) Milanowek-ch 1998 0-1}) 9... a6 10. Nd4 Be7 11. O-O O-O 12.
f4 b5 13. axb5 Nxd4 14. Bxd4 axb5 15. Rxa8 Qxa8 16. Bd3 Bc6 17. e5 dxe5 18.
fxe5 Nd7 19. Qe2 b4 20. Ne4 Bxe4 21. Bxe4 Qa5 $11) ({In the event of} 8. Bb3 {
We can stay within our repertoire with} Nxd4 $1 (8... a6 {allows White to
switch to an improved version of the Fischer system with} 9. f4 $14) (8... Be7
{is best met with} 9. Qe2 $1 $14 {followed by 0-0-0, once again taking us out
of the repertoire.,}) 9. Qxd4 (9. Bxd4 b5 $11) 9... Be7 10. O-O-O (10. O-O O-O
11. f4 {transposes to a variation from Line 57.}) (10. g4 O-O 11. Rg1 {Before
advancing his g-pawn further, White needs to prevent ...Ng4.} b5 12. g5 {
De Vreugt,D (2452)-Bosboom,M (2439) Corus-B Wijk aan Zee 2001 (5) 1-0} Nh5 13.
O-O-O a5 14. a3 g6 15. f4 b4 16. axb4 axb4 17. Qxb4 Re8) 10... O-O 11. f4 b5 (
11... Bc6 12. Kb1 {Istratescu,A (2540)-Hracek,Z (2615) Krynica zt 1998 (6) 0-1}
Ng4 13. Bg1 b5 $132) 12. e5 Ng4 13. exd6 (13. Bg1 a5) 13... Bf6 14. Qd2 Nxe3
15. Qxe3 a5 16. a3 Bc6 $44) (8. O-O {is examined in Lines 56 and 57.}) 8... a6
9. O-O-O (9. O-O {is not tricky enough. True, Black has been talked into
playing ...a7-a6 in the Fischer system, but there are some concrete details
making his position entirely viable.} b5 10. Bb3 Be7 11. f4 {Due to the fact
that WHite, too, has made an early commitment, Black gets immediate
counterplay with} Nxd4 12. Bxd4 b4 13. Nd1 Bb5 {In Line 57, the bishop moves
