{[%evp 0,48,26,22,32,32,57,38,38,35,36,42,51,41,28,26,45,44,34,3,8,8,33,1,33,
28,70,29,54,-1,40,21,34,23,44,-14,-5,7,7,-20,-26,-26,-30,-30,-36,-36,-31,-38,
-39,-46,-49]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 d6 6. g3 {
Against all the "traditional Sicilians", this is a solid but not dangerous
system. White intends to over-defend e4 and increase his control over d5. In
many cases, White later switches to some sort of a delayed Keres attack with ..
.g3-g4. The main drawback of this system is that it weakens the control over
the f1-a6 diagonal, making Black's queenside counterplay easier to carry out,
irrespective of the fact whether White plays a2-a4 or not. The c4-square is
also easier to invade, of course, and the black bishop may later occupy the
uncontrolled diagonal.} Nf6 7. Bg2 Bd7 {With the knight on c6 already, Black
has to delay the advance of his queenside pawns. It is useful to over-defend
the c6-knight, in order to neutralize the enemy bishop.s pressure.} (7... Be7 {
may run into} 8. Nxc6 bxc6 9. e5 {, an operation available later, too, if
instead of ...Bd7 Black plays, say, ...a7-a6.}) 8. O-O (8. Ndb5 {fails to
cause Black to lose coordination.} Qb8 9. Bf4 (9. Bg5 a6 10. Bxf6 {may be
answered with} axb5 $1 11. Bg5 b4 12. Ne2 h6 13. Be3 Be7 {Ognerubova, A (1928)
-Avdeeva, V (2122) Voronezh City-ch (Women) 2007 (9) 0-1}) 9... Ne5 10. a4 (10.
Bg5 a6 11. Bxf6 {runs into the familiar} axb5 12. Bg5 h6 13. Bc1 Qc7 14. O-O
Be7 15. Ne2 O-O 16. c3 Bf6 17. f4 Nc4 18. b3 {Rakhmatullaev,A (2182)-Alekseev,
E (2626) Ismagambetov Memorial 1st blitz 2020 (4) 1-0} Na3 19. Bb2 b4 $15) (10.
O-O a6 11. Nd4 b5 $15 {only leads to time loss for White.}) 10... a6 11. Nd4
Be7 12. O-O O-O 13. Qe2 Qc7 14. Rfd1 Rac8 15. h3 {Kholmov,R (2458)-Kharitonov,
A (2562) RUS-Cup03 Geller Memorial 1999 (8) 1/2-1/2} Rfe8 {With the queen on
e2, this is a natural square for the rook. Black may continue with ...Bf8,
when ...d6-d5 becomes an issue.} 16. Kh2 Nc4 17. Bc1 Bf8 18. b3 Ne5 19. Bb2 h5
20. Nf3 Ng6 $15 {White obviously lost his coordination.}) 8... Be7 ({Black
does not need to define his queenside intentions with} 8... a6 {, even though
the move should be playable.}) 9. Re1 {For unknown reasons, the plan based on
this and the next move is quite popular.} ({The plan} 9. Ndb5 Qb8 10. Bg5 {
is once again inoffensive, but for other reasons than before..} O-O $1 (10...
a6 $6 {allows} 11. Bxf6 {, since the bishop on e7 is exposed. After} gxf6 12.
Nd4 {White can claim having achieved a little something.}) 11. Bxf6 {Otherwise
...a7-a6.} Bxf6 $1 12. Qxd6 (12. Nxd6 $2 Rd8 13. Nc4 b5 14. Ne3 b4 $17 {
with very strong initiative.}) 12... Rd8 {The strong bishop on f6 and the
misplaced white knight on b5 yields Black excellent compensation for the pawn.
} 13. Rfd1 (13. a4 a6 14. Qxb8 Raxb8 15. Nd6 Nd4 $44 16. Nxb7 $2 Rxb7 17. e5
Rxb2 18. exf6 gxf6 19. Rfd1 e5 20. Nd5 {Wedberg,T (2425)-Sznapik,A (2405)
Eksjo-08 grupp A 1980 (4) 1/2-1/2} Kg7 $15) (13. Qxb8 Raxb8 14. f4 {De Armas
Perez,A (2055)-Erenska Barlo,H (2240) Olympiad Women-27 1986 (11) 1/2-1/2} Nd4
15. Nxd4 Bxd4+ 16. Kh1 Bxc3 17. bxc3 Rdc8 18. Rfd1 Ba4 19. Rd4 Bxc2 20. c4 Rc5
21. Rc1 Ba4 22. e5 Kf8 23. Kg1 Be8 $15 {The position is close to equal, but
only Black can hope to fight for an advantage, due to the weak pawns on a2 and
c4.}) 13... a6 14. Qxb8 (14. Na3 Qa7 $1 15. Qd2 Ne5 16. Ne2 b5 17. c3 b4 $17)
14... Raxb8 15. Nd6 b5 16. a3 Nd4 17. f4 (17. Rd2 Bc6 18. e5 Bxe5 19. Re1 Rxd6
20. Rxe5 Nf3+ 21. Bxf3 Rxd2 22. Bxc6 Rxc2 $15 23. Re2 $2 Rxe2 24. Nxe2 b4 $19
25. a4 Rd8 {and the bg4-pawn is likely to decide the game.}) 17... Nxc2 18.
Rac1 (18. e5 $2 Nxa1 19. exf6 Be8 20. Nce4 Nb3 $19 {Raja,H (2432)-Andreikin,D 
(2725) PRO League Stage rapid 2019 (3) 1/2-1/2}) 18... Bd4+ 19. Kh1 Bxc3 $11
20. Rxc2 (20. bxc3 Ne3 21. Rd2 Bc6 22. Re1 Nxg2 23. Kxg2 Bd5 24. exd5 Rxd6 $15
{Black has the more pleasant side of an almost equal ending.}) 20... b4 21. b3
(21. bxc3 Ba4 22. axb4 Bxc2 23. Rd2 Rbc8 24. c4 Rb8 $17) 21... a5 $15) ({
It is too early to start the delayed Keres Attack with} 9. Nxc6 Bxc6 10. g4 a6
11. g5 Nd7 12. f4 h6 13. h4 hxg5 14. hxg5 Qb6+ $17) (9. Be3 {is examined in
Lines 59 to 61.}) 9... O-O 10. Nxc6 Bxc6 {Since Black sometimes plays ...Nxd4
followed by ...Bc6, it means that here White is just wasting time to reach a
similar position.} 11. a4 Qd7 $5 {Black does not intend to waste time on ...
a7-a6.} (11... a6 {is possible, with similar play as in later lines.}) (11...
Qc7 {[%cal Gb7b6] is playable, too, but less restrictive than the main move.}
12. Nb5 Bxb5 $146 13. axb5 a6 14. bxa6 Rxa6 15. Rxa6 bxa6 16. Re3 Nd7 17. Rc3
Qb6 18. b3 a5 $132) 12. Be3 b6 {The point. Black prepares ...Qb7.} 13. a5 (13.
Bf4 Rfd8 14. Qe2 a6 15. Rad1 Qb7 16. h3 b5 17. axb5 axb5 18. b4 (18. Nd5 exd5
19. exd5 Nxd5 20. Bxd5 Bxd5 21. Qxe7 Qc6 $5 $36) 18... d5 $11 {Taulbut,S (2390)
-Hartston,W (2485) Christmas Congress 1978/79-54 Premier (7) 1/2-1/2}) (13. e5
Ne8 14. Bf4 Rd8 15. Ne4 Qb7 16. exd6 Nxd6 17. Bxd6 Bxd6 18. Nxd6 Qc7 $11) 13...
bxa5 $5 {The simplest.} (13... b5 14. e5 {yielded White some light initiative,
which vanished soon, though.} Ne8 15. Ne4 Qc7 16. exd6 Nxd6 17. Bf4 Rad8 18.
Qh5 Bd5 19. Be5 Qc6 20. Qg4 {Barczay,L (2450)-Tompa,J (2440) Zamardi GM+ 1980
1/2-1/2} Nf5 $17) 14. Rxa5 Rfc8 15. Bd4 Bd8 16. Ra6 (16. Ra2 Qb7 $11) 16... Bb7
(16... Qb7 17. Rxc6 Rxc6 18. e5 dxe5 19. Bxe5 Rac8) 17. Rxa7 (17. Ra2 a5 $11)
17... Rxa7 18. Bxa7 Ba5 19. Qd3 Bxc3 20. bxc3 Bxe4 21. Bxe4 Qxa7 22. Qxd6 Nxe4
23. Rxe4 Qa1+ 24. Kg2 Qxc3 $11 *

