Kxg2 Qb7+ 20. Kg3 (20. Kg1 Bc5 $5 $15) 20... Bc7 $1 $11 21. Qxd7 $2 Rad8 $19)
11... Qc7 12. Nde2 {Still preparing for the attack. This is an important
difference with respect to the classical system (6.Be2 followed by 0-0), where
the knight mainly retreats to b3. White maintains the possibility of expelling
a black knight from c4 with b2-b3, while also overdefending the knight on c3
for that purpose.} (12. g4 {allows Black to clear the d7-square for his knight
just in time.} Nxd4 13. Qxd4 (13. Bxd4 Bc6 14. g5 Nd7 15. Qg4 b5 16. f4 b4 17.
Ne2 e5 18. Be3 exf4 19. Nxf4 Ne5 20. Qg3 {Zatonskih,A (2320)-Baciu,A (2185)
Bucharest Fest IM (Women) 1998 1-0} Qb7 21. Nd5 Bxd5 22. exd5 Rac8 23. Rf2 a5
24. Kh1 Bd8 $15) 13... Bc6 14. g5 Nd7 (14... Nh5 $5 15. Bf3 g6 16. Bxh5 gxh5
17. f4 f5 $13) 15. f4 (15. Nd5 Bxd5 16. exd5 e5 $11) 15... e5 16. Qd2 exf4 17.
Bxf4 Rac8 18. Ne2 {Benkirat, R-Kaabi, M (2344) Kheireddine Ameyar Memorial 2011 
(3) 1/2-1/2} b5 19. axb5 Bxb5 20. Rf2 Qxc2 21. Qxc2 Rxc2 22. Nd4 Rxf2 23. Kxf2
f6 24. g6 hxg6 25. Nxb5 axb5 26. Ra7 Rd8 27. Bd2 d5 28. Rb7 Bc5+ 29. Ke2 dxe4
30. Ba5 Ra8 31. b4 Ne5 $13) (12. Qe2 {is equivalent to giving up the initial
plans and switching to a setup examined later.}) 12... Rab8 13. g4 Bc8 {This is
the most popular reaction, similar to the same bishop retreat in one of the
main Scheweningen lines, mentioned in Line 44, even though with our move order
we avoid it.} ({However,} 13... h6 {may offer better chances to cast some
doubt over White's plan.} 14. f4 {Waitzkin,J (2435)-Polgar,S (2500) San
Francisco 1995 (6) 1/2-1/2} b5 15. axb5 axb5 $15 16. g5 hxg5 17. fxg5 Nh7 18.
h4 b4 19. Na4 Ne5 20. Nf4 Bb5 21. Rf2 Ra8 22. b3 Qc6 $17) 14. g5 (14. f4 b5 15.
axb5 axb5 16. g5 Nd7 {transposes below.}) (14. Qd2 {is a bit committal.} b5 15.
axb5 axb5 16. Ng3 b4 17. Nce2 d5 $5 (17... Bb7 18. g5 Nd7 19. f4 Rfe8 20. f5
Bf8 21. Nf4 Nce5 22. b3 Nc5 23. Rad1 g6 $5 $11 {White already has to count
with ...exf5.}) 18. g5 (18. exd5 Nxd5 19. Bxd5 exd5 20. Qxd5 Bd6 21. Rfd1 Be5
$44) 18... Nxe4 19. Nxe4 dxe4 20. Bxe4 Rd8 21. Qc1 {Sanchez Alarcon,J (2248)
-Brock, F (2145) CHI-ch  Santiago de Chile 2002 (9) 1/2-1/2} Bb7 $17) 14... Nd7
15. f4 b5 16. axb5 axb5 17. Ng3 (17. Qd3 $2 {runs into} Nc5 18. Bxc5 dxc5 19.
Nxb5 c4 (19... Qb6 20. c4 Ba6 21. Nec3 Bxb5 22. Nxb5 Rfd8 23. Qa3 Nd4 24. Nxd4
Rxd4 $15) 20. Qxc4 Qb6+ 21. Nbd4 Bc5 (21... Nxd4 22. Nxd4 e5 23. fxe5 Be6 24.
Qd3 Qxb2 25. h4 Rfd8 26. c3 Rbc8 $44 {Ponkratov,P (2604)-Belous,V (2557) RUS
GP rap Khanty-Mansiysk rapid 2015 (9) 1/2-1/2}) 22. c3 (22. Rfd1 $2 {leads to
a worse version of the main line, because it exposes the rook.} Rd8 23. c3 Na5
24. Rxa5 Qxa5 25. b4 Qa4 $1 $17) 22... Na5 {[%cal Gc8a6,Ga5b3]} 23. Rxa5 (23.
Qd3 Ba6 24. Qe3 Nc4 25. Qf2 Nxb2 $15) (23. Qa4 Nb3 24. Rad1 Ba6 25. Rfe1 Bxe2
26. Rxe2 Bxd4+ 27. cxd4 Ra8 28. Qc4 Rfc8 29. Qd3 Nc1 $17) 23... Qxa5 24. b4
Bxd4+ 25. Nxd4 Qa3 $13) 17... b4 18. Nce2 Re8 19. Qe1 (19. b3 Bf8 20. Qe1 d5
$11) 19... Bf8 (19... b3 $15 20. c3 $6 Na5 $17) 20. Qf2 Bb7 21. f5 exf5 (21...
Nce5 22. Nf4 Rbc8 23. Ra7 Nc5 24. b3 g6 $5 $11 {/=/+}) 22. Nxf5 (22. exf5 d5
23. Kh1 Rbc8 24. Rad1 Nce5 $36) (22. Nf4 Nd8 23. exf5 Bxg2 24. Kxg2 Rc8 25.
Rac1 Qb7+ 26. Kh2 Nc5 27. g6 Ne4 28. Qg2 Nxg3 29. Qxg3 Qe4 30. gxf7+ Nxf7 31.
