{[%evp 0,36,18,18,30,36,39,34,34,34,34,60,64,36,36,25,25,36,36,8,32,19,36,32,
32,39,34,52,32,34,34,35,35,5,5,1,-7,1,1]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4
Nc6 5. Nc3 d6 6. g3 Nf6 7. Bg2 Bd7 8. O-O Be7 9. Be3 O-O 10. Qe2 {The most
harmonious way of completing the development, once again not available in the
classical system.} a6 11. a4 (11. Nxc6 Bxc6 12. a4 Qc7 {transposes below.}) (
11. Rad1 {is examined in Line 61.}) 11... Qc7 12. Nxc6 {The limits of the
fianchetto systems are revealed by the fact that this is the most popular and,
apparently, only constructive move.} (12. Rad1 Rab8 $5 13. f4 $6 Nxd4 14. Bxd4
e5 15. Be3 b5 16. axb5 axb5 17. Rfe1 Bg4 18. Bf3 Bxf3 19. Qxf3 b4 20. fxe5 dxe5
21. Nd5 Nxd5 22. Rxd5 Qxc2 $17 {Andriasian, Z (2546)-Van Wely, L (2680)
Hoogeveen Essent Crown 11th 2007 (3) 0-1}) (12. Nb3 Ne5 {leaves the c4-square
in Black's hands.} 13. a5 (13. Rad1 Nc4 14. Bc1 b5 15. axb5 axb5 16. e5 dxe5
17. Bxa8 Rxa8 18. Nd2 Nxd2 19. Rxd2 b4 20. Ne4 {Gdanski,J (2430)-Rotstein,A 
